<DOCNO> AP890906-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Barco     09-06 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barco,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Colombian President Who Doesn't Back Down From Drug Traffickers
^Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Colombia-Fair Fight?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getting tough with deadly drug gangs may
be a macho job in a macho land, but the man who's doing it is 69,
with white hair and an unsteady voice, and has been depicted in
Colombian newspapers as a weak leader.
   Virgilio Barco, elected to a four-year term in 1986, looks more
like a university professor than the president of a violent nation.
   Polls have shown as many as 70 percent of Colombians disapprove
of his performance, but the number of serious problems he faces
simultaneously may be unprecedented for a president of this troubled
South American country.
   In addition to murderous drug traffickers, Barco has to deal with
an estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas, a foreign debt of $15
billion and declining prices for Colombia's gold, oil and coal.
   He is a quiet man who thinks, reads and studies history. He does
not smoke and drinks only an occasional glass of white wine at
official receptions.
   His only sport is golf, which he is not able to play often, and
his handicap is a state secret.
   Aides say the president rises at 5 a.m. and begins his day with a
briefing on what happened during the five or six hours he slept.
   Barco graduated from the Massachussetts Institute of Technology,
is married to Carolina Isackson of York, Pa., and served as
ambassador to Washington. He became so Americanized and made so many
errors in Spanish grammar during his presidential campaign that the
cocktail circuit made him the butt of jokes.
   On Aug. 18, assassins hired by cocaine barons killed Sen. Luis
Carlos Galan at a rally. Galan was the leading presidential
candidate and an outspoken foe of the narcotics trade.
   If the drug lords had expected Barco to knuckle under, they were
wrong. In the toughest presidential speech Colombia's 30 million
people had heard in many years, he said the nation might face the
most bloodshed since a civil war four decades ago took 250,000 lives.
   He said he was sending police and soldiers to raid and confiscate
hundreds of luxurious villas, ranches and other property of drug
traffickers. His delivery may not have been forceful, but his
message is shaking the country from the high Andes to its vast
plains.
   In the most surprising announcement of all, Barco said he was
using emergency powers to extradite Colombians so those wanted on
drug charges in the United States could be tried there.
   The traffickers, who have said often they preferred tombs in
Colombia to jail cells in the United States, retaliated with a
rampage of terror, bombings and arson.
   What the outcome will be is not clear. Barco's term as president
has 11 months to run.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ControlledChoice     09-06 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Controlled Choice,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Controlled Choice' School Desegregation Plan Set To Begin in Seattle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in more than a decade, back to
school should mean back to the same school for most children under a
revamped, relaxed desegregation plan, officials say.
   Three years in the making, ``controlled choice'' replaces a
system blamed for the loss of hundreds and perhaps thousands of
middle-class students to private, parochial and suburban schools.
   ``Anybody can pick at the edges of this plan,'' said Mayor
Charles Royer. ``I think the (school) administration has done a good
job.''
   Under one key feature, virtually all the system's 43,000 students
have been told they can remain at the same school from year to year
until they advance to the next level _ from grade school to middle
school, for example.
   Since 1978, when the city became the largest in the nation to
adopt a mandatory desegregation plan without a court order, students
have been switched from one school to another an average of three
times in grade school and once each in middle and high schools to
maintain racial balance.
   White students comprise 46.6 percent of Seattle's public school
system, with non-whites _ predominately blacks, Asians and Hispanics
_ at 53.4 percent, said Pat Patterson, a spokeswoman for the school
system. However, the desegregation plan concerns only balance
between blacks and non-blacks, and Ms. Patterson did not know the
breakdown of the student population in those terms.
   Superintendent William Kendrick convened an advisory panel to
begin work on the new plan shortly after he was hired in 1986. He
said it should cut reliance on mandatory busing in half this year
and could end busing entirely in as little as three years, although
he is making no predictions at this point.
   ``We're into a transitional period,'' Kendrick said. ``My goal is
a totally voluntary program.''
   The plan covers the entire city, including some predominately
white North End neighborhoods that had previously been exempt. It
also include kindergartners for the first time.
   Under the new policy, parents can choose any grade school from a
cluster of at least a half-dozen that includes one in their
neighborhood. Exceptions are allowed for 4th-, 5th-, 7th- and
8th-graders to remain in their current schools and, in some cases,
for students to attend the same schools as brothers and sisters.
   Despite a rocky start, with assignments delayed by computer
problems and uncounted parents registering children in public and
private schools, the plan shows signs of success, Kendrick said.
   Of the 43,293 children registered by Monday, 90 percent got their
first choice of schools, Ms. Patterson said Tuesday. Classes start
Wednesday.
   But parents who didn't get their first choices for their children
voiced their displeasure.
   ``It's been a horrible two weeks. All we've asked is for them to
be assigned together,'' said Mary Potts, whose first-grade son's
school assignment is an hour's bus ride from the school her
third-grade daughter will attend.
   For others, like Rochelle Mastin, the outcome was better. ``I
can't believe it,'' said Mastin, who moved to Seattle a year ago and
feared her 7-year-old daughter's request would not be granted.
   ``We've got a number of parents now who are coming in and saying
they're coming back from the private schools,'' Kendrick said. He
said he had no precise number, but that 300 parents had expressed
that sentiment recently at one of three special parent information
centers.
   Only after fall enrollment figures are tallied next month will
there be any solid indication of how many students the public school
system regained, he said.
   Kendrick said half of the 21,000 students who relied on buses
last year would have done so regardless of desegregation, 30 percent
were taking advantage of optional and special programs and 20
percent were transported solely to achieve racial balance.
   Mandatory busing should be cut to 10 percent this year and still
lower after two years, the end of the ``grandfathering'' period for
school assignments, he said.
   Despite improvements in the desegregation program, opponents of
mandatory busing in any form are pushing Initiative 34, dubbed SOS,
for Save Our Schools.
   It would reserve 6 percent of the city's sales tax revenue _
about $4 million a year _ for ``magnet'' programs in schools with
less than 33 percent white enrollment, but only if forced busing
were discontinued. The city now provides no money for operation of
the schools.
   The City Council and School Board have sought court action to
keep the latest measure off the Nov. 7 general election ballot. A
ruling is expected in about a week.
   ``My concern is that in all this furor over the initiative that
people give this new plan a chance,'' Royer said. ``I think the
(school) administration has done a good job.''
</TEXT>
