<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneReturns 1stLd-Writethru a0744 09-06 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Returns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>TWA Jet Dives to Avoid Another Plane; Returns to Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to CORRECT number of injured to five sted six;
UPDATES with FAA comment other details; quotes and color. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Trans World Airlines jet with 151 people
aboard had to dive suddenly Tuesday to avoid another plane directly
in its path at 37,000 feet, and five passengers were injured, an
airline spokesman said.
   Air traffic controllers in Chicago apparently steered the plane
onto the collision course, said TWA spokesman Don Morrison. But a
Federal Aviation Administration spokesman in Chicago disputed
Morrison's statement.
   ``We have no knowledge of air traffic controllers being
involved,'' FAA spokesman Mort Edlestein told The Associated Press.
   Morrison said TWA Flight 818 was approaching Detroit about 45
minutes after it took off from St. Louis Lambert International
Airport at 4:21 p.m., CDT, non-stop for Paris when contact was made
with Chicago air traffic controllers.
   The pilot ``was given a vector change, a direction change, by the
air traffic control system,'' Morrison said. ``He made that change
until (situated) at 37,000 feet, which was his assigned altitude.
   ``As he made the turn, he noted immediately in front of him an
airplane _ a foreign aircraft. He immediately dropped altitude to
avoid the aircraft. He avoided the aircraft, went underneath it,''
Morrison said.
   Edlestein said the incident involved the TWA jetliner and a
military aircraft but said it was not being classified immediately
as a near collision.
   ``The last we knew, the planes were eight miles apart,'' said
Edlestein. ``Why he took evasive action we won't know until we talk
to the (TWA) pilot.''
   Edelstein said the FAA and the National Transportation Safety
Board would investigate.
   Morrison said the TWA pilot returned to St. Louis because the
airline's main maintenance facility is located at Lambert. Flight
818's passengers were reboarded on other flights to Paris, he said.
The plane returned to St. Louis about 6 p.m., CDT.
   Morrison said the five injured people, one a flight attendant,
were taken to hospitals for treatment. None was believed to be
seriously hurt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
