<DOCNO> AP890906-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-CulturalTies Bjt   09-06 0933</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Cultural Ties, Bjt ,0958</SECOND>
<HEAD>Though Tentatively, Foreign Scholars, Cultural Circles Again Seeking
Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academics and cultural groups worldwide are
tentatively reaching out again to China, but the June crackdown the
pro-democracy movement and its aftermath have left both sides wary
of each other.
   Chinese officials say they want exchanges but accuse Western
countries of seeking to subvert China's socialist system by sowing
ideas about democracy and capitalism.
   ``Windows cannot be opened without a screen to keep flies and
bacteria from coming in freely,'' Vice Education Minister He
Dongchang said in a recent interview.
   In an example of the new arms-length approach, he said China will
send abroad fewer doctoral students but more short-term visiting
scholars who are less likely to ``fall in love with life abroad.''
Just 20,000 of the 80,000 students China has sent abroad in the past
decade have returned.
   On the other side, Western students and scholars say they want to
continue work in China but fear it could be interpreted as a sign of
unconcern or even support for the June 3-4 army attack on student
pro-democracy protesters in which hundreds of unarmed civilians were
killed.
   ``We are hopeful that scholarly exchanges will resume but only
under conditions with which we can feel comfortable ... and not
serve political purposes,'' said Michel Oksenberg, a Chinese
specialist and political science professor at the University of
Michigan.
   ``If anything the events of April through June underscore the
inadequacies of our understanding of each other's societies,'' he
said.
   Foreign academics also wonder if it will be possible to share
ideas as before, given the government's new emphasis on stamping out
the Western liberal influences it blames for the spring of student
protests.
   ``Don't talk about politics,'' Chinese university officials
warned several Americans who arrived to teach English.
   ``Last year we had a debate _ I was George Bush and my roommate
was Michael Dukakis'' _ the U.S. presidential candidates, said one
American teacher, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``We went
through this whole spiel about how America elects presidents. I
wonder if they'd let us do that this year.''
   It is not yet clear how the dismissal of liberal Culture Minister
Wang Meng, announced by the government Monday, might affect China's
cultural ties with the outside world. Wang, a novelist who survived
two decades of persecution because of his candid works, actively
supported free expression and artistic exchanges with the outside
world.
   His apparent successor, former Propaganda Department official He
Jingzhi, is unlikely to change China's policy of encouraging
scientific, educational and cultural exchanges but will likely
require closer monitoring of foreign books, plays, movies and
performers for political messages.
   Before June, China's cultural exchanges with the rest of the
world were spiraling so rapidly that Bob Frame of the British
Council, which administers government cultural programs, said his
office had a hard time keeping up.
   But after the army attack, most exchanges with China came to an
abrupt halt. Foreign teachers and students were evacuated by their
governments amid fears of civil war, and some countries canceled
planned visits by Chinese performers.
   Suddenly, Frame said, his office had time to install a new
computer system.
   Over the past three months, however, what many foreign scholars
referred to as the ``trauma of June'' has subsided and the lure of
China has reasserted itself.
   With the new academic year, exchanges are tentatively resuming.
Programs that bring foreign scholars to China for short periods have
the highest percentage of returnees.
   No figures are available, but there seems to be a shortage of
foreigners to teach English at Beijing colleges, a job often taken
by recent American college graduates.
   ``They just begged me to stay,'' an American woman back for her
second year of English teaching said of her university officials.
   Other Americans said Chinese schools are so eager for native
English speakers that they were hired with the briefest of
interviews.
   Yale and Stanford, two major U.S. universities that send
graduates each year to teach English, will not this fall.
   Many European and American schools also are not sending Chinese
language students, placing them in Taiwan or Hong Kong programs
instead out of concern for their safety.
   But most say the move is temporary, and that they would like to
return to Beijing when it lifts martial law, now in its fourth month.
   The University of South Carolina is even thinking of starting up
a new program to send international business students to China.
``China will be a major player in the world economy,'' said the
university's Jeffrey Arpan, explaining his visit to Beijing to meet
Chinese educators.
   Western performing groups seem in no hurry to rush back to China,
partly in anger over the crackdown and partly because commercial
sponsors are reluctant. However, most foreign tours by Chinese
groups this fall are going forward.
   Most Chinese scheduled to go abroad to teach or study also appear
to be going, although the Ford Foundation said a few scholars
canceled U.S. visits because they are being investigated in
connection with the protests.
   Political investigations and re-education also have distracted
from planning new programs. Embassy spokesman Sheridan Bell said
Chinese officials say ``Let's wait until after Oct. 1, let's wait
until the new year'' when the embassy suggests exchange ideas.
   Oksenberg said putting exchanges on hold makes him nervous. It
reminds him, he said, of 1949 when the Communists took power.
   ``Things were postponed and it was thought to be temporary, but
it turned out to be for 20 years,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
