<FIRST>u a AM-PartyBloodbath     09-06 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Party Bloodbath,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent to Birthday Party Multiple Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who allegedly shot and killed his wife
and three other women at a birthday party pleaded innocent Tuesday
to four counts of murder and three counts of attempted murder.
   Raymond Navarro Jr., 26, pleaded innocent to the charges that
also included multiple murder special circumstance allegations,
which would make him eligible for the death penalty if convicted.
   Navarro was ordered held without bail pending an Oct. 11 court
appearance, said Deputy District Attorney Greg Denton.
   Maria Delia Navarro was celebrating her 27th birthday with about
20 family members and friends in her East Los Angeles home on Aug.
27 when Navarro allegedly burst in and began shooting a handgun.
   Mrs. Navarro was shot dead along with her aunts, Maria Garcia,
65, and Francisca Arizpe, 62. Family friend Leticia M. Dipp, 46, was
also killed.
   A third aunt, Berta Galvan, 47, and party guest Richard
Covarrubias, 43, survived gunshot wounds.
   Shortly before the rampage, a man called to warn Mrs. Navarro
that her estranged husband was coming to kill her. The woman called
the 911 emergency line for help, but was told to call back in what
officials later defended as standard procedure.
   ``The dispatcher did, in fact, function properly. She did not
violate any department policies or procedures,'' said Sheriff
Sherman Block.
   ``There are threats made all the time,'' the sheriff added.
``There is a difference between a threat and a clear and present
danger.''
</TEXT>
