<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-06 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICOPEE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For sale: 450 units of old military
housing at Westover Air Force base at $1 for each two-, three- and
four-family unit.
   The hitch: they must be carted off by Dec. 15 and rehabilitated
at an estimated $77,000 each.
   Chicopee officials concede the deal they are offering is no
bargain.
   ``I'd be shocked if we got any offers,'' Community Development
Director Thomas Haberlin said Tuesday. ``They are not worth
$77,000.''
   But before the city can demolish the vacant apartments to develop
the surplus base property, state regulations require it to make
every effort to sell them, he said.
   ``The units are not in very good condition, but we thought we
ought to give it a shot even through it is unlikely that we will
find someone with a use for them,'' agreed Allan W. Blair, president
of the Westover Metropolitan Development Corp.
   The corporation is a regional group that has been working for 15
years to develop the base property declared surplus by the military
when it scaled back the former Strategic Air Command base.
   Blair said the 38-year-old housing was ``very modest'' even in
its salad days and has been vacant since it was abandoned by the Air
Force in 1973.
   The units are difficult and costly to move because they were laid
on concrete slabs with no basements or floor joists to hold them
together, he said.
   ``Before they can be lifted, you have to run steel rods through
the walls to hold them together and then you have to set them down
very precisely, because the utilities are run through the walls and
you have only a 4-inch margin of error,'' he said.
   After weeks of advertising, the development group has gotten
inquiries about just two units, Haberlin said. So far though, no
deals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OGALLALA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The folks who want to keep this a nice
place to live and play in have a large _ and heavy _ message for
visitors to one of Nebraska's most popular outdoor attractions.
   ``Leave Only Your Footprints Please'' is painted in blue and
white on a 150-foot-long concrete bunker in Lake McConaughy's Martin
Bay. Two large white footprints lend emphasis.
   Sponsors hope to have the edifice cited as the world's heaviest
billboard by the Guinness Book of World Records, said Gayle Mason,
coordinator of Make Ogallala Beautiful.
   ``It's the first major thing that you see when you enter the
north side of the lake across Kingsley Dam,'' she said Tuesday.
``And it very definitely proclaims that we mean business. We want
people to take care of the lake and respect its natural beauty.''
   The anti-litter message was painted by the civic group for the
thousands of Labor Day weekend visitors to the western Nebraska lake.
   It adorns a 12-by-150-foot concrete slab once used as part of a
railroad trestle to unload train cars filled with rock used in the
dam's construction.
</TEXT>
