<FIRST>r a PM-Drugs-Nancy     09-06 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Nancy,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Reagan: Education is Key to Drug Abuse Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan, who launched an anti-drug
effort during her eight years as first lady, said education remains
the key in fighting drug abuse.
   She also told a women's conference Tuesday that her ``Just Say
No'' campaign produced positive results.
   ``They talk about Colombia and how terrible it is, which it is.
But they don't talk about the fact that at the lower age levels
there has been progress made,'' she said hours before President Bush
unveiled his $7.9 billion plan to attack drug abuse.
   ``I'd like to think that was a little bit due to the work that we
did.''
   Mrs. Reagan said education may be the ``long way around'' to
conquer drug abuse, but it is necessary.
   ``I think we have to take the customer away from the drug. We can
only do that through education,'' she said.
   Recently, U.S. attention has focused on violence sweeping through
Colombia because of the recent crackdown on cocaine traffickers.
Colombia's efforts were started after the assassination of a
presidential candidate opposed to the drug trade.
   ``They have to realize that, yes, there may be the cartels in
Colombia, or wherever. And it's sometimes easier to talk about that
than it is about the fellow on the corner who you can arrest or the
Wall Street broker who's dealing or using.
   ``Yes, the cocaine may be foreign-grown but the users are
homegrown,'' she said.
   Mrs. Reagan also talked about her years in the White House during
the speech to the Southern California Conference on Women.
   ``Everything is larger than life, the highs are higher .. by the
same token, the lows are lower,'' she said of life on Pennsylvania
Avenue.
   After moving from Washington back to California, ``I was
exhausted for a month,'' Mrs. Reagan said.
</TEXT>
