<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Analysis Bjt   09-06 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Analysis, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Anti-Drug Plan Already Embroiled in Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, the latest in a long line of
leaders to declare war against drugs, is tackling a $100
billion-a-year narcotics industry with a $7.9 billion program
already embroiled in political dispute.
   Bush describes the program he announced in his first nationally
televised address as a plan that ``is as comprehensive as the
problem.''
   To critics such as Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the
House select committee on narcotics, it is ``a thousand points of
light with no batteries.''
   ``Quite frankly,'' said Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman
Joseph Biden, ``the president's plan is not tough enough, bold
enough or imaginative enough to meet the crisis at hand.''
   Quite simply, congressional Democrats are not willing to let Bush
seize the initiative or claim credit for leading a politically
popular cause.
   After all, it was the Democratic-controlled Congress that
overcame opposition from then-President Reagan and passed
legislation that required now-President Bush to develop the overall
drug strategy he announced Tuesday night.
   House Speaker Thomas Foley faults Bush's plan as too limited, but
also warns that it could increase pressure for a tax increase.
Biden, for example, is already calling for higher taxes on wine,
beer and cigarettes to finance the drug war.
   Bush, however, insists that the battle can be waged without
raising taxes or increasing the deficit. He proposed siphoning more
than $751 million from other areas, including juvenile justice,
housing, immigration and economic development.
   Politicians of every stripe recognize that Americans are anxious
for action. A Gallup Poll released at the White House last month
found that a record 27 percent of adults view drugs as the most
important problem facing the nation, more serious than poverty, the
economy, the environment and even fear of war. That survey was taken
even before the declaration of war by drug barons against the
government of Colombia.
   Despite efforts by every president for decades, the drug problem
in America has swollen to immense proportions, with cocaine more
plentiful, purer, cheaper and more in demand than ever.
   It's big business for drug lords in Latin America and their U.S.
lieutenants. The U.S. Chamber of Commerce estimates illegal drug
sales at $110 billion annually, more than double the profits of all
the Fortune 500 companies combined.
   There are plenty of willing consumers. About 21 million Americans
have tried cocaine; 3 million still use it occasionally and 1
million report being heavy users.
   Those cocaine users are the chief targets of Bush's program.
Rather than emphasize efforts to intercept drugs before they reach
the United States, Bush's strategy is to go after the casual user.
   ``Where this country got off track in the late '60s and '70s was
believing the only people worthy of attention were the major
traffickers and kingpins, and not the individual users,'' said
William Bennett, Bush's national drug policy director and the author
of much of Bush's program.
   Bush's proposal encourages states to adopt harsher fines for
casual drug users, to seize users' cars, suspend their drivers'
licenses and send some offenders to military-style boot camps.
   Colleges and universities would be required to adopt drug
prevention programs as a condition for receiving federal funds.
   ``All of us agree that the gravest domestic threat facing our
nation today is drugs,'' Bush declared.
   ``American cocaine users need to understand that our nation has
zero tolerance for casual drug use.''
   He said the nation can win the war with hard work and over time.
   Yet, without directly pointing a finger at his critics, Bush
said, ``If we fight this war as a divided nation, then the war is
lost.''
   Democrats are anxious not to appear that they're dragging their
feet, even though they insist on reshaping Bush's program. ``We
don't oppose the president's plan,'' Biden said. ``All we want to do
is strengthen it. We don't doubt his resolve; all we want to do is
stiffen it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Terence Hunt heads the AP's White House staff and
has covered the presidency since 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
