<FIRST>r w PM-OilSpillChief     09-06 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill Chief,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Organizing Response Team Will Take Another Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil industry will be hard-pressed to
organize a nationwide network of oil spill response teams by the end
of next summer, according to a retired Coast Guard commander chosen
to direct the project.
   On his first day as president of PIRO Implementation Inc., John
D. Costello said Tuesday the industry-financed group hopes to get
the response teams fully equipped and ready for possible action
within one year.
   ``Even that's going to press us,'' Costello, 59, said in a
telephone interview.
   Costello's organization is charged with creating a Petroleum
Industry Response Organization, a coast-to-coast network of spill
cleanup experts and equipment that can respond quickly to a major
oil accident anywhere in U.S. waters.
   The idea was proposed in June by the major oil companies as the
industry's main response to the Exxon Valdez disaster in Alaska _
the largest oil spill ever in U.S. waters.
   Costello, who retired from the Coast Guard as a vice admiral in
July 1988, said he saw ``some exciting possibilities'' for quickly
improving the industry's capability of cleaning up shorelines hit
with large oil spills.
   But he stressed that it will take longer to develop ways to limit
the spread of spills as large as the Valdez accident in which the
Exxon tanker dumped 11 million gallons of crude into Prince William
Sound after ramming a reef.
   ``Current technology simply does not exist'' to contain spills of
that size, he said.
   The proposed industry network would include a headquarters in
Washington D.C. and regional ``response centers'' in New York;
Norfolk, Va.; New Orleans; Long Beach, Calif., and Seattle.
   Each center would be staffed around the clock by trained cleanup
specialists and would be equipped to handle a 30,000-ton oil spill _
about the same as the Valdez spill.
   The whole system, including PIRO Implementation, is being
financed by the major oil companies. The industry said last June in
announcing plans for the response system that it would spend $250
million on the project over five years.
   Costello capped a 36-year Coast Guard career with a four-year
stint as Pacific commander, based in Alameda, Calif., from 1984-88.
He previously was the service's representative on the National
Security Council, at the State Department and at the Justice
Department.
   Costello directed Coast Guard activities during the mass exodus
of Cubans to the United States in 1980, and during his tenure as
Pacific commander he played a role in directing the cleanup of
several oil spills off the West Coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
