<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AfricaLive     09-06 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Africa Live,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Safari: African Wildlife on Live Television for US Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African wildlife will burst into U.S.
classrooms live and in color on Sept. 28 when The Discovery Channel
establishes a two-way television and telephone link between the
United States and Kenya.
   American students nationwide will be able to peek over the
shoulders of a group of Washington-area students who will use the
linkup to ogle exotic animals in their natural habitat and discuss
conservation issues with wildlife experts in Kenya, Discovery
Channel officials said Tuesday.
   The one-hour cable television program, ``Student Safari: Africa
Watch,'' will be part of TDC's week-long series on Africa and will
use seven cameras throughout Kenya's Masai Mara Reserve _ four on
mobile vehicles and three in fixed positions.
   Four telephone lines will carry questions and replies back and
forth in what TDC officials said will be the first such
long-distance interactive classroom setup.
   Julian Pettifer of the British Broadcasting Corp., which is
co-producing the program, will play host from the Masai Mara, and
WJLA-TV news anchor Renee Poussaint will perform similar chores in
Washington. The students who participate in the linkup from a studio
in Washington will be from elementary through high school age.
   ``We believe that `Student Safari: Africa Watch' represents a
breakthrough, allowing for the first time _ live before a national
audience _ students to be linked by television to a country half the
world away,'' said Greg Moyer, TDC senior vice president@programming
group.
   ```Student Safari' represents all the exciting possibilities of a
global classroom,'' TDC Chairman John Hendrick said.
   The program will be broadcast from 10 a.m. to 11 a.m. EDT as a
special edition of TDC's new ``Assignment Discovery'' series that is
designed for use in U.S. classrooms. The World Wildlife Fund will
provide each Washington student participating in the production with
background materials before the telecast, TDC said.
   The American Association of School Administrators, National
Education Association, National School Boards Association and
National Association of Secondary School Principals are
participating in the ``Assignment Discovery'' project.
   The Discovery Channel jumped into the burgeoning classroom cable
TV market in May when it announced ``Assignment Discovery'' as a
five-day-a-week teaching tool for this school year.
   Cable News Network just began a 15-minute current events show,
``CNN Newsroom,'' that teachers may tape for use in their
classrooms, and Whittle Communications of Knoxville, Tenn., is
offering schools free televisions and videocassette recorders if
they accept a 12-minute ``Channel One'' program that contains two
minutes of commercials.
   ``Assignment Discovery,'' which will be commercial-free, will
feature a particular subject area on each day of the week, starting
with science and technology on Monday, followed by social science on
Tuesday; natural science on Wednesday; arts and humanities on
Thursday; and world events and contemporary issues on Friday. It
begins Sept. 18.
   The BBC and TDC also are producing ``Safari Live! Africa Watch''
for American audiences Sept. 22-24 from the Masai Mara Reserve.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
