<FIRST>r w PM-SovietJews     09-06 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Jews,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>US May Prescribe Waiting Period For Some Soviet Jewish Emigrants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, after successfully
persuading the Soviet Union to lower its emigration barriers, is
trying to deal with the rising tide of Jewish emigres.
   The backlog of 35,000 Soviet Jews seeking entry to the United
States poses economic and philosophic problems. After encouraging
Moscow to lower barriers to emigration, it would be awkward for the
United States to restrict admission.
   A total of 22,462 Soviet immigrants _ not all of them Jews _
entered the United States in a nine-month period that ended June 30,
according to the State Department.
   Figures released Tuesday night showed a steep increase over a
four-year period: from 640 in 1985 to 20,421 in 1988.
   Under consideration to deal with the increase, a U.S. official
said Tuesday, is a six-month waiting period for emigres who don't
have close relatives in the United States.
   There also is a proposal to process refugees in Moscow, phasing
out the Vienna offices through which many of the emigres pass.
Processing the emigres in Moscow would mean the addition of dozens
of U.S. workers there to handle paperwork.
   But the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, stressed
that no decision had been made, although one may be imminent.
   ``We are not prepared to announce any policy decisions at this
time,'' said State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   She estimated that more than 50,000 Soviets, not all of them
Jews, would apply to emigrate to the United States this year.
   Although most Soviet Jews file applications to go to Israel, the
vast majority opt for the United States once they reach Vienna.
   That distresses the Israeli government and many of its supporters
who see in the Soviet Jewish population the last large reservoir of
potential immigrants to help build up the Jewish state.
   It isn't clear whether closing the Vienna office would have the
effect of increasing the flow to Israel. Once an emigre goes there
or to any other country it is more difficult to gain admission to
the United States.
   ``There is no consensus at the State Department to close the door
on anyone,'' the official said, disputing a published report that
Soviet Jews who don't have close relatives in the United States
would become ineligible.
   However, the official said, they could be kept on hold for six
months in the Soviet Union. Those who didn't gain entry might apply
for parole status, which requires support from private organizations.
   Meanwhile, Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said the FBI
had expressed concern that a large influx of Soviet emigres could
increase the likelihood of spying.
   Although there have been discussions about curbing Soviet
immigration, ``the Justice Department has not signed off on any
proposal at this time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Pentagon-Iowa     09-06 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Iowa,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Report Unable to Cite Cause of Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is unable to cite a specific reason
for the explosion that killed 47 sailors aboard the USS Iowa, and is
expected to point only to the ``probability'' that human
intervention could have caused the tragedy, Defense Department
officials say.
   Three Navy admirals _ including the service's No. 2 man _ are
slated to release the report Thursday.
   The study wraps up the investigation into the April 19 explosion
in the battleship's No. 2 gun turret, which occurred during open
seas gunnery practice near Puerto Rico.
   Defense Department officials, speaking privately, say the report
is not expected to point to a single cause of the blast.
Investigators were hampered by the fact that no eyewitnesses
survived.
   ``There is no specific cause cited,'' said one official, who
spoke on condition his name not be used. ``It's very complicated,
and the report goes into a considerable amount of detail. It's very
complex.''
   Another official, who also spoke on background, said the report
``cites a probability'' that human action, calculated or otherwise,
could have caused the explosion.
   ``When they can't find a mechanical reason in an investigation,
they look to see whether there was a human factor involved,'' the
second official said.
   That official said investigators tried to look at all the
circumstances that could have led to the explosion, but that none
appears to have been the overriding reason for the disaster.
   The Naval Investigative Service launched a criminal investigation
into the allegations of murder and sabotage, but failed to come up
with any solid conclusions, and will instead provide a summary of
the evidence compiled through interviews, statements and other
research, the official said.
   The official said the report will show a number of ``lapses in
procedures,'' involving maintenance and the certification of sailors
to operate the ship's complex guns.
   But such problems were discounted as the primary causes of the
explosion, both officials said.
   At his daily briefing, Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said the
1,100-page report will be discussed by the Vice Chief of Naval
Operations Adm. Leon Edney and the investigating officer, Rear Adm.
Richard Milligan at a formal Pentagon briefing Thursday.
   ``It will be a very thorough briefing,'' Williams said.
   The two admirals will be joined by the head of the NIS, Rear Adm.
William Schachte.
   The long-awaited study has been the subject of much speculation,
including numerous television and newspaper reports.
   Officially, the Navy has withheld comment on the investigation,
as reports contended investigators were looking into the possibility
that suicide or murder was involved in the explosion.
   Gunner's mate 3rd Class Kendall Truitt, one of 11 sailors in the
base of the seven-story turret who survived but did not witness the
blast, has charged the Navy with leaking reports that it was
investigating his relationship with gunner's mate Clayton Hartwig,
who died in the explosion.
   Truitt has said the investigators suggested he'd had a sexual
relationship with Hartwig, or that Hartwig had committed suicide
after the two had had a falling-out.
   Truitt's lawyer, Ellis Rubin, has charged that the report ``will
find that there was defective equipment in gun turret No.2,'' as
well as unqualified personnel manning the guns.
   ``The report will hint at the possibility, through circumstantial
evidence, that gunner's mate Clayton Hartwig could have committed
suicide. I trust that the report will clear Kendall Truitt of any
prior knowledge or responsibility for the blast, whether he was
accused officially or not,'' Rubin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
