<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Facts     09-06 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Facts,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drugs in America: Quick Facts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Drugs Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a quick look at the drug problem facing
the United States of America, based on material from the American
Council for Drug Education, the National Household Survey on Drug
Abuse, the Urban Institute, the Justice Department, the House Select
Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control, the Encyclopedia Americana
and The Wilson Quarterly.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HOW MANY=
   _Some 72 million Americans, 37 percent of the population age 12
or older, have used illegal drugs at least once.
   _An estimated 14.5 million people had used illegal drugs within a
month of being asked last year.
   _About 21 million Americans have tried cocaine; 3 million still
use it occasionally and 1 million report being heavy users.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHO=
   _About 75 percent of illegal drug users are white.
   _Women constitute 41 percent of drug users, including 5 million
women of childbearing ages.
   _Eleven percent of babies born last year were exposed to illegal
drugs during the mother's pregnancy.
   _More than half those arrested for serious crimes in 14 major
cities, and who volunteered for drug testing, were found to be drug
users. In Philadelphia the figure was 82 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE COST=
   _Cocaine-induced deaths totaled 1,696 last year, up from 604 in
1984.
   _Among the victims of cocaine have been comedian John Belushi and
basketball star Len Bias.
   _Hospital emergency rooms treated 46,020 cocaine users last year,
up from 8,831 in 1984.
   _Drug-related absenteeism and medical expenses cost businesses
about 3 percent of their payroll.
   _More than 6 million people are estimated to need treatment for
drug abuse problems, including 1.3 million intravenous drug users.
   _The Justice Department charged that a group of banks involved in
laundering money for drug dealers was sending $1.2 billion annually
to Colombian drug traffickers. The Drug Enforcement Administration,
however, says no estimate of the total value of the illicit drug
trade has been made.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE DRUGS=
   _A California survey found that the purity of cocaine sold on the
street increased between 29 percent and 73 percent between 1982 and
1984 and has remained at the higher level since then. The price has
gone down in the meantime to under $100 per gram of the deadlier
drug.
   _Today's marijuana is reportedly as much as 10 times stronger
than the weed popular in the 1960s.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AT SCHOOL=
   _During the past year, 8 percent of high school seniors and 10
percent of college students said they had used cocaine.
   _Occasional drug use by college students has declined from 17
percent two years ago 10 percent now.
   A survey of 9th and 10th graders in poorer Washington D.C.
neighborhood schools found that 28 percent carried a concealed
weapon and 13 percent admitted selling drugs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AT WORK=
   _Employers report that as many as one worker in five has either
an alcohol or drug abuse problem.
   _About 3 percent of workers aged 20 to 40 report using cocaine.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY=
   _Opium has been used for medical purposes for thousands of years,
but became popular for psychological effects in the 1700s.
   _By 1900 opiates were sold over the counter and as many as one in
400 Americans were using them regularly. Laudanum, a tincture of
opium, was popular with women as a medication.
   _In 1885 one major manufacturer was selling cocaine in 15
different forms including cigarettes, cigars, inhalants, a cordial,
crystals and a solution for injection.
   _Restrictions were imposed in 1914. A substitute offered was
heroin, which only later was found to be addictive.
   _``The illicit sale of (cocaine) ... and the habitual use of it
temporarily raises the power of the criminal to a point where in
resisting arrest there is no hesitation to murder: It is more
appalling in its effect than any other habit-forming drug used in
the United States.'' From a statement to Congress by President
William Howard Taft, 1910.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0153EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Schools     09-06 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Schools,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools Must Have Firm Drug Policies or Lose Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Drugs Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools, colleges and universities stand to
lose federal aid unless they prove they have tough anti-drug use
policies with stiff penalties for use, sale or distribution of
illicit drugs.
   The anti-drug strategy unveiled by President Bush on Tuesday
night also would pay for altenative schools for youths with drug
habits and encourage states to declare schools as drug-free zones.
   Colleges and universities already have conditions for receiving
federal aid. New laws require them to ensure that illegal drugs are
not being used by employees on the job, and to have student-aid
recipients certify that they do not use drugs.
   The new strategy drafted by William Bennett, director of the
National Drug Control Policy Office, would require colleges to
develop specific punishments for students who use illegal drugs. The
plans will be required as a condition for any federal aid, including
grants and contracts as well as student aid.
   ``This is the primary goal of prevention: to see to it that
Americans _ especially school children _ never start down a slippery
slope of drug use that begins with `experimentation' but can
culminate in dependency,'' according to the drug strategy document.
``For those school children and adults who have already begun to use
drugs, the goal is a rather different one: to get them to stop.''
   Elementary and secondary schools would lose federal aid if they
failed to implement specific punishments for students caught
possessing, using or selling drugs.
   American schools have been educating students about drugs for
more than 20 years. Statistics show that about 99 percent of high
schools and 87 percent of elementary schools offer anti-drug
lessons, and even some kindergartens offer them.
   But the national drug strategy stressed that school-based
prevention programs should be reinforced by tough but fair school
policies on use, possession and distribution of drugs.
   Voicing his support for Bush's ``clear, tough blueprint for a
drug-free nation,'' Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos urged
educators and parents to ``resolve to eliminate once and for all
this threat to American education.''
   Keith Geiger, new president of the National Education
Association, agreed that Bush ``laid out a challenge for all of us''
and stressed that ``we're ready to work.''
   ``In general, (the proposal was) certainly well intentioned and
means to do the right thing but is not adequate to meet the
problem,'' said Lou Nayman of the American Federation of Teachers.
``It spoke to the goals, the kinds of things that need to be
accomplished but really did not supply any significant resources to
match the objectives.''
   Bennett singled out the ``simple and straightforward'' Anne
Arundel County, Md., drug policies that immediately expel any
student caught selling or distributing drugs. When a student is
caught using or possessing drugs, the school notifies the police,
calls his parents, and suspends him for one to five days.
   The Education Department has $354.5 million budgeted for drug
prevention programs in the current fiscal year, with 83 percent
going for state and local programs. That compares with only $3
million budgeted for drug education in 1986.
   In the next fiscal year, the administration is seeking $25
million more for emergency drug education grants, intended for urban
areas with major drug problems.
   The new strategy will encourage states to enact legislation that
protects schools as drug-free zones. About 14 states have failed to
propose or pass such legislation, said the document.
   Last year, New Jersey's drug-free school zones resulted in
arrests of 8,800 people statewide.
   The plan is for all public and private schools to become
drug-free zones where dealers and users caught on school grounds
will face penalties of five years for possession, and up to 40 years
and fines of $40,000 for distribution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Text Excerpts   09-06 1129</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Text, Excerpts,1,100</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the text of President
Bush's speech announcing a $7.9 billion war on drugs.
   
   This is the first time since taking the oath of office that I
felt an issue was so important, so threatening, that it warranted
talking directly with you, the American people. ...
   Drugs have strained our faith in our system of justice. Our
courts, our prisons, our legal system are stretched to the breaking
point. The social costs of drugs are mounting. ...
   Who's responsible? ... Everyone who uses drugs. Everyone who
sells drugs. And everyone who looks the other way. ...
   In 1985, the government estimated that 23 million Americans were
using drugs on a ``current'' basis _ that is, at least once in the
preceding month.
   Last year, that number fell by more than a third. That means
almost 9 million fewer Americans are casual drug users. ... Because
we changed our national attitude toward drugs, casual drug use has
declined.
   ... There is also bad news _ very bad news. Roughly 8 million
people have used cocaine in the past year, almost 1 million of them
used it frequently once a week or more.
   ... To win that war against addictive drugs like crack will take
more than just a federal strategy. It will take a national strategy,
one that reaches into every school, every workplace, involving every
family.
   Earlier today, I sent ... our first such national strategy to the
Congress. ... Tonight, I'm announcing a strategy that reflects the
coordinated, cooperative commitment of all federal agencies. ... Our
weapons in this strategy are: the law and criminal justice system,
our foreign policy, our treatment systems, and our schools and drug
prevention programs.
   ... Let me address four of the major elements of our strategy.
   First, we are determined to enforce the law, to make our streets
and neighborhoods safe. So to start, I'm proposing that we more than
double federal assistance to state and local law enforcement.
   ... I am also proposing that we enlarge our criminal justice
system across the board _ at the local, state and federal levels
alike. We need more prisons, more jails, more courts, more
prosecutors. ... I'm requesting _ altogether _ an almost
billion-and-a-half dollar increase in drug-related federal spending
on law enforcement.
   And while illegal drug use is found in every community, nowhere
is it worse than in our public housing projects. ... That is why I'm
targeting $50 million to fight crime in public housing projects _ to
help restore order, and to kick out the dealers for good.
   The second element of our strategy looks beyond our borders. ...
In Colombia alone, cocaine killers have gunned down a leading
statesman, murdered almost 200 judges and seven members of their
supreme court. ...
   But you and I agree with the courageous president of Colombia,
Virgilio Barco, who said that if Americans use cocaine, then
Americans are paying for murder. .... The $65 million emergency
assistance announced two weeks ago was just our first step in
assisting the Andean nations in their fight against the cocaine
cartels. ...
   Our strategy allocates more than a quarter of a billion dollars
for next year in military and law enforcement assistance for ...
Colombia, Bolivia and Peru. This will be the first part of a
five-year, $2 billion program to counter the producers, the
traffickers and the smugglers.
   I spoke with President Barco last week, and we hope to meet with
the leaders of affected countries in an unprecedented drug summit.
... I'm also asking the Senate to ratify the U.N. Anti-Drug
Convention concluded last December.
   To stop these drugs on the way to America, I propose that we
spend more than an billion-and-a-half dollars on interdiction.
   Our message to the drug cartels is this: The rules have changed.
We will help any government that wants our help. When requested, we
will for the first time make available the appropriate resources, of
America's armed forces. We will intensify our efforts against drug
smugglers on the high seas, in international airspace and at our
borders.
   We will stop the flow of chemicals from the United States used to
process drugs. We will pursue and enforce international agreements
to track drug money to the front men and financiers.
   And then we will handcuff these money launderers, and jail them _
just like any street dealers. And for drug kingpins, the death
penalty.
   The third part of our strategy concerns drug treatment. Experts
believe that there are 2 million American drug users who may be able
to get off drugs with proper treatment. But right now, only 40
percent of them are actually getting help. ... I'm proposing an
increase of $321 million in federal spending on drug treatment. ...
   Fourth, we must stop illegal drug use before it starts. ... I am
proposing a quarter-of-a-billion-dollar increase in federal funds
for school and community prevention programs that help young people
and adults reject enticements to try drugs. ... Every school,
college and university _ and every workplace _ must adopt tough but
fair policies about drug use by students and employees. Those that
will not adopt such policies will not get federal funds. Period.
   ... As you can tell, such an approach will not come cheaply. Last
February, I asked for a $700 million increase in the drug budget for
the coming year. Over the past six months of careful study, we have
found an immediate need for another billion-and-a-half dollars. With
this added $2.2 billion, our 1990 drug budget totals almost $8
billion _ the largest increase in history.
   ... The next fiscal year begins just 26 days from now. So
tonight, I'm asking the Congress ... to help us move it forward
immediately.
   We can pay for this fight against drugs without raising taxes or
adding to the budget deficit. ... To start, Congress needs not only
to act on this national drug strategy, but also to act on our crime
package announced last May; a package to toughen sentences, to beef
up law enforcement and build new prison space for 24,000 inmates.
... The states need to match tougher federal laws with tougher laws
of their own _ stiffer bail, probation, parole and sentencing.
   And we need your help. If people you know are users, help them
get off drugs. If you are a parent, talk to your children about
drugs. ... If we fight this war as a divided nation, then the war is
lost. But if we face this evil as a nation united, this will be
nothing but a handful of useless chemicals.
   Victory. Victory over drugs is our cause, a just cause, and with
your help, we are going to win.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Glance     09-06 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Glance,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Drugs Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following outlines components of President
Bush's national drug strategy at a glance. The highlights of the
strategy include:
   _ $350 million for states and local governments for criminal
justice, law enforcement and prison systems.
   _ $1.2 billion for construction of federal prisons.
   _ Requiring federally acceptable drug prevention programs and
policies as a condition to receive federal funds for schools and
colleges.
   _ Withholding federal criminal justice funds from states that do
not have drug testing for prisoners, parolees and people arrested,
and consider test results when determining sentencing, bail and
parole.
   _ $261 million to help the Andean countries of Peru, Bolivia and
Colombia fight drug lords.
   _ More money for domestic eradication efforts.
   _ Tougher regulations for federal housing projects to expedite
evictions of drug dealers, and expand drug prevention programs for
resident associations.
   _ Urges greater use of employee drug testing in state and local
government and the private sector.
   _ Encourages stiffer penalties for drug users.
   _ More federal money for community drug prevention efforts.
   _ Increased money for treatment programs to expand the number of
people who can be treated, the range of treatment programs, and
emphasize treatment for pregnant women who use drugs.
   _ Making receipt of federal treatment funds contingent on state
and local compliance with federal standards for effective drug
treatment programs.
   _ Expanded research and information coordination to evaluate and
develop more effective treatments.
   _ Greater border interdiction emphasis on drug-detection dogs,
document fraud, container inspection and other methods.
   _ More emphasis on air interdiction, and catching drug couriers
and money launderers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Plan     09-06 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Plan,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Anti-Drug Plan Urges Crackdown on Casual Users</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Drugs Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Casual drug users could lose their cars, be
fired from their jobs, pay stiff fines, or suffer the embarrassment
of having their names published in the newspaper in an anti-drug
society envisioned by President Bush.
   Bush, in an national drug strategy announced Tuesday night,
called for more spending on law enforcement and drug treatment,
education and prevention. He also earmarked $261 million next year
to go after drug kingpins in Colombia, Peru and Bolivia, the
beginning of a $2 billion installment over five years.
   But he also urged a crackdown on users, including non-addicts who
take drugs for so-called recreational purposes.
   ``American cocaine users need to understand that our nation has
zero tolerance for casual drug use,'' Bush said in his nationally
televised address.
   He said the government will withhold federal funds from schools
and colleges that don't have federally acceptable drug education and
prevention policies.
   Many components in Bush's drug strategy are merely
recommendations. Others include federal funding proposals.
   Among the principal spending plans outlined for fiscal year 1990:
   _ $350 million for law enforcement grants to cities and states, a
$200 million increase over the current authorization. To get the
money, states must impose drug testing for arrestees, prisoners,
parolees and those out on bail.
   _ $1.2 billion for construction of new federal prisons. That
money was already included in the crime package proposal he sent to
Congress earlier this year, and is included in an overall $1.6
billion figure for federal corrections spending.
   _ $925 million for drug abuse treatment, a 53 percent increase
from the current year's $604 million authorization.
   _ $1.2 billion for prevention and education efforts, 25 percent
over the current authorization of $943 million.
   _ $261 million for military and law enforcement aid for the three
South American countries that are the principal producers of
cocaine, more than four times the approximately $53 million they get
in the current budget.
   Total foreign aid to those countries, including the anti-drug
money, is almost $163 million in 1989. The $261 million is part of a
total $449 million to include economic aid that Bush proposes for
international anti-drug efforts.
   The 1990 proposal does not include the $65 million in military
aid Bush ordered for Colombia last month. The $2 billion envisioned
for the three countries over a five-year period will be conditioned
on evaluation of their efforts to quash the drug lords, said
national drug policy coordinator William Bennett.
   _ $250 million for courts, correctional institutions and
alternatives to jail and prison, such as boot camps and house arrest.
   The total $7.9 billion package also includes $3 billion for
border interdiction and other efforts including a campaign against
money-laundering.
   Marijuana eradication efforts would be doubled from $8 million to
$16 million.
   Giving a Democratic response to Bush's plan, Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-Del., said ``the president's plan is not tough enough, bold
enough'' to deal with the drug problems. He accused Bush of trying
to fight the drug wars ``on the cheap.''
   The numbers in the 154-page strategy reflect authorization
figures, not money that actually will be spent, and they do not
indicate where that money will come from. For example, because
prisons take a long time to build, only a small portion of the $1.2
billion for prisons will be spent in 1990.
   Bush is calling on the states to stiffen penalties for users.
   Bennett explained the philosophy, saying, ``Where this country
got off track in the late 60s and 70s was believing the only people
worthy of attention were the major traffickers and kingpins, and not
the individual users.''
   ``You can exercise sanctions without putting people in jail,''
Bennett said. ``You can take away their drivers' licenses, you can
fine them, you can take away their automobiles if they're using
their automobiles to hide drugs or to store drugs. You can notify
their employers. Employers can fire them.''
   Bush's strategy advocates imposition of such actions, as well as
publishing convicted drug users' names in newspapers.
   For the most hardened drug traffickers, Bush renewed his
endorsement of the death penalty.
   Other components include:
   _ Tougher regulations for federal housing projects to expedite
evictions of drug dealers and expand drug prevention programs for
resident associations.
   _ Urging greater use of employee drug testing in state and local
government and the private sector.
   _ More federal money for community drug prevention efforts.
   _ Expanded research and information coordination to evaluate and
develop more effective treatments.
</TEXT>
