<FIRST>r w PM-ArmsNegotiator 490   09-06 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Negotiator, 490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Name Conservative Democrat as New Negotiator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will name James Woolsey Jr., a
conservative Democrat and weapons specialist, as the new U.S.
negotiator in 23-nation talks to reduce non-nuclear forces in
Europe, an official says.
   Security checks have begun on Woolsey, a lawyer chosen over two
other candidates, the official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said Tuesday.
   The other candidates were Stephen Ledogar, a career diplomat who
now holds the job, and Philip Karber, vice president of the BDM
Corp., the official said.
   The negotiations resume Thursday in Vienna between the 16-nation
North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the seven-nation Warsaw Pact.
Ledogar, who was appointed by President Reagan in 1987 to help
arrange the talks, will remain in the post for the time being.
   Another official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Tuesday evening that NATO would press hard in Vienna for a treaty
provision for the stationing of monitors in the two alliance areas
across Europe.
   The Washington Post said in today's editions that the proposal
would mean inspection of virtually every military installation from
the Atlantic Ocean to the Ural Mountains dividing the European and
Asian parts of the Soviet Union.
   The official also said NATO was considering a proposal for the
expansion of the existing East-West requirements that each side
notify the other of certain military maneuvers, but questions
remained unsettled about what equipment should be covered by the
notice requirement and how big a maneuver area should be specified.
   Some compromises may have to be made on several questions.
   ``We don't want to table something and then have a squabble
within NATO ranks,'' the official said.
   Bush has raised expectations of an accord by the end of the year,
but that appears only a long-shot possibility.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler declined to assess
the prospects. She said Secretary of State James A. Baker III had
met Friday and Tuesday with aides to prepare for the resumption of
negotiations.
   The process of nominating Woolsey and having him confirmed by the
Senate could take several weeks.
   Woolsey, 48, has a reputation for political skill as well as
weapons expertise. He has close ties with Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the
chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, while retaining the
trust of defense-minded Republicans.
   He was undersecretary of the Navy in the Carter administration,
has served on the staffs of the National Security Council and the
Senate Armed Services Committee and has worked at the Pentagon.
   As an occasional adviser to the Reagan administration, Woolsey
joined with Brent Scowcroft, Bush's national security adviser, in
recommending development of the Midgetman missile, a mobile,
single-warhead long-range nuclear weapon.
   In April, Bush decided to proceed with a plan to buy and deploy
300 to 500 of the missiles on trucks and proposed that 50 MX
missiles housed in underground silos be put on rail cars.
   The cost of the two programs, if Congress provides the funds,
could exceed $40 billion.
</TEXT>
