<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Dooney     09-06 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Dooney,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Cites Case of Maryland Boy in Drug Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is promising a 6-year-old
Maryland boy named Dooney that he won't have to be a drug dealer
when he grows up.
   ``Not long ago, I read a newspaper story about a little boy named
Dooney, who, until recently, lived in a crack house in a suburb of
Washington, D.C.,'' Bush said Tuesday in a televised address on his
national drug strategy. ``In Dooney's neighborhood, children don't
flinch at the sound of gunfire. And when they play, they pretend to
sell to each other small white rocks they call crack.
   ``Life at home was so cruel that Dooney begged his teachers to
let him sleep on the floor at school. And, when asked about his
future, 6-year-old Dooney answers, `I don't want to sell drugs, but
I will probably have to.'''
   Bush, after outlining his anti-drug plan, declared: ``Dooney does
not have to sell drugs. No child in America should have to live like
this.''
   Dooney Waters was the subject of a Washington Post series in July
that detailed the fear and filth he lived in with his drug-addicted
mother.
   ``My mother don't take care of me,'' Dooney told the Post. ``All
she want is drugs.''
   The Post stories told how Dooney had to fend for himself in a
home where drugs users slept, dealers made their sales and police
made arrests. A reporter and photographer from the Post spent two
months observing Dooney's life.
   Before the series ran, Dooney's 32-year-old mother, Addie L.
Waters, checked into a treatment program to kick her drug habit and
the boy went to live with his father.
</TEXT>
