<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Warns Against Shoreham Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy may be setting a
time-consuming precedent by asking for an environmental impact study
before the Shoreham nuclear power plant can be closed, a nuclear
watchdog group says.
   ``If the state of New York is required to submit a full EIS for
the dismantling of Shoreham, a plant which has operated for less
than 30 hours, a precedent would be established under which the
nation's nuclear utilities may likewise be required to submit full
EIS's for the decommissioning of their nuclear power plants, some of
which have operated for more than 10,000 hours,'' Public Citizen
said in a letter Tuesday to Energy Secretary James Watkins.
   The group was founded by consumer activist Ralph Nader. In July,
Watkins called for a full environmental review of the plan to close
Shoreham, which could delay its decommissioning by several years.
</TEXT>
