<FIRST>u i AM-Demjanjuk 3rdLd-Writethru a0614 09-06 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Demjanjuk, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0614,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Claims New Evidence Found in Demjanjuk Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: CORRECTS in lede and 4th graf that attorney asked for a delay
of at least six months, sted 18 months; pickup 5th graf pvs, `The Israeli...'
^By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for Nazi war criminal John Demjanjuk
said Tuesday new evidence that could help his client has been found
in a garbage bin at the U.S. Justice Department, and he asked for a
delay of at least six months in the case.
   Attorney Yoram Sheftel accused people in the department of
concealing the evidence, which he said includes testimony
contradicting court rulings Demjanjuk was responsible for gassing to
death hundreds of thousands of Jews in World War II.
   Demjanjuk, 69, a retired auto worker from a Cleveland suburb, was
found guilty by an Israeli court in April 1988 of crimes against
humanity and crimes against the Jewish people and sentenced to death.
   His appeal was scheduled to be heard starting Nov. 1. In court
petitions, Sheftel asked for a delay of at least six months, citing
documents he said were found in a garbage bin at the Justice
Department's Office of Special Investigations. The office probes
suspected Nazi war criminals.
   The Israeli attorney accused the office of ``concealing important
evidence on the one hand and falsifying other evidence'' in
proceedings that stripped Demjanjuk of U.S. citizenship in 1981,
paving the way for his extradition to Israel five years later.
   There was no comment from the office. A spokesman in Washington
did not immediately return a phone call from The Associated Press.
   Demjanjuk's trial was Israel's first of an accused war criminal
in 25 years.
   Witnesses identified him as a sadistic guard known as ``Ivan the
Terrible'' who switched on the gas chambers at the Treblinka death
camp in Nazi-occupied Poland, where 850,000 Jews perished between
1942 and 1943.
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk claimed to be a victim of mistaken
identity.
   Sheftel said in a telephone interview that the documents found
were ``of decisive importance to the results of the appellant's
trial'' because they challenge important testimony identifying
Demjanjuk as Ivan.
   He said one document shows that a key witness, former Nazi prison
guard Otto Horn, failed to identify Demjanjuk in a photo lineup.
During the trial, the court was told Horn did identify him.
   Another document would appear to challenge whether a witness at a
1980 trial to strip Demjanjuk of U.S. citizenship recognized
Demjanjuk in a photo from a Nazi identification card, the attorney
said. The card was a key piece of evidence in the trial.
</TEXT>
