<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0258EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     09-06 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Uncle Buck' Leads Weekly Box-Office Charts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Box Office-Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Uncle Buck,'' starring John Candy as an
obnoxious relative taking care of his two nieces and a nephew, was
the best box office ticket during the holiday weekend. ``Casualties
of War'' dropped out of the top 10.
   ``Uncle Buck'' held the top spot for the third-straight weekend,
this time on sales of $7.8 million, according to Exhibitor Relations
Co.
   In second place was ``Parenthood'' with $7.5 million. It was
followed in third by the underwater action film ``The Abyss,'' with
$5.5 million.
   ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' the action sequel reuniting Mel Gibson and
Danny Glover, was fourth with $4.7 million. In fifth with $4 million
was the romantic comedy ``When Harry Met Sally...,'' starring Billy
Crystal and Meg Ryan.
   Next was the police comedy ``Turner &amp; Hooch,'' pairing Tom Hanks
with a salivating canine, which grossed $3.8 million. ``Batman''
finished in seventh, adding $3.5 million.
   The lower-case, acclaimed character study ``sex, lies and
videotape,'' which has been playing in limited release, expanded to
347 screens and boosted its income to $3.4 million for eighth place.
   Rounding out the top 10 were ``Relentless,'' the new Judd Nelson
movie, which brought in $2.8 million, and ``Honey, I Shrunk the
Kids'' with $2.7 million.
   ``Casualties of War,'' the story of a group of U.S. soldiers who
rape and murder a South Vietnamese girl during the war, has proved
to be a flop. In just its third week of release, ``Casualties of
War,'' starring Michael J. Fox and Sean Penn, took in $1.9 million.
It has grossed only $13.7 million so far and is no longer among the
top 10.
   ``Shirley Valentine'' made a strong but limited debut, collecting
$245,422 on eight screens.
   Here are the top movies for the Labor Day weekend as tallied by
Exhibitor Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of
screens, average per screen, total gross and weeks in release.
   1. ``Uncle Buck,'' Universal, $7.8 million, 1,832 screens, $4,270
per screen, $34.7 million, three weeks.
   2. ``Parenthood,'' Universal, $7.5 million, 1,390 screens, $5,395
per screen, $64.1 million, five weeks.
   3. ``The Abyss,'' 20th Century Fox, $5.5 million, 1,532 screens,
$3,611 per screen, $40.7 million, four weeks.
   4. ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' Warner Bros., $4.7 million, 1,613
screens, $2,889 per screen, $131.3 million, nine weeks.
   5. ``When Harry Met Sally...,'' Columbia, $4 million, 1,152
screens, $3,429 per screen, $66.6 million, eight weeks.
   6. ``Turner &amp; Hooch,'' Disney, $3.8 million, 1,536 screens,
$2,500 per screen, $57.2 million, six weeks.
   7. ``Batman,'' Warner Bros., $3.5 million, 1,344 screens, $2,634
per screen, $238.6 million, 11 weeks.
   8. ``sex, lies and videotape,'' Miramax, $3.4 million, 347
screens, $9,847 per screen, $8.1 million, five weeks.
   9. ``Relentless,'' New Line, $2.8 million, 835 screens, $3,399
per screen, $3.3 million, one week.
   10. ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids,'' Disney, $2.7 million, 1,257
screens, $2,179 per screen, $119.1 million, 10 weeks.
