<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia-Security     09-06 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Security,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs and Security are Booming in Violent Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When bombs are exploding in Bogota and
other Colombian cities, so is the multimillion-dollar security
business in this violent country.
   A car bullet-proofing plant in Bogota recently was jammed to
capacity with 20 vehicles being armored at $50,000 to $60,000 each.
   The number of security companies in the city of 6 million people
has grown to 315 from just 20 a decade ago, and that is just the
number legally registered with the Defense Ministry.
   American and Colombian businessmen are spending up to $1 million
a year for personal security, a former Colombian army major, now the
vice president of a Bogota security firm, said in an interview.
   The violence comes from many directions: leftist guerrillas,
right-wing death squads, revenge-minded drug traffickers upset with
the government's extradition plans and common criminals.
   The former army major's security company offices were buzzing at
7 a.m. one recent day.
   ``Get two more men over there! Now!'' he yelled to an assistant
who had just received a call from a customer, an American company,
for more protection.
   ``We don't have enough men to fill all the jobs we're being asked
to do'' and new business is being turned away, he said.
   He asked that he and his company not be identified because he
fears for the lives of his wife and 3-year-old daughter.
   The former major was an intelligence officer twice decorated for
leading commandos that freed kidnapped people during states of siege
in Colombia, and he has made a lot of enemies in his work against
leftist guerrillas and common criminals.
   He said there are about 2,000 bulletproof cars in Colombia, many
of them imported. Drug traffickers have bulletproof cars that are
imported with bribe payments to customs officials, he said.
   A former U.S. ambassador to Colombia, Tom Boyatt, once told an AP
reporter that it took the embassy months to import his
bullet-resistant V-8 Cadillac limousine because eight-cylinder
engines are prohibited in Colombia.
   They consume too much gas, the government decided years ago.
   At the car bullet-proofing plant, Veimas, the noise was deafening
as employees swarmed around the cars, pounding, scraping, sanding
and sawing.
   Last year the company bullet-proofed 80 cars, said an execuctive
with the company, Eugenio Villegas. Business is increasing every
year, he said.
   The cars are armored with combinations of quarter-inch steel and
woven materials. The vehicles being armored during the visit were
mostly four-wheel drive types used by security men who follow an
executive and other guards in another bullet resistant car.
   In Bogota, it is common to be forced off the road by cars crammed
with men with submachine guns, shotguns and pistols who are trying
to stay on the bumper of the car they are protecting.
   On almost every block of Bogota's wealthy neighborhoods, in the
northern area of the capital, guards can be seen on the streets, in
doorways and in cars.
   Some of the guards come from security companies that pay them the
minimum wage of about $100 a month. They typically look like
gardeners, armed with rusty, single-shot shotguns.
   Others look more professional with modern weapons.
   The 315 registered security companies in Bogota offer bodyguards
and home security systems.
   Every morning at private schools limousines pull up and the
children who get out are surrounded by burly guards.
   Women on the way to the hair salon occasionally are seen
accompanied by up to 10 men with submachine guns, shotguns and
pistols.
   A few golfers at country clubs are accompanied by men carrying
Ingram submachine guns in leather briefcases that will flop open at
the flick of a finger.
   ``It's tough to get a foursome together when your friends know
someone might start popping away at you,'' an American once told an
AP reporter who was his golf partner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
