<DOCNO> AP890906-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0335EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Drugs-Addicts     09-06 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Addicts,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Addicts Say Bush Plan Won't Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Drugs Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Addicts at a drug treatment center say
President Bush is leading the charge up the wrong hill in his war on
drugs, attacking cocaine and threatening prison when his program
should focus on treatment.
   Frank, Terry and Richard, an alcoholic, watched the speech in a
room at the Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, which has a 27-bed
voluntary treatment program. The patients spoke on condition that
their last names not be revealed.
   ``He's talking like he's talking to a bunch of schoolchildren,''
said Frank, 33, who is being treated for his addiction to
painkillers.
   Terry said Bush's plan to spend $925 million for treatment of
addicts was far too little.
   ``He sounded like a third-grade schoolteacher,'' said Terry, 34,
who is battling heroin. ``He was banging those rocks on the table _
he didn't make it scary enough.''
   She referred to the plastic bag of rock cocaine the president
used as a prop during the speech.
   ``Treatment is expensive. Street addicts are not going to be able
to come to Cedars-Sinai ... and the state programs are a joke,'' she
said.
   ``He made one big blunder, calling cocaine the nation's No. 1
drug problem,'' said Dr. Ronald Gershman, medical director of the
Center for Chemical Dependency.
   ``Alcoholism is the No. 1 drug in the nation. I think they are
being very narrow to focus all their attention on cocaine. It's a
scapegoat,'' said Gershman, who has been treating addicts for 15
years.
   Gershman said Americans face a flood of drugs, including
domestically made illegal amphetamines, abuse of prescription drugs,
heroin from Asia and Mexico and so-called designer drugs, such as
ecstasy.
   ``He talks about cocaine fields in Colombia _ how about the
California marijuana fields?'' Gershman asked.
   ``The bottom lines on those programs is that they are
ineffectual,'' he said. ``He missed the point. What he outlined
won't work. Drug treatment is labor-intensive and expensive. It has
to be recognized as a major medical problem.''
   All three patients agreed that employee insurance should be
mandated to cover treatment programs.
   Richard said he believed his employer, a law firm, used its
employee health program to discover his alcohol addiction and find a
way to fire him.
   ``I thought my employer was backing me, but they were really
looking for any way they could to get rid of me,'' he said.
   The patients derided Bush's proposal to increase the size of
federal prisons and toughen sentences for drug users.
   ``When you have an addiction, you don't think about anything but
the drug,'' Frank said.
   ``The worst patient in our unit right now has spent most of his
life in San Quentin,'' Gershman said.
</TEXT>
