<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Drugs-Reax Bjt   09-06 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Reax, Bjt,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Speech Reax: More Than Quick Fix Only if Neighborhoods Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's plan of attack in the war on drugs will be no
more than a quick fix unless neighborhoods across America rally to
the cause, say some state and local officials.
   Others found the $7.9 billion plan proposed in a nationally
televised speech Tuesday night too small for an all-out war.
   The president's push drew plaudits from those on the drug front
lines who have said they needed him in the fight.
   ``Maybe at last we'll have a nation that is dedicated to
comprehensive solution and can get off the quick fixes and cliches
like the death penalty,'' said Cary Edwards, former New Jersey
Attorney General and author of the state's Comprehensive Drug Reform
Act of 1987.
   Bush's call for a battle fought ``block by block, child by
child'' struck a responsive chord in many communities.
   In a drug-infested Chicago neighborhood, Leola Spann, director of
the Northwest Austin Council, said residents have begun the fight.
   ``I think communities are coming out and saying we're going to
take back our communities. Law enforcement knows we're behind
them,'' said Spann, whose group has hung ``Drug-Free Zone'' signs
around a school.
   Florida Gov. Bob Martinez said Bush was correct in saying that
money was not the solution.
   ``Floridians have already spent tens of millions of dollars on
the drug fight and the crime rate continues to rise,'' the
Republican Martinez said.
   ``What the president emphasized tonight is that money alone is
not going to win this fight. What wins it is the will of the
American people.''
   Some said education remained the key to the drug war, but Los
Angeles Police Chief Daryl Gates said U.S. troops also were needed.
   ``I think you're going to see the need for the U.S. military to
become more actively involved,'' Gates said. He advocated ``a
friendly invasion'' of Colombia and other drug-producing nations.
   But Miami-based U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen, whose office
prosecutes more cocaine cases than any other, advocated a fight
focusing on cutting demand for drugs.
   ``We are to blame, not some Latin American country. Until we
realize that, we will not be taking a realistic approach to cleaning
up our own act,'' he said.
   Bush for the first time pledged U.S. military help to any
government that requests it, but most of his initiatives were close
to home: harsher penalties for users and more money for prisons,
treatment and education.
   Many said Bush's plan offered too little.
   ``I feel a little bit like the man whose house is burning down,
only to find that my next-door neighbor brought over a garden hose
to fight the fire,'' said California Attorney General John Van de
Kamp, an expected Democratic gubernatorial candidate.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said the president's program provided
little comfort to states.
   ``Local governments that are the front line in the war against
drugs welcome the president's concern, but they would welcome more
the resources needed to win this war before more of our children
become casualties,'' said Cuomo, a Democrat.
   Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn, also a Democrat, found other faults.
He said the policy was ``an empty gesture'' because it doesn't
provide for mandatory drug education in the schools, mandatory
treatment on demand for drug addicts or for mandatory federal prison
sentences for convicted drug dealers.
   Some officials were already making plans for federal funds.
   Asked how he would use $1 million if the federal government
granted it to his department to fight drugs, St. Paul, Minn., Police
Chief William McCutcheon said he would give it to schools.
   ``What we do in law enforcement is really short-term,'' he said.
``We need to change attitudes. We need to tell the young people
there's something better than chemicals.''
   In California, Orange County Sheriff Brad Gates said educational
efforts should include corporations and churches. He also said
people should speak their minds on the issue.
   ``You have to stick your head out the window and say `I'm not
going to take it anymore,'' he said.
</TEXT>
