<FIRST>r a PM-SubProtest     09-06 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sub Protest,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-War Protestors Subvert Base Security, Board Nuclear Submarine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GORDON FAIRCLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear-weapons protester said she was
able to swim unnoticed into a top-secret Navy research center and
beat on a Trident-missile-firing submarine with a hammer before she
was arrested.
   Jacqueline Allen, 24, of Voluntown, discussed the Labor Day
attack on the moored USS Pennsylvania after an appearance Tuesday in
U.S. District Court, where she and six others were charged with
trespassing on Navy property and with destruction of government
property.
   They were released by a magistrate after signing promises to
appear in court to face the charges.
   Allen said the protesters wanted to send a message to the Navy
that ``these weapons don't make us secure and you can't secure the
weapons.''
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., said the incident raises
``grave questions about security at the underwater systems center.''
   ``From a political standpoint, you wouldn't want to equate an act
of protest with an act of sabotage. From a security standpoint,
however, the fact that protesters could actually climb up on a
nuclear sub at a naval installation suggests the potential for far
more serious mischief.''
   Security at the Naval Underwater Systems Center was appropriate
and no investigation was planned, said Navy Lt. Cmdr. John Ward, a
spokesman for the Groton submarine base, which has authority over
security at the New London center.
   The protesters swam and paddled in a blackened canoe to reach the
sub at its berth at the New London center, according to authorities
and the protesters.
   Allen said she swam under the dock alongside the Pennsylvania,
reached the sub at about midship, poured a bottle of her blood on
the hull, scratched the word ``death'' in the paint and began
pounding on the ship with a hammer. She said it was the banging that
caused the guards to notice her.
   Two other swimmers, including Anne Montgomery, a 62-year-old
Roman Catholic nun from New York, were discovered shortly before
they reached the sub, the protesters said. Both pounded the hull
with hammers, an action meant to symbolize the biblical admonition
to beat swords into ploughshares.
   The submarine was not damaged and the protesters were prevented
from boarding, the Navy said.
   The ship is to be commissioned into the fleet on Saturday.
   The attack was similar to one seven years ago when nine
anti-nuclear activists broke into a shipyard across the Thames River
from the research center and vandalized the Trident submarine USS
Florida.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
