<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-US 2ndLd-Writethru a0478 09-06 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-US, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0478,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix garble in coding.</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Staff Leave Lebanon, `Deteriorating Circumstances' Cited</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with official U.S. confirmation of evacuation,
details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. ambassador John McCarthy and his
American staff were evacuated from Lebanon early Wednesday after
hundreds of Christians besieged the U.S. Embassy compound to protest
Washington's policy in Lebanon.
   The 30 diplomats were taken by helicopter to Cyprus because of
``deteriorating local circumstances ... no longer permitted the
embassy to function effectively,'' said Keith Peterson, a spokesman
for the U.S. Embassy in Nicosia.
   Peterson stressed: ``The United States of America is not
abandoning Lebanon,'' dismissing accusations the traditionally
pro-American Lebanese Christians have repeated in recent days.
   He said the diplomatic staff would return ``when the situatioon
permits.'' The sudden decision to pull out of Lebanon, where
Christian forces and Syrian troops have been fighting for six
months, came after supporters of Christian army commander Gen.
Michel Aoun surrounded the embassy on Tuesday.
   The protesters hoped to force the United States to take a tougher
stance against Syria's military presence in Lebanon.
   Peterson added: ``The personnel were evacuated to Cyprus and are
being flown from Cyprus to their final destination.'' He would not
give details of their travel plans.
   An army spokesman at Aoun's headquarters in the Christian suburb
of Yarze said the American diplomats left aboard three helicopters.
   Unofficial sources in Cyprus, 100 miles west of Lebanon, said the
aircraft had landed at Akrotiri, one of two British bases on the
island. Officers at the base would neither confirm nor deny the
report.
   The Lebanese army spokesman, who insisted on anonymity, said the
Americans had notified Aoun of their ``intention to leave.''
   He said that after the departure of dependents and non-essential
staff during the past six months of renewed fighting, ``about a
dozen'' Americans had been left at the embassy.
   Beirut's leftist daily paper As-Safir had said Tuesday that the
U.S. Embassy ``has informed those concerned that it is prepared to
close down if it comes under harassment.'' It did not elaborate.
   The Christians besieging the embassy compound were angry at the
United States for not coming to their aid against the Syrian army
and its Moslem allies since hostilities began March 8.
   Since then, fighting between the factions has clained the lives
of 827 people and wounded 2,452.
   The siege reflected widespread anger among Lebanon's estimated 1
million Christians that the West has not come to their rescue. They
are trapped in a coastal enclave that is ringed by the Syrians and
their allies.
   The crowd had on Tuesday gone into a frenzy, shouting ``We
Sacrifice Our Blood for You, Oh Aoun,'' ``McCarthy Go Home'' and
``The Biggest Catastrophe Is McCarthy.'' They waved placards and
posters denouncing America.
   Christian sources said the embassy siege was designed by Aoun to
whip up anti-American sentiment among Christians inside and outside
Lebanon, to bring pressure to bear on the United States.
   The demonstrators said Tuesday that their peaceful siege would go
on ``until our demands are met.''
   They demanded that McCarthy submit his credentials to ``the
legitimate Lebanese authorities represented by General Aoun'' and
official U.S. recognition of Aoun's authority.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, is competing
for legitimacy with Aoun's three-member Christian Cabinet.
   McCarthy, who took up his post in September 1988, after the
emergence of the dual government, has not submitted his credentials
to either Cabinet. He has publicly criticized Syria for not
responding to a U.S. behest to negotiate with Aoun, but Aoun has
charged that Washington is not turning sufficient heat on Syria to
soften its intransigence.
   The demonstrators also demanded that Washington dispatch an
official delegate to Lebanon on a fact-finding mission like ``the
Soviets and French did'' and the lifting of the blockade imposed on
the Christians by the Syrians.
   The Christian enclave has taken a fearful pounding from Syrian
artillery since yjr fighting broke out between Aoun's mainly
Christian forces and an alliance of Syrian troops and Druse
miltiamen.
   Aoun launched his self-proclaimed ``war of liberation'' to force
the Syrians to withdraw their 40,000 troops in Lebanon.
   Even though his forces are outnumbered and outgunned, his
objective appeared to be to mobilize U.S. and European support for
the Christians.
   That startegy has patently failed. Washington has made
sympathetic noises, but has made it clear it has no intention of
getting drawn into the Lebanese quagmire again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
