<FIRST>r a PM-People-MCA-Azoff     09-06 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-MCA-Azoff,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savior of MCA's Music Unit Quits to Start His Own Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Azoff, who in six years
resurrected MCA Records from an also-ran to the No. 2 pop music
label, has quit to form his own entertainment company.
   ``Now it's time for me to gather up my stuff, move outside the
system and try slaying the dragon again,'' he said Tuesday in a
farewell letter to MCA Records employees. ``See you soon on the
charts _ at the top, of course.''
   Azoff decided in April 1983 to join MCA, which he said was ``to
the record business what strip-mining is to the ecology.''
   He broadened the label's base beyond rock and jazz into black
music, signing such acts as Klymaxx, Stephanie Mills, Patti LaBelle
and Gladys Knight, and contemporary country, with artists such as
The Judds, Lyle Lovett, George Strait and Reba McEntire.
   ``Today our roster boasts some of the most impressive names in
contemporary including ... Bobby Brown, Elton John, Boston, Tiffany,
Jody Watley, New Edition, Pebbles and Fine Young Cannibals,'' Azoff
said.
   Billboard magazine reported MCA had become the No. 2 pop label in
1988, behind CBS Records. MCA was ranked 12th in 1983.
   In 1983, MCA had nine gold and one platinum LPs; by 1988 the
figures were 17 gold, eight platinum, four double platinum, two
triple platinum and one quadruple platinum record. Gold records are
awarded for sales of 500,000 long-playing records, tapes and compact
disks, platinum for 1 million.
</TEXT>
