<FIRST>r a PM-CasinoGambling     09-06 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casino Gambling,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indiana Lawmakers Gather in Gary to Consider Issue of Casino Gambling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took some imagination to envision two
industrial sites and a cornfield as home to glittering gambling
casinos.
   But all it really will take is money.
   ``You could put grass on that and make it look like a pasture,''
said Steve Norton, executive vice president of Resorts
International, after viewing the sites with a legislative study
committee.
   The committee tour was part of a daylong hearing Tuesday on
legislative efforts to bring casino gambling to the city's ailing
economy.
   Mayor Thomas V. Barnes, who contends that casinos could bring
thousands of jobs and $60 million in tax revenues, said the
90-minute tour gave legislators firsthand knowledge of the sites.
   ``From then on, it's up to us to build our case for revenue and
job potential,'' he said.
   The move faces continued opposition.
   ``We need to be capitalizing on the strengths of people, not on
their weaknesses,'' the Rev. William D. Booth said before a meeting
of the study committee reviewing casino legislation.
   Booth said the lure of jobs and tax revenue hides the reality of
family disruption and wasted money brought on by gambling.
   ``We don't believe we will build a great city or build a great
people bringing into our circumstance this kind of enterprise,'' he
said.
   Booth is a co-chairman of No Casinos for Gary, a church
based-organization seeking oppostion votes in a non-binding
referendum.
   Barnes has been rallying votes for the Nov. 4 referendum while
urging the General Assembly to pass laws permitting casino gambling
in Gary.
   Resorts International operates a casino in Atlantic City, N.J.,
and joined Gary officials earlier this year in an unsuccessful
effort to win approval for casino gambling in Indiana.
   The General Assembly earlier this year approved the referendum
for Gary after rejecting the broader legislation.
</TEXT>
