<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0439EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-06 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Unchanged, Nikkei Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose during trading to a two-month high
against the yen today but closed unchanged, while share prices on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined.
   The dollar opened at 146.90 yen, slightly above Tuesday's close
of 146.65 yen, and rose rapidly to 147.38 yen despite repeated
interventions by the Bank of Japan during morning trading, currency
dealers said.
   It was the first time the dollar rose above 147.00 yen since June
15, when it closed at 150.30 yen.
   The dollar turned bearish in the afternoon, however, following
speculation that Japan may increase its interest rates, the dealers
said. It closed at 146.65 yen, unchanged from Tuesday's close.
   The dealers attributed the dollar's strength in the morning to
the continued strong performance of the U.S. economy and reduced
anxiety about inflation.
   ``When it passed the 147-yen mark, the traders in the market were
beginning to feel it may be rising too fast,'' said a dealer at
Daiichi Kangyo Bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Then the
rumor about an interest-rate increase hit the market.''
   He said a report that quoted Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita as
saying the central bank would take every possible measure to stop
the yen's slide was taken as a warning of an interest rate increase.
   Dealers also said the dollar's firmness followed its surge in the
New York market Tuesday despite concerted interventions by central
banks in the United States and Europe.
   ``In the morning, the dollar's upsurge made us think it may
surpass the 150-yen mark before long,'' said the dealer at Daiichi
Kangyo.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 41.83-point loser Tuesday, shed another 170.64 points, or
0.48 percent, to close at 34,271.31.
   Securities dealers said the rising dollar had dampened investors'
buying enthusiasm, although the market's environment was thought to
be improving.
   ``All the market needs right now is stable exchange rates and I
think stock prices will regain strength shortly,'' said a dealer at
Nikko Securities Co., who also asked his name not be used.
   Dealers said speculation over an interest rate hike also
discouraged investors in the stock market.
</TEXT>
