<HEAD>Chris Evert's Last Major Tournament Appearance Ends in Defeat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chris Evert's storybook career on the tennis
court is over without a storybook ending.
   She was defeated Tuesday in the quarterfinals of the U.S. Open by
Zina Garrison, 7-6, 6-2. She shook hands with Garrison and received
a standing ovation.
   The 34-year-old Evert will represent the United States in the
Federation Cup at Tokyo next month and will play in some
exhibitions, but she said this was her last appearance in a major
tournament.
   ``It's just playing a lot of matches in my career, I think that
has caught up to me,'' Evert said. ``Mentally, I cannot sustain that
intensity every single match.''
   The master of the two-handed backhand first made her mark by
reaching the semifinals at the U.S. Open in 1971, when she was 16.
Evert went on to win 18 Grand Slam titles _ six U.S. Opens, seven
French championships, three at Wimbledon and two Australian.
