<DOCNO> AP890906-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0521EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CouncilTrial     09-06 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Council Trial,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Leaders Testify in Dallas Voting Rights Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHIP BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black leaders told a judge that minorities in
Dallas have trouble gaining power within city government because the
election system is biased.
   Qualified black candidates typically have been beaten in city
council elections by whites ``because one face was black and the
other was white,'' Eddie Bernice Johnson, a state senator from
Dallas, testified Tuesday at the opening of a federal trial.
   Two unsuccessful black council candidates and an Hispanic group
have charged in a lawsuit that Dallas' apportionment system,
particularly the use of at-large districts, has resulted in the
underrepresentation of the minority community.
   The current council, governing a population estimated to be 51
percent minorities, consists of nine non-Hispanic whites and two
blacks.
   The plaintiffs are asking U.S. District Judge Jerry Buchmeyer to
order a restructuring. Voters approved a new structure last month
and some attorneys say the case jeopardizes the plan that was
approved overwhelmingly by voters.
   The plaintiffs would like the city to be apportioned in 15
single-member districts, their attorneys said.
   The city said the voters' right to pick their system of
government is at stake and its attorneys dispute charges that the
current system is discriminatory.
   ``In the last 14 elections, since 1983, the black preferred
candidate has been successful in nine races,'' Paul Pearce, an
attorney for the city, said during opening arguments.
   Johnson and state Rep. Fred Blair of Dallas criticized the use of
at-large districts, which they said sap the voting strength of
minorities.
   ``The at-large structure is a convenient way of maintaining
control of the city of Dallas. At-large council members don't make
themselves available to the concerns of the entire city,'' Blair
said.
   Last month, Dallas voters adopted a so-called 10-4-1 council
structure with 10 members elected from single districts, four from
quadrants or ``super'' districts and the mayor at-large.
   Pearce sought a dismissal of the case because the U.S. Justice
Department has not approved the plan. Buchmeyer rejected the motion,
saying he would not rule on the viability of the plan.
   Under Dallas' current system, eight members are elected from
single-member districts, and three, including the mayor, are elected
at-large.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0527EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-06 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Across Kansas, Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Warm, humid air from the Gulf of Mexico and an upper air
disturbance produced showers and thunderstorms today across Kansas
and parts of the middle Mississippi Valley.
   Some of the storms produced locally heavy rainfall that flooded
roads, low-lying areas and basements in northeast Kansas.
   A cold front pushed through the northern Plains and central
Rockies, and strong, gusty winds blew through western parts of the
Dakotas and Wyoming.
   A high wind warning was in effect for western South Dakota.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered in eastern New Mexico,
and along the Gulf and southern Atlantic coasts.
   Laredo, Texas, reached 100 degrees Tuesday, the 100th day this
year temperatures reached triple digits there. Phoenix has had 116
days of 100 degrees or higher this year and is closing in on its
record of 122 days set last year.
   The nation's high Tuesday was 114 degrees at Bullhead City,
Ariz., and Palm Springs, Calif.
   Warm weather continued today in much of Texas, which had
temperatures in the 80s, and in the desert Southwest where readings
were in the 80s or 90s.
   Cool temperatures were behind the front moving across the
northern Plains and the central Rockies. Early morning readings were
in the 40s and 50s.
   Crisp, cool weather with clear skies prevailed across eastern New
York state and much of New England where temperatures were in the
40s and 50s. Temperatures also were in the 50s along the Pacific
Coast. The remainder of the nation generally had early morning
readings in the 60s or 70s.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
