<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in early European trading today,
knocked down by comments by Bank of Japan officials during earlier
Asian trading, foreign currency dealers said.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   An unnamed Bank of Japan official was quoted as saying the
central bank is willing ``to do anything, anytime'' to stabilize
foreign exchange rates.
   Later remarks by Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita indicating
his desire to see the dollar below 140 yen put renewed pressure on
the currency, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 146.65 yen, unchanged from Tuesday. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 146.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.9789 West German marks, down from 1.9895
   _1.7065 Swiss francs, down from 1.7170
   _6.6710 French francs, down from 6.7055
   _2.2295 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2415
   _1,417.00 Italian lire, down from 1,425.50
   _1.1790 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1811
   The dollar fell against the pound in London. It cost $1.5485 to
buy one pound at midmorning, compared with $1.5385 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $359.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $358.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $360.00.
   The bid price in Zurich was also $360.00 a troy ounce compared
with $358.30 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.19 to close at a bid $360.47.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.09 a troy ounce,
up from Tuesday's $5.07.
