<FIRST>r a PM-SalemBombs     09-06 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salem Bombs,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Man Guilty of Planting Bombs Around Salem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ALBANY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury convicted a factory worker in a
failed plot to blow up Salem with 13 bombs that were planted around
the southern Indiana city last year.
   The U.S. District Court jury deliberated for a little more than
seven hours before finding Jerry A. Conrad, 42, of Salem guilty of
all 29 counts against him. He faces up to 285 years in prison.
   Defense attorney Michael McDaniel said he planned to appeal the
conviction.
   As he heard the verdict, Conrad slumped in his chair and his
mouth sagged. One juror wept.
   ``My husband is innocent, and this is not over,'' said the
defendant's wife, Rose Mary, as she left the courtroom.
   Conrad made no comment to reporters as federal marshals led him
from the courthouse.
   ``We were confident from the outset the jury would convict on all
29 counts,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Stanley Powell told
reporters. ``The evidence in this case was overwhelming.''
   U.S. District Judge Sarah Evans Barker set no sentencing date.
   McDaniel said Conrad probably would not be sentenced until after
the trial of John M. Hubbard III, also charged in the case.
Hubbard's trial is set for Oct. 2, and Conrad is expected to testify.
   Conrad and Hubbard, 31, also of Salem, were charged with 14
counts of making bombs, 13 counts of attempting to destroy bridges
and buildings used in interstate commerce, and one count each of
illegal possession of dynamite and conspiracy.
   The bombs were found stashed behind buildings and beneath bridges
July 5, 1988. The government contends they were placed in the
downtown area partly because of Hubbard's feeling of rivalry for
state Rep. Frank Newkirk Jr., who also is the son of Salem's mayor.
The largest bomb was found behind Newkirk's law office.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen make no mistake about it. These were bombs
that were meant to go off and were meant to cause death and
destruction,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Linda S. Chapman said in
closing arguments Tuesday.
   ``But for the grace of God, Salem would have been literally blown
off the map that day,'' she told the jury.
   Three of the bombs ignited and fizzled, but none exploded, and no
one was hurt.
   During the trial, the government described Conrad as a
survivalist who collected books on making explosives but suggested
no other motive for his role in the bomb incident.
</TEXT>
