<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0700EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NBC-Program     09-06 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NBC-Program,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Asks ABC-Owned Company to Produce Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC television has asked an ABC-owned production
company to create and produce a prime-time drama series. It would be
the first time one TV network has produced a show to run on a rival
network.
   The offer of the deal comes as federal regulations governing
television are being lifted, sparking changes in the traditional
network-studio relationship of television production, said Brandon
Stoddard, head of ABC Productions.
   Stoddard said he is considering the request by NBC for a drama
series that would air in a 10 p.m. slot, as well as a mini-series,
The New York Times reported in today's editions.
   Stoddard said he expected in five to seven years a ``network
studio system'' would develop in which the networks will produce
more of their programming.
   In 1990, a limit of five hours of prime-time programming produced
by the networks will be lifted. The new rules have prompted the
three networks to seek more of their own progamming.
   In the past, the major Hollywood-based production companies such
as Warner Brothers Inc., Universal and Paramount, produced the
majority of programming seen on television.
   Hollywood-based studios can reap high profits from syndicating
their programs. The networks have been prevented from taking a
percentage of the profits from the syndication sales.
   Congress has asked the networks and the studios to reach a
compromise.
</TEXT>
