<FIRST>r i PM-Netherlands-Election     09-06 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Netherlands-Election,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vote May Push Dutch Government to the Left</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Democrats 66 party is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch voted today in a
parliamentary election that was expected to return longtime Premier
Ruud Lubbers to power but force him to veer to the left in order to
form a government.
   Voter turnout appeared to be high in crisp autumn weather.
   In Amsterdam, polling stations reported that 22 percent of the
electorate had cast ballots within the first three hours after polls
opened. In Rotterdam, that figure was 15 percent.
   Lubbers, the nation's highly popular premier who has led the
government since 1982, was expected return to office for a third
term.
   But pre-election polls predicted that Lubbers, a centrist, may
have to turn to the opposition Labor Party to form a new coalition
government.
   That would result in a swing to the left that could herald an
easing of his seven-year program of austerity and fiscal reform.
   A last-minute opinion poll, conducted Tuesday night, indicated
that although Lubbers' Christian Democrats would win 56 seats in the
150-member Dutch parliament, up two from their current strength, his
right-wing liberal coalition partner would loose at least five of
its 27 seats.
   The poll by the Maurice de Hond polling organization predicted
that the leftist Labor Party will remain at 52 seats, while the
center-left Democrats 66 party was expected to win three seats on
top of their current nine.
   The Green Left, an environmentalist coalition of four left-wing
fringe parties, will jump from three to eight, according to the
telephone poll.
   Such results would make Labor the obvious coalition partner for
the Christian Democrats. Though Lubbers said this week that a Labor
victory would bring ``bad politics,'' he has not ruled out forming a
coalition with any group.
   Voting booths, where the 10-million-member electorate had a
choice of 22 parties, were scheduled to close at 7 p.m. (1 p.m.
EDT). The first election returns were expected about an hour later.
   Lubbers center-right government fell on May 2 in a dispute over
an ambitious plan to clean up the heavily polluted Dutch air, soil
and waterways by the year 2010. A general election had been
scheduled for May 1990.
</TEXT>
