<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--LesbianSlaying     09-06 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Lesbian Slaying,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Allows `Battered Spouse' Defense in Lesbian Murder Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman on trial for the slaying of
her lesbian lover will be allowed to use the ``battered spouse
syndrome'' as a defense, ruled a judge who said the type of
relationship makes no difference.
   ``It's a relationship among humans,'' Circuit Judge Tom Waddell
ruled Tuesday over prosecutors' objections that research on battered
women in lesbian cases is scant.
   Research on women battered by men could be applied to women
battered by women, Waddell said. ``I believe they are essentially
the same,'' he said. ``In other words, sex has nothing to do with
these problems.''
   The battered spouse syndrome has been used successfully by women
who killed their abusive male lovers.
   Annette Green, 30, admitted killing Ivonne Julio, her live-in
lover of 11 years, but said she had been beaten and tormented for
years.
   Neighbors, friends and co-workers testified Ms. Julio often beat
Ms. Green and inflicted broken bones, bruises and black eyes.
</TEXT>
