<SECOND>PM-Miracle Crash,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>14 Survive 70-Foot Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMPTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen people packed into a sedan, none
wearing a seatbelt, survived a 70-foot plunge into a rock quarry
after the car was forced off the road, police said.
   The car carrying three women and 11 children crashed through a
chain-link fense Monday night and landed upright at the bottom of
the quarry, said Detective Michael Markey.
   ``It's a miracle that nobody was seriously hurt,'' Markey said.
``I'm really surprised. The car didn't roll over either. It just
went down and landed on all four wheels.''
   Passenger Vanessa Burns, 34, suffered a broken ankle and jaw and
was in stable condition at Martin Luther King Jr.-Drew Medical
Center, spokeswoman Paula Wauls said.
   Nine other passengers were hospitalized in stable to fair
condition. Four children were treated and released.
   The children ranged in age from 9 months to 16 years.
   Witnesses said a car swerved in front of the Oldsmobile Delta 98
and caused it to plow through the fence at nearly 40 mph.
