<FIRST>u a PM-TeachersStrike     09-06 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teachers Strike,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Teachers On Strike, Nearly 150,000 Students Nationwide Affected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in two more Michigan districts walked picket lines
today, joining strikes that have idled nearly 150,000 students in
seven states.
   Pay and benefits were the major issues for the estimated 8,000
teachers across the nation on strike since early last week.
   In Michigan, teachers in four districts voted to walk out
Tuesday; two districts picketed on Tuesday and 310 teachers from the
other two marched today. In all, eight districts and 1,600 teachers
are on strike in Michigan.
   Strikes in 18 districts in Illinois, Michigan, Pennsylvania,
Washington, Montana, Ohio, and California have affected some 147,900
students.
   In the largest district on strike, Sacramento, Calif., the
teachers union said the the walkout could be long. Nearly 80 percent
of the 2,300 district employees represented by the union honored the
strike that began Tuesday.
   The teachers are seeking a 12.7 percent raise this year and 6.5
percent for last year.
   Teachers in Elgin voted to strike and officials called off
classes for today for about 27,000 students in the northern Illinois
district. Some 6,800 Quincy, Ill., students continued their summer
break in a week-long teachers walkout.
   In Montana's 12,500-student Great Falls district, negotiators
scheduled their first bargaining session in more than a week today.
But a negotiator for the district said the two sides are ``miles
apart'' on salaries.
   Classes were canceled today for 2,300 Bristol, R.I., students as
teachers gathered to decide whether to launch the state's first
teacher strike in three years.
   In Massachusetts, teachers in Everett voted to strike on the
verge of the 1989 school year.
   Their counterparts in Chelsea agreed to an unusual six-month
contract with Boston University, which will run the schools in the
city outside Boston under an unprecedented arrangement approved by
the Legislature earlier this year.
   Teachers in at least 30 Massachusetts cities and towns are still
without contracts as schools prepare to open over the next 10 days.
</TEXT>
