<FIRST>u i PM-Brazil-Plane 1stLd-Writethru a0434 09-06 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Plane, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0434,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors of Plane Crash Taken From Jungle, One More Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with evacuation under way, one survivor
dying en route, quotes from mother of survivor. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue teams today began evacuating
survivors from a domestic jetliner that crashed three days ago in
thick Amazon jungle, killing nine of the 54 people aboard, an air
force spokesman said.
   A woman airlifted from the wreckage of the Varig airlines jet
died en route to Brasilia, said spokesman Col. Jose Maria dos Santos
said in Brasilia.
   Santos said an air force helicopter was ferrying 41 survivors
from the crash site to a ranch near Sao Jose do Xingu, in
north-central Mato Grosso state 1,050 miles northwest of Rio de
Janeiro.
   ``We've got 11 in the air and 30 more at the site, but we'll get
them all out today,'' Santos said by telephone.
   On Tuesday, four survivors walked hours through the jungle to the
ranch and radioed for help. Searchers had been unable to locate the
plane or to confirm the crash since the Boeing 737 went down Sunday.
   The jungle prevented the helicopter from landing at the crash
site, Santos said. He said it had to hover over the wreckage while
victims were raised by winch.
   ``The plane opened a clearing in the jungle when it crashed, but
it's not big enough for the helicopter to land,'' the spokesman said.
   A 3-year-old girl, identified as Bruna Costa, was flown out with
a concussion and a crushed leg, he said.
   The girl's mother, Marinez Coimbra, said those killed were mostly
sitting in the front of the plane.
   ``Those in the front suffered the worst,'' Mrs. Coimbra said in a
live televised interview from Brasila.
   The survivors were taken to the Curumare ranch, 28 miles away,
where a Brazilian-made, twin-engine Bandeirante plane took off from
a dirt airstrip and flew to the Serra do Cachimbo Air Force Base,
185 miles away in neighboring Para state, Santos said.
   From the Air Force base, the survivors would be flown to
Brasilia, he said.
   Medical teams first reached the crash site late Tuesday night,
but officials decided to wait until today to start removing
survivors. The Air Force parachuted in kits of food, water and
medicine.
   Officials said the survivors, including the four who walked out,
were generally in good condition.
   The plane disappeared Sunday on the last leg of a regularly
scheduled flight between the southeastern city of Sao Paulo and
Belem.
   Varig, the national carrier, said there were six crew members on
the flight and all survived. It said the crew and all of the
passengers on the domestic flight were Brazilians, it had no
information about the people who died.
   A television camerman aboard a search plane took some footage of
the crash site, but visibility was poor because of smoke from
burning brush fires and fog. The fuselage appeared to be intact, and
it was not clear if the plane may have landed in an area cleared by
ranchers.
   Air Force Ministry spokesman Col. Ronaldo Borges said the pilot
had reported problems in the navigational system Sunday, and plane
strayed far off course. Two hours after his scheduled arrival in
Belem, he radioed the airport at Carajas, 600 miles from Belem,
asking for permission to make an emergency landing.
   Ten minutes later, a Cruzeiro airline plane received the Varig
pilot's final message, saying he was running out of fuel, only one
engine was working and he would make an emergency landing in the
jungle, Borges said.
</TEXT>
