<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SchoolDrugTests     09-06 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Drug Tests,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>School District Limits Drug-Test Plans to Athletes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLOSSMOOR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school board has dropped a plan to
give random drug tests to all high school students in
extracurricular activities _ from the band to the math club _ and
decided to screen only athletes.
   More than 100 parents and students packed the board room Tuesday
night for the three-hour debate on amending the testing policy in
the Chicago suburb. Some parents complained about the cost of
widespread testing.
   The Homewood-Flossmoor School Board voted 5-2 to restrict the
tests to athletes. The board is expected to decide in two weeks how
to conduct the tests.
   Three weeks ago, the board adopted a policy that would have
tested every high school student in extracurricular activities. The
district's high school has 2,100 students; 1,500 were in
interscholastic activities last year.
   Superintendent Ed Rachford had said that all students
representing the school in after-school activities should be subject
to drug testing.
   Board member Robert Butler, who offered the amendment restricting
the tests, said limiting the tests to athletes would face less of a
constitutional challenge than widespread testing of many students.
   A federal appeals court last year unanimously ruled that a high
school near Lafayette, Ind., could randomly test athletes. Only a
handful of high schools across the country test athletes for drugs.
</TEXT>
