<FIRST>r w PM-US-Iran     09-06 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Iran,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Urge Tough U.S. Stand Toward Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 200 House members are asking Secretary
of State James A. Baker III to abandon the Bush administration's
hopes for a moderate leadership in Iran and recognize instead
Iranian resistance groups seeking to topple the government.
   In a letter initiated by Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., the
lawmakers also called on the administration to work with its allies
and impose an arms and oil boycott against Iran.
   President Bush has taken a conciliatory tone toward the new
government that took power in Iran following the death earlier this
year of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. Bush has sent messages to newly
elected President Hashemi Rafsanjani saying Iran could end its
international isolation by releasing the eight Americans held
hostage by Iranian-backed militants in Lebanon.
   But the congressional letter, signed by 121 Democrats and 65
Republicans, warned the administration against ``continuing to
speculate and hope for the miraculous emergence of moderates from
within the present ruling clique.''
   It said ``those who have been identified as moderates, including
... Rafsanjani ... have continued the repressive policies of
Khomeini.''
   The lawmakers said it remains the responsibility of the Iranian
people, including the opposition group People's Mujahedeen of Iran,
to ``bring about change and a new order in Iran.''
