<SECOND>PM-BRF--Train Derailment,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>500 Residents Evacuated After Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RISON, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train carrying hazardous material derailed
and caught fire today, prompting the evacuation of about 500 people,
officials said.
   Five Cotton Belt Railroad cars jumped the tracks about 5:15 a.m.,
said Ray Briggler of the state Office of Emergency Services. The
sheriff's office said two cars caught fire. A column of black smoke
rose above the city.
   One burning car was hauling acetic acid, a flammable liquid used
as a food additive and in the production of petroleum products,
officials said.
   One person, believed to part of the train crew, was injured,
officials said. The extent of the injuries were not immediately
known.
   People living within a half-mile of the accident were moved from
their homes in this city of about 1,300 south of Little Rock,
Briggler said.
