<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru   09-06 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0541,0911</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Injures 4 in Medellin, Restrictions Imposed in Bogota</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 8-16 pvs, `The restaurant...Carlos Galan.' with 9
grafs to ADD quotes from one of injured, details on bomb. Pickup 17th,
`As part....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded at a restaurant in the
drug trafficking center of Medellin, and police said today that four
people were injured, including two American journalists.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the blast Tuesday
night, but drug lords recently declared war on the government after
it began cracking down on the traffickers for a string of bombings
and assassinations.
   Earlier Tuesday, two bombs exploded at banks in central Medellin,
injuring seven people, the radio network Caracol reported.
   In Bogota on Tuesday, the mayor banned large public gatherings,
fearing terrorist attacks by drug gangs trying to halt the
U.S.-backed crackdown, which police say has virtually paralyzed
Colombia's cocaine-producing labs.
   In Washington Tuesday night, President Bush declared war on drug
traffickers and users and praised the Colombian government's
2{-week-old offensive against the world's most powerful drug barons,
who are responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the
United States.
   The speech was broadcast live in Colombia.
   Also Tuesday, an army colonel's wife was shot to death on a
Bogota street, but police said it was not clear if the killing was
related to the campaign against the cocaine cartels.
   The restaurant bombing in Medellin occurred 9 p.m. Tuesday at the
Bella Epoca. It injured reporter Bernardette Pardo and cameraman
Carlos Ignacio Corrales, who work for the Miami-based,
Spanish-language station WLTV and for the Spanish language network
Univision. Both are U.S. citizens.
   Also injured were Jorge Saenz, an independent Colombian reporter
and documentary film maker, and his wife, Angela. Saenz was working
for Ms. Pardo as a local producer and assistant.
   Ms. Pardo said in a telephone interview from her hospital bed in
Medellin today that she had a broken shoulder blade, fractured
vertebrae and facial cuts.
   Corrales suffered a gash on the head, and the Saenzes suffered
bruises, she said.
   Ms. Pardo, a native of Cuba, said she and other injury victims
were sitting at a table on the restaurant's terrace when the bomb
exploded in the restaurant's bathroom.
   ``One minute we're sitting there. The next minute we're blown on
the floor. Everything fell on us,'' she said.
   She said police suspected a couple who had been in the restaurant
may have planted the bomb, she said. The couple left before the
explosion, she said.
   Police said the bomb was made of about 22 pounds of dynamite.
   President Virgilio Barco launched the anti-narcotics offensive on
Aug. 18 in response to the assassinations of a judge, a police
colonel and a highly popular presidential candidate, Luis Carlos
Galan.
   As part of the campaign, Barco revived extradition to the United
States, which had been nullified by Colombian Supreme Court rulings
in 1987 and 1989. In Bogota, the national capital and the most
populous Colombian city, Mayor Andres Pastrana on Tuesday decreed a
ban on public marches and demonstrations as a safety measure.
   ``The public order of the country, as well as that of the capital
of the republic, has been notoriously threatened in recent days,
putting the citizenry in imminent danger,'' said his decree. It
established a 60-day jail term and a fine of $150 for violators.
   About 6 million of the country's 30 million people live in
metropolitan Bogota.
   On Saturday, a powerful bomb blast injured 80 people and
destroyed the offices of El Espectador, a prominent Bogota daily
that has crusaded against drug trafficking. There have been almost
daily bombings and other attacks, most of them in Medellin, by drug
traffickers who declared ``total and absolute war'' in response to
the government crackdown.
   A nightime curfew has been in effect since last Wednesday in
Medellin, 150 miles north of Bogota.
   The National Police said Tuesday that since the crackdown began,
cocaine production in Colombia has practically stopped and that
prices should go up as a result. Authorities say they have destroyed
252 cocaine labs this year.
   The Bogota daily El Tiempo, citing unidentified police sources,
on Tuesday forecast a cocaine shortage in the United States. It also
said 2.2 pounds of cocaine, which now costs $1,500 in Colombia and
$10,000 wholesale in Miami, would go up in price ``considerably'' in
coming months.
   The government's offensive has included the seizure of drug
traffickers' mansions, office buildings and other real estate and a
fortune in helicopters, airplanes, cars, racehorses and other goods.
   The United States has responded by allocating $65 million in
military aid, including two C-130 transport planes, eight A-37
observation and attack jets and five UH-1H ``Huey'' helicopters
already delivered to Colombian anti-narcotics forces.
   According to a U.S. Embassy communique, more gear will arrive in
coming weeks.
   In his drug speech, Bush proposed spending $7.9 billion to fight
the drug problem. That money would include a fourfold increase in
the amount of military and law enforcement aid for Colombia, Bolivia
and Peru, to $261.2 million in 1990.
   He called it the downpayment on a $2 billion, five-year anti-drug
program in the Andean region.
   Bush also said he and Barco hoped to convene a summit to
``coordinate an inter-American strategy against the cartels.''
</TEXT>
