<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   09-06 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: as you go.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 2
   The Phoenix Gazette on education:
   If American University president Richard Berendzen's view of the
future is accurate, we are at a zenith in educational attainment.
How's that for a scary thought?
   At his annual back-to-school breakfast with reporters at the
National Press Club in Washington, D.C., recently, Berendzen
predicted declining college achievement standards for the 1990s and
beyond.
   He relates plunging standards to demographic trends and fierce
competition for high school graduates: ``Starting in 1993 the number
of 18-year-olds will rise ... but 80 percent of the increase will be
students who are black, Hispanic or Asian,'' he said.
   According to Berendzen, the real growth industry will be in the
community colleges, most of which will be providing remedial
education.
   Unfortunately, educators' repeated recitations of the link
between ethnicity, income and poor achievement doesn't contribute
anything that isn't already known.
   John H. Bunzel, president of San Jose State University, writing
in the The Wall Street Journal, suggests that schools stop focusing
on what is outside of their control and instead ``concentrate on
what should be their primary mission: strong instructional
leadership that will foster the academic preparation and performance
of students.''
   Unless public education is restructured to permit all parents,
not just wealthy ones, to choose schools that fit that description,
Berendzen's dismal prediction is almost certain to come true.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31
   Kennebec Journal, Augusta, Maine, on ambassadorial appointments:
   Should President Bush have named as ambassador to Spain a Florida
real estate developer who donated at least $100,000 to Bush's
presidential campaign _ but doesn't know beans about Spain?
   More than any recent president, Bush has rewarded wealthy
campaign donors with lengthy stays abroad. Of the 44 ambassadorships
he has filled so far, only 14 went to career diplomats, rather than
political appointees _ less than a third.
   By contrast, even Ronald Reagan, profoundly suspicious of federal
bureaucrats, and the State Department in particular, appointed about
65 percent from career civil servants.
   Not that ambassadors chosen from other fields don't sometimes do
a fine job. They do. But ability is important. There's a big
difference between an oil baron who'd like to live abroad and David
Bruce or Mike Mansfield _ to name two superb diplomats who came from
outside the State Department ....
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 4
   The Philadelphia Inquirer on President Bush's ambassadors:
   President Bush has doled out ambassadorships to so many cronies
that it's hard to single out someone as the least qualified. Former
Sen. Chic Hecht, who once argued that Nevada shouldn't get a
``nuclear waste suppository,'' liked being sent to the Bahamas
because of the golf links there.
   Then there's Peter F. Secchia, a building supply executive and
GOP stalwart, who kicked off his tour of duty as ambassador in Rome
with a little joke. The new Italian navy, he said, has
glass-bottomed boats _ so it can see the old Italian navy.
   Still, the most embarrassing nomination may be that of developer
Joseph Zappala, who gave the GOP more than $100,000, to be the main
man in Spain. A foreign affairs neophyte, he knows little about
Spain. Mr. Zappala can't even speak Spanish.
   Yet, unless the Senate says no, he might still be in the job in
1992 _ when Spain and the United States will honor the 500th
anniversary of Christopher Columbus' voyage to the New World. That's
when this envoy could turn to a translator, or a phrase book, to
toast U.S.-Spanish relations.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 30
   Burlington County Times, Willingboro, N.J., on cost of the U.S.
Capitol Police:
   The U.S. Capitol Police, whose sole mission is to protect House
and Senate members and their staffs, will cost almost $60 million
next year.
   One wasteful feature is that the House and Senate branches of the
police force are administratively separate, with different pay
scales. But efforts to unify the two forces have been frustrated by
a clash between the House and Senate sergeants-at-arms. Neither
wants to relinquish control over personnel.
   This is one problem Congress cannot blame on the White House, and
it naturally raises a question. If they cannot handle a management
challenge of the sort that every mayor or city council takes for
granted, why should we trust their judgmemt on harder issues?
</TEXT>
