<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   09-06 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0852</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: harder issues?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31
   Philadelphia Daily News on baby boomers and the Rolling Stones:
   Rolling Stones Mick Jagger and Keith Richards probably have
gathered a bit of moss. And Jerry Garcia's Grateful Dead ought to be
_ grateful, that is.
   But they are the hottest tickets in the oddly nostalgic world of
rock and roll. When word got around about a return tour for The Who,
we asked: Where? When?
   Why?
   For the same reason sports fans step over today's leading golfers
to join Arnie's Army or to follow Jack Nicklaus, for the same reason
they stay away from the fights until Ray Leonard or Roberto Duran
laces up the gloves.
   Because the baby boomers, who outnumber any other living
generation, make the decisions about what's worth paying for.
   And those who used to distrust anybody over 30 now cast a
jaundiced eye toward anyone who doesn't have at least an occasional
use for liniment.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 1
   The Sun, Bremerton, Wash., on the Soviet economy:
   In the latest of several developments that threaten perestroika,
the Moscow city government has decided to bar non-residents from
buying items such as clothing from the Soviet capital's stores, due
to scarcities.
   That is far more serious than it might seem. Relatively speaking,
Moscow has long been an oasis in the desert of Soviet consumer
goods. Every week, hundreds of thousands of shoppers from elsewhere
have flocked there in search of meat, refrigerators and other
merchandise they cannot find in their hometown stores.
   In effect, the Soviets are moving toward internal protectionism.
This protectionism mirrors a new trend among other Warsaw Pact
countries, which are making it harder for each other's tourists to
take scarce goods home. Czechoslovakia and East Germany, for
example, recently outlawed foreign purchases of food and toilet
paper; the Soviets responded with their own ban on exports of
refrigerators and caviar.
   Whatever its immediate advantages for particular groups, in the
long run such protectionism will inevitably make the Eastern bloc's
economic woes even worse. Thoughtful Soviets realize this: The
government newspaper Izvestia strongly denounced Moscow's new
shopping rules.
   Gorbachev's entire reform agenda is in danger unless he can turn
the economy around. The only way to do that is to move far more
boldly toward a free market, not further away.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31
   Bangor (Maine) Daily News on the Polish economy:
   ... Poland, ironically, is back where it was a half-century ago,
the object of bargaining between East and West. The new Poland
cannot survive on the meager financial aid package offered by
President George Bush; but the United States and Europe, which must
be ready to make a substantial infusion of funds into the Polish
economy, cannot do so now out of self-interest. It must be clear
that public opinion will acknowledge Solidarity as the victor if the
new Polish government slays its economic monster. The credit cannot
go to the discredited and politically bankrupt communists in the
coalition.
   Like their countrymen in the lines outside the bakeries, the
Polish people will have to wait. It is difficult to ask for further
patience from people who have suffered and sacrificed for three
generations. But this time there is genuine reason for hope and gain
in the crumbling of the Soviet empire.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 5
   The Milwaukee Journal on Fawn Hall:
   If the student association at Marquette University wanted to
squander $3,500 to hear Fawn Hall last Thursday give her
unenlightened version of the Iran-Contra scandal, that's their
business. But we have to wonder why undergraduates whose fees
support the Associated Students organization didn't rise up in
protest. Or were they just momentarily blinded by Hall's star status?
   And why did the student group roll over and play dead to the
demand by Hall, herself a media creation, that the news media be
kept out of the event? The ban _ a part of Hall's standard contract
for all speaking engagements _ didn't work very well at Marquette
anyway. Print journalists got in easily and even a television
reporter managed to hurl a loaded question at the
secretary-turned-celebrity before he was thrown out. Cynics might
think that the press restrictions were part of a clever plot by
Hall's handlers to generate still more news coverage of her
appearances.
   The real marvel is that there was an audience for the woman who
typed, filed and shredded for Lt. Col. Oliver North, the convicted
Contragater. She shed absolutely no light on the arms-for-hostages
debacle. She offered her same tired defenses of North's illegal
actions. And she showed a continuing contempt for the role of
Congress in setting foreign policy.
   Clearly, Fawn Hall's audiences don't come to hear a reasoned
analysis of national security issues. They come because: (1) She is
blond, leggy and attractive; and (2) notoriety sells. When Hall's 15
minutes of fame have expired, what will she and her fans do for an
encore?
</TEXT>
