<FIRST>u w PM-BeachRiot 1stLd-Writethru a0493 09-06 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beach Riot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0574 to correct category code to W sted A</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede VIRGINIA BEACH</HEAD>
<HEAD>Justice Department Opens Criminal Probe of Police Conduct</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Justice Department opening investigation;
picks up at pvs 2nd graf,``I have;'' other editing changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department today opened a criminal
investigation of allegations that law enforcement officers committed
civil rights violations while quelling a weekend riot at Virginia
Beach, Va.
   A department spokeswoman, Deborah Burstion-Wade, said the FBI had
received two complaints from civilians who were in Virginia Beach,
the scene of rioting among a crowd of 100,000 youths over the Labor
Day weekend.
   Police and National Guard troops used clubs to disperse the
crowds, which largely consisted of students from predominantly black
East Coast colleges.
   Burstion-Wade said the FBI and the department's civil rights
division had formally opened a criminal investigation into possible
deprivation of civil rights.
   The spokeswoman said she couldn't provide specific information
about the two complaints against law enforcement officers that were
filed today with the FBI.
   The Justice Department was continuing to review published
accounts and videotapes of police and National Guard troops clashing
with the rioters, she said.
   Virginia Beach's mayor said earlier that she welcomed a federal
investigation into how the city handled the disturbances.
   ``I have nothing to fear in this city being open to scrutiny,''
Mayor Meyera E. Oberndorf said Tuesday. ``We want the opportunity to
have our name cleared.''
   Other city officials joined the mayor in supporting the police.
   According to perliminary counts, 1,235 people were charged with
1,346 offenses. Most of the charges involved disorderly conduct,
traffic offenses and public drinking.
   The rioters early Sunday and Sunday night were mostly black
college students attending the annual end-of-summer Greekfest. At
least 43 people were injured, including 30 police officers or
National Guardsmen.
   ``These statistics do not even begin to tell the story. When
you're in the middle of a riot, you don't have time to make arrests.
Your main concern is to get the streets secured,'' said Police Chief
Charles R. Wall.
   ``These officers were exposed to an extreme situation,'' City
Manager Aubrey V. Watts Jr. said. ``It's incredible that they were
able to restore law and order without firing a single shot or using
fatal force.''
   Watts said a city team will evaluate the millions of dollars in
damage, much of it attributed to looting, caused by a crowd of about
100,000 young people who attended the annual event known as
Greekfest. He also said he will gather reports from police, fire and
emergency personnel.
   Sen. John W. Warner, R-Va., said he has alerted the U.S. Small
Business Administration to be ready to process requests for disaster
aid from more than 100 businesses damaged.
   Merchants and innkeepers said they would meet to discuss how to
avoid similar problems at next year's Greekfest.
   ``You can't do a whole lot,'' said Rick Kowalewitch, owner of
RK's Windsurf Shop on 17th Street. ``No matter what we do we look
like a racist.''
   Many of the young people who were chased off the streets by
police were black, but Kowalewitch said he and other whites were
ordered around by police as well.
   Greekfest participants were divided about whether they would
return.
   Brad Williams, 23, of White Plains, N.Y., said he has enjoyed the
gathering for five years and will come back.
   Muriel Steptoe, 26, and Alicia Dailey, 25, of Springfield, Mass.,
said they would not return because of the disturbance this year.
   ``If anybody comes back next year I think it will be the ones who
want to make trouble,'' Ms. Steptoe said.
</TEXT>
