<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CelebrityTapes     09-06 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Celebrity Tapes,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted In Tax Scam Featuring Celebrity Voices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of cheating investors out
of $12.6 million in a tax-shelter scheme featuring audio tapes made
by baseball manager Tommy Lasorda, singer Pat Boone and actor
Vincent Price.
   Johnathan D'Orio, 41, of Akron, Ohio, was found guilty Tuesday in
federal court of tax fraud, mail fraud and conspiracy.
   D'Orio told investors that for $10,000 they could take part in a
program allowing them to take 10 percent of the tapes' value off
their taxable income, resulting in a write-off of at least $18,000,
said Assistant U.S. Attorney David Katz.
   About 1,150 investors were bilked out of $12.6 million and the
government was cheated out of $20 million in taxes, Katz said.
   Lasorda, Price and Boone testified they were paid $10,000 to
$15,000, plus $250 per tape, to make recordings. Lasorda, manager of
the Los Angeles Dodgers, made tapes on baseball strategy, Price made
cooking tapes and Boone recorded nursery rhymes.
   Katz said the celebrities had no idea their status was being used
to cheat unsuspecting investors.
</TEXT>
