<FIRST>u a PM-HurricaneGabrielle 3rdLd-Writethru a0527 09-06 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hurricane Gabrielle, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0527,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giant Storm Passes Caribbean, Aims For Bermuda</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with noon advisory. PICKS UP 8th
graf pvs, `Early today ...'; SUBS last graf with UPDATE on Felix. </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gabrielle churned toward Bermuda and the
East Coast with winds of 135 mph today, raising 10-foot swells up to
1,300 miles away on North Carolina's Outer Banks.
   Gabrielle's 500-mile wide spiral bypassed the Caribbean and was
expected to reach Bermuda by Friday or Saturday. The island got
15-foot swells today.
   Already the Atlantic season's biggest hurricane, it was upgraded
Tuesday evening to a Category 4 hurricane, with 5 the strongest.
   An Air Force reconnaissance plane flew over Gabrielle late
Tuesday and reported rising barometric pressure and a slightly
expanding eye in the hurricane, signs that strengthening could be
unlikely, forecasters said.
   But early today, Gabrielle's pressure decreased slightly and its
eye constricted again.
   As of noon, Gabrielle was centered near 24 north latitude and 59
west longitude, 610 miles south-southeast of Bermuda. It was moving
north-northwest at 12 mph and was expected to take a more northerly
course in the next 24 hours.
   Early today, a buoy on the Outer Banks recorded 10-foot swells
from the distant hurricane, said hurricane specialist Jim Gross.
   While it was uncertain how close Gabrielle would come to Bermuda,
its considerable size prompted forecasters to advise residents of
the island and the East Coast to monitor it closely.
   Forecasters said the storm rivaled last year's record-setting
Hurricane Gilbert at the same stage but was on a path more like
1985's powerful Hurricane Gloria, which did $900 million in damage
as it raced up the East Coast.
   Gilbert's winds reached more than 155 mph and had the lowest
central pressure measured this century at 888 millibars. Central
pressure governs wind intensity. Gilbert was ranked Category 5.
Gabrielle's pressure increased from 942 millibars to 945 millibars
late Tuesday.
   While Gilbert stayed on a westerly course across the upper
Caribbean, devastating Jamaica and landing in Mexico, Gabrielle
dodged past the Caribbean and headed up into the Atlantic.
   Gloria roared up the Atlantic in the fall of 1985 at an unusually
fast 30 to 50 mph, panicking thousands of East Coast residents. But
its winds dropped from 150 mph to minimal hurricane strength by the
time it reached land.
   In Barbados, the easternmost Caribbean island 550 miles southeast
of Puerto Rico, Gabrielle's tail caused 10-foot waves and some
flooding in beachfront homes and businesses in the capital of
Bridgetown. No injuries or serious damage were reported.
   Far to the north, meanwhile, Hurricane Felix's winds were 85 mph.
   Little strengthening was expected for Felix, which posed no
threat to land. At noon, its center was near 37 north latitude and
48 west longitude, or 910 miles west of the Azores. It was drifting
to the north-northeast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
