<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-US 4thLd-Writethru a0544 09-06 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-US, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0544,0960</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Diplomats Leave Lebanon After Protests at Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to ADD that it's first time U.S. ambassador
pulled from Lebanon, subs 11-12th graf, `In Washington...in Lebanon.' with
2 grafs to ADD diplomats to return to the U.S. Pickup 13th graf, `The U.S....'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy and his
staff were evacuated today from Lebanon after hundreds of Christians
besieged the embassy in a protest to demand action against Syria.
   It was the first time Washington has pulled its ambassador out of
Lebanon, despite 14 years of civil war.
   The 30 diplomats left because ``deteriorating local circumstances
... no longer permitted the embassy to function effectively,'' said
Keith Peterson, a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Nicosia.
   The sudden decision to pull out of Lebanon, where Christian
forces and Syrian troops have been battling for six months, came
after hundreds of angry Christians surrounded the embassy compound
Tuesday.
   The protesters at the embassy in the Beirut suburb of Aoukar
dispersed several hours after McCarthy's departure today. But they
said in a statement they would besiege the compound again if the
ambassador returns.
   The Christian army leader, Gen. Michel Aoun, said in a statement
released by his office: ``It seems the American Cain couldn't endure
the stare of the Lebanese Abel so he left.'' Aoun has repeatedly
criticized the United States for failing to help the Christians in
their battle with the Syrians.
   The withdrawal of American diplomats represents the latest
setback for U.S. policy in Lebanon. On April 18, 1983, a bomb at the
U.S. Embassy killed at least 49 people while the United States was
involved in talks to arrange a withdrawal of foreign forces from
Lebanon.
   On Oct. 23, 1983, suicide bombers rammed trucks packed with
explosives into Marine and French peacekeeper posts, killing 241
Americans and 58 French. In February 1984, the U.S. Marines force
was withdrawn from Lebanon.
   In addition, eight of 16 Western hostages held by pro-Iranian
extremists in Lebanon are American. The longest-held is Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   In today's embassy evacuation, the ambassador and 29 American
staff were flown by helicopter to a British sovereign base in Cyprus.
   Three hours later, they took off aboard a military aircraft for
Italy, informed sources said. The sources, who insisted on not being
identified further, said the DC-9 aircraft departed at noon (5 a.m.
EDT) from the Akrotiri base in southern Cyprus bound for a NATO
military base in Sigonella, Sicily.
   In Washington, however, State Department spokesman Mark Dillen
said the diplomats would travel to a U.S. base in West Germany later
today. Officials said they would then head back to the United States
in a day or two.
   Dillen added, ``The evacuation does not represent a diminution of
our intention to try to help Lebanon.'' He said the United States
would work with Arab states, European allies, the Soviet Union, and
countries of the region on achieving a cease-fire, an end to
blockades of Lebanese ports, and political reconciliation in Lebanon.
   The U.S. Embassy is in the country's Christian enclave, where
about 1 million Christians have been trapped for six months, ringed
by the hostile Syrians and their allies and angry that the West has
not come to their rescue.
   One source said the helicopters airlifted McCarthy and the
diplomats from the embassy compound _ not from any of the regular
Lebanese army air bases in the Christian heartland.
   A diplomatic source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the British Embassy in Beirut was informed of the decision to
evacuate the American embassy staff Tuesday night.
   The Foreign Office in London said its diplomats had no immediate
plans to follow suit. About 15 British Embassy staff are in Beirut.
   A Lebanese army spokesman, who also spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the Americans had notified Aoun of their ``intention
to leave.''
   The Christians besieging the embassy compound were angry at the
United States for not coming to their aid against the Syrian army
and its Moslem allies since hostilities began March 8. Fighting
between the factions has since claimed the lives of 827 people and
wounded 2,452.
   The crowd went into a frenzy Tuesday, shouting ``McCarthy Go
Home'' and waving placards and posters denouncing America.
   Christian sources said the embassy siege was designed by Aoun to
whip up anti-American sentiment among Christians inside and outside
Lebanon, to bring pressure on the United States.
   The demonstrators had demanded that McCarthy submit his
credentials to ``the legitimate Lebanese authorities represented by
General Aoun'' and official U.S. recognition of Aoun's authority.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, is competing
for legitimacy with Aoun's three-member Christian Cabinet.
   McCarthy took up his post in September 1988 after the emergence
of the dual government and has not submitted his credentials to
either Cabinet. He has publicly criticized Syria for not responding
to a U.S. request to negotiate with Aoun, but Aoun has charged that
Washington is not pushing Syria hard enough.
   The Christian enclave has taken a fearful pounding from Syrian
artillery since March, when Aoun launched his self-proclaimed ``war
of liberation'' to force the Syrians to withdraw their 40,000 troops
in Lebanon.
   Even though his forces are outnumbered and outgunned, his
objective appeared to be to mobilize U.S. and European support for
the Christians.
   That startegy has failed. Washington has made sympathetic noises,
but has made it clear it has no intention of getting drawn into the
Lebanese quagmire again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
