<FIRST>r i AM-Soweto     09-06 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soweto,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soweto Marks Elections With Quiet Day of Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most populous city in South
Africa was quiet on election day.
   As the morning sun burned off the coal-smoke haze covering
Soweto, the township of 2.5 million blacks substituted its usual
weekday bustle for a day of silent protest Wednesday.
   The huge taxi depot near Baragwanath Hospital, where thousands
catch minibus taxis into Johannesburg each day, was nearly empty. A
wind sent swirls of dust across a deserted parking lot that normally
overflows with commuters.
   ``I'm not going to work for political reasons,'' said Martin
Mika, a salesman for the South African Breweries.
   Mika joined hundreds of thousands of blacks in a general strike
Tuesday and Wednesday to protest the segregated parliamentary
elections that exclude the black majority.
   No formal protest rallies were planned, but Soweto schools,
frequently the site of militant protest, were closed, as were most
stores. The Sowetan newspaper, the country's largest black-oriented
daily, did not publish.
   Taxi driver Fred Sadike estimated that only 20 percent of the
taxis, the primary means of transportation for most urban blacks,
were operating Wednesday. Most were traveling only inside the
township, not going to Johannesburg, he said.
   Sadike said he believed the election promise made by Acting
President F.W. de Klerk, who pledged to bring blacks into the
national government on a limited basis within five years.
   ``I think we'll be able to vote someday, but I don't know when,''
said Sadike, 32. ``I'd like to vote for the ANC,'' he said,
referring to the African National Congress guerrilla group.
   Blacks, who account for 28 million of the country's 37 million
people, are allowed to vote only in municipal elections or in the 10
tribal territories. Soweto blacks routinely boycott the local polls,
saying the candidates are collaborators with the white-led
government.
   In mixed-race and Indian townships, where residents can vote for
segregated houses of Parliament, those boycotting the polls
outnumbered those who cast ballots.
   In the Indian township of Lenasia, activists burned an effigy of
de Klerk on Tuesday night. ``Don't Vote'' signs vied for space on
light poles with campaign posters.
   ``I voted because the candidate promised to help get me a
house,'' said an Indian grocery store owner in Lenasia, who refused
to give his name. ``But I don't think too many people care who wins,
because the Indians don't have any real power.''
</TEXT>
