<SECOND>AM-BRF--Liquor Scare,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Popular Gin Drink Withdrawn After Poison Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state-owned liquor store chain said
Wednesday it removed all bottles of a popular gin and grapefruit
drink from its self-service stores after an extortion attempt by
someone who claimed to have put poison in bottles.
   Ilkka Kaski of the sales division of the Alko chain said tens of
thousands of Gin Long Drink bottles were taken off the shelves in
the 51 stores immediately after the threat Tuesday.
   An anonymous telephone caller claimed he had put poisoned bottles
on a shelf of a self-service store and would retrieve them in
exchange for an undisclosed sum of money.
   Alko holds a monopoly on liquor sales in Finland.
   ``This is the first time such a thing has happened in the history
of Alko. We took it very seriously indeed,'' Kaski told The
Associated Press.
   Gin Long Drink is one of Alko's best-selling items, with 60
million bottles sold last year.
