<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cuba-Crash     09-06 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Crash,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wind Given as Factor in Crash, Deaths Raised to 170</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban airliner that crashed on takeoff and
killed 170 people was buffeted by powerful winds from a thunderstorm
just before it plunged into a Havana suburb, Cuban news reports said
today.
   Of 126 people aboard the chartered Cubana de Aviacion plane, only
one survived. The plane carried mostly Italians returning from
vacation.
   Forty-five people were killed on the ground in the suburb of
Boyeros, a half mile from the airport, according to the Cuban
official news agency Prensa Latina monitored in Mexico City. Earlier
reports said 25 died on the ground.
   Dozens of people were injured, many critically.
   The Soviet-made Ilyushin 62 crashed moments after takeoff from
Havana in a thunderstorm Sunday night, destroying two square blocks
of homes in Boyeros.
   In a preliminary report, a Cuban government commission said that
at the time of the disaster, there was ``an abrupt worsening of the
meteorological conditions, which produced strong upward and downward
wind currents at low altitudes near the end of the runway,'' Prensa
Latina said.
   It quoted Gen. Rogelio Acevedo, head of the commission and
president of Civil Aeronautics Institute, as saying the information
came from two flight data recorders recovered from the plane.
   Carlo Civiletti, the Italian ambassador to Cuba, said
investigators were trying to determine whether the crash was due to
windshear, reports in Rome said. It was not clear if the Cuban news
reports were talking about drafts that would be defined as windshear.
   Windshear develops beneath thunderstorms. Scientists say it is a
downward flow of air that hits the earth and fans out in all
directions. Such winds are known to have caused airliner crashes in
Dallas and New Orleans.
   However, Civiletti said in an interview published today in the
Rome newspaper Republica that Cuban authorities had said the cause
of the crash was due to both pilot error and poor weather.
   Cuban investigators expect to report their conclusions in 15 to
20 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
