<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1348EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Medfly     09-06 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medfly,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spraying Against Medfly to Begin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State agriculture officials
announced today they will begin immediate spraying to protect
California's $14 billion produce industry from an infestation of the
voracious Mediterranean fruit fly.
   The decision required a declaration of an emergency by Gov.
George Deukmejian, who signed the order today after 16 Medflies were
found in the Mountain View area since last week, said Gera Curry,
Food and Agriculture Department spokeswoman.
   The spraying of the pesticide malathion take place in northern
California's Santa Clara County.
   Ground spraying was to begin about noon, and an aerial spraying
will be done on Friday if the weather is clear, the department said.
   Beginning Sept. 18, the state will also release 30 million
sterile Medflies a week until biologists decide the infestation is
destroyed.
   Medflies lay eggs in 250 varieties of fruits and vegetables _
including all citrus fruits, apples, cherries, avocados and tomatoes
_ and are capable of devastating California's $14 billion annual
agricultural industry.
   When Medfly eggs hatch, the larvae feed on the fruit, which spoil
and fall to the ground.
   Immediate ground and aerial spraying of malathion was recommended
Tuesday by a group of international experts in pest eradication.
   The advisory group, which discussed the infestation during a
conference call from such locations as Guatemala, Hawaii and
Florida, said other options available involve quarantine or
treatment only of the affected plants.
   Under state law, aerial spraying of malathion requires at least
24-hour notice to each home in the area. A state study in 1987 found
no damage to people's health as a result of large-scale spraying in
the early 1980s.
   About 300 members of the California Conservation Corps were
distributing leaflets today to about 100,000 homes in the area, The
leaflets described time and place of spraying, possible health
hazards and steps to protect vehicles.
   A 1980-81 Medfly infestation in Santa Clara County caused a
bitter debate over the use of chemical sprays. Helicopter spraying
of malathion over eight San Francisco-region counties eventually
wiped out the pests.
   An infestation in the Los Angeles area last year cost $2 million
to eradicate by way of malathion spraying and the release of 700
million sterile flies. Another infestation in 1980-82 cost $100
million.
   In the early 1980s, the state spent more than $100 million to
eradicate the pest in parts of central California and Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1351EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--AbortionClinic     09-06 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Abortion Clinic,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clinic's New Home Burns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire caused $3,000 to $5,000 in damage to a
building where an abortion clinic moved in the hope of escaping
further attention from anti-abortion protesters, authorities said.
   Firefighters responded around 4:30 a.m. Wednesday to a report
that a fire bomb was used against Allegheny Reproductive Health
Center.
   ``It very well could have been, but there's no proof that that's
what it was. There was a fire. That's all we know at this time,''
said Chuck Perlick, an investigator for the federal Bureao of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
   The clinic had moved from across the street.
   Anti-abortion activists apparently were not fooled.
   ``I heard for a month on the radio that they moved ... to an
undisclosed location to avoid protests. But for a month the
protesters were in my store telling me what they were doing
upstairs,'' said David Falcione, a manager of a neighboring
appliance store.
   No one was hurt in the fire, which damaged the door and a
staircase..
</TEXT>
</DOC>
