<SECOND>AM-BRF--Overboard Drill,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carrier Crew Went Overboard in this Drill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A routine man-overboard drill
on the USS Saratoga turned into the real thing for five sailors in a
lifeboat.
   Six sailors were being lowered from the aircraft carrier in the
boat to rescue a dummy that had been tossed overboard when the small
boat flipped, tossing five men into the water, a Navy official said
Tuesday. None of the sailors was injured.
   The accident, which occurred Aug. 18, when the ship was 70 miles
east of Jacksonville, is still under investigation, said Lt. John
Singley, a ship spokesman.
   The five crew members were rescued by a helicopter assigned to
the carrier. The sixth managed to hang on to a cable securing the
boat to the carrier and was able to climb back on board, officials
said.
   The Navy did not release information on the accident until crew
members contacted a Jacksonville newspaper.
</TEXT>
