<FIRST>u w PM-Poindexter     09-06 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poindexter,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poindexter Lawyers Say Reagan Authorized Letters to Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan authorized John Poindexter to
send letters to Congress on which part of the indictment against the
former national security adviser is based, Poindexter's lawyers said
today.
   Frederick Robinson, Poindexter's lawyer, told a hearing in
federal court that the former president's notes on various meetings
with his national security adviser should be produced for Poindexter
as part of his defense.
   Poindexter is charged in the Iran-Contra scandal with conspiracy,
two counts of obstructing Congress and two counts of making false
statements.
   Robinson depicted Reagan as having approved administration
responses to Congress about the Nicaraguan Contras. The indictment
against Poindexter depends in part on those responses.
   Poindexter ``went to the president to talk about'' sending
letters responding to congressional inquiries, said Robinson.
   U.S. District Court Judge Harold Greene asked whether he was
suggesting that ``the president said, `You go ahead and do this'.''
   ``Yes,'' responded Robinson.
   The president was saying, ``I want these things done,'' Robinson
said.
   ``I think that the president's notes ... we believe will show ...
discussions about the letters that were sent to Congress and the
appropriateness of any response,'' said Robinson.
   The congressional inquiries to which the Reagan White House was
responding focused on whether the administration was assisting the
Nicaraguan Contras in violation of a congressional ban on military
aid to the rebel force.
   Two of Poindexter's responses referred to year-old answers his
predecessor, Robert McFarlane, sent to Congress denying that the
National Security Council staff was supplying military advice or
raising funds for the Nicaraguan rebels. McFarlane subsequently
pleaded guilty to withholding information from Congress in
connection with his letters.
   One of the charges against Poindexter is that he obstructed
Congress in July and August 1986 by sending the letters. He also is
charged with conspiracy to obstruct congressional inquiries in
connection with the letters.
   Robinson said Poindexter is entitled to a wide range of material
for his defense, including notes from then-Vice President Bush,
White House chief of staff Don Regan and Defense Secretary Caspar
Weinberger.
   Robinson said that ``any time'' Bush ``missed a meeting, Admiral
Poindexter briefed him.''
   Poindexter wants the judge to direct the office of independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh to obtain some of Reagan's notes so that they
can be turned over to the former national security adviser.
   Walsh's office obtained some typewritten excerpts of Reagan's
diaries for the Iran-Contra trial of Oliver North. North's lawyers
subpoenaed Reagan's diaries, but U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard
Gesell quashed the subpoena.
</TEXT>
