<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Nominations     09-06 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Nominations,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Says Unfilled Jobs Are Bush's Responsibility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is largely responsibile for the
slow pace of filling key government positions and his complaint of
Senate foot dragging is ``unfounded and unfair,'' Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell said Wednesday.
   The Maine Democrat told the Senate that of the 432 full-time
Executive Branch positions requiring Senate confirmation, there are
200 jobs for which no nomination has been submitted or no
announcement made that the incumbent would be retained.
   ``Thus, nearly eight months after he took office, the president
has failed to make nominations for nearly half of the full-time
positions in executive departments and independent agencies which
require Senate confirmation,'' Mitchell said.
   ``Whose responsibility is that?'' he asked. ``It is certainly not
the Senate's.''
   Mitchell noted that after he met with Bush on Aug. 4 to discuss
nominations, White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said,
``The president wanted to express his deep concern that these
(nominations) were being held up for artificial reasons not related
to the candidates themselves.''
   Mitchell said that, based on a careful review of the status of
the Bush nominations to date, he is ``urging that the president
discontinue such criticism.''
   ``It is unfounded and unfair,'' Mitchll said. ``The principal
problem is in the slow pace at which nominations are being made, not
in the pace at which nominations, once made, are being processed.''
   He said there are 48 leadership positions in government
departments that are ``totally vacant,'' with no nominations
submitted and no holdovers from the Reagan administration in place.
   ``Out of 14 Cabinet deartments, only the Department of
Transportation has no totally vacant positions,'' Mitchell said.
``There are five totally vacant positions in the Executive Office of
the President and another 20 in major independent agencies.''
   In the field of public health, Mitchell said, there is no nominee
for Surgeon General, commissioner of aging or for the position of
administrator of the Health Care Finance Administration.
   In education, he said, there are no nominees to fill assistant
secretary positions in elementary and secondary education or in
vocational and adult education and civil rights.
   ``The vital 1990 census is rapidly approaching and there is no
nominee to be director of the Census Bureau,'' Mitchell said.
``Whose responsibility is that?''
   Mitchell asserted that the Senate, by way of contrast, has
confirmed 212 Bush nominees, 90 percent of them within two months of
the time the nominations was received.
   Mitchell did not include in his count nominations for U.S.
ambassadors, U.S. marshalls or U.S. attorneys.
</TEXT>
