<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1428EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Simenon     09-06 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Simenon,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simenon, Creator of Detective Maigret, Dead at 86</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgian author Georges Simenon, who created the
popular Inspector Maigret while churning out novels that sold more
than 500 million copies worldwide, has died. He was 86.
   Simenon died in his sleep Monday at his home in Lausanne,
Switzerland, Henri-Charles Tauxe, a Swiss journalist and friend of
the author, said Wednesday.
   Simenon's strength had ebbed over the past year and he was
confined to a wheelchair.
   His popularity stemmed from more than 200 novels, including 80
that centered on Paris detective Maigret, who tried to understand
rather than condemn criminals.
   His books were translated into 55 languages, including Chinese,
Armenian and Yiddish. Charles Laughton and German actor Heinz
Ruehmann were among those who played Maigret in about 50 film
adaptations.
   Jean Richard, a French actor who played Maigret in dozens of
television films, said: ``For me, he was the greatest popular French
author without comparison. He was the new Balzac.''
   French President Francois Mitterrand said Simenon's books ``will
remain the companions of generations of readers on all continents.''
   The official Soviet news agency Tass eulogized Simenon as a
``master detective story writer.''
   His novels were a staple in the Soviet Union.
   While best known for Maigret, Simenon himself preferred the 132
other novels, often dark accounts of people in crisis.
   ``The Cat,'' describing the love-hate relationship of a French
couple, was turned into an acclaimed movie starring Jean Gabin and
Simone Signoret.
   His 1981 memoirs were called ``Intimate Memoirs.'' Sparked by the
1978 suicide of his daughter, Marie-Jo, at age 25, its tempestuous
story encompassed despair and happiness, love and sex, luxury and
homesickness.
   Simenon said he spent most of his life ``obsessed by a frantic
sexuality'' and claimed he slept with 10,000 women ``to learn the
truth'' about the other sex.
   He also published 21 volumes of ``Dictations,'' transcripts of
thoughts and memories taped during an eight-year period when Simenon
suffered an ear condition that upset his sense of balance.
   Simenon also wrote about 300 early pulp fiction novels under
pseudonyms and more than 1,000 newspaper articles on his travels.
   Andre Gide, the late French Nobel laureate, once rated his friend
``perhaps the greatest and most genuine novelist'' of a generation.
   Simenon was born Feb. 13, 1903, in Liege, Belgium.
   He quit school at 16, working as a baker's apprentice and
bookstore clerk before reporting for a local newspaper. That career
ended after he wrote a satire about his superiors and his family,
including his wealthy uncle who never spoke to him again.
   Simenon moved to Paris in 1922 and began churning out novels,
chiefly for consumption by homemakers. He wrote anything that sold _
from sentimental stories to adventure books and travelogues _
drawing his basic information from the Larousse encyclopedia.
   In three years, he made enough money to rent a chic apartment at
the Place des Vosges and own a chauffeur-driven car and a yacht.
   He wrote his first Maigret work, ``The Strange Case of Pieter the
Lett,'' in 1929.
   After World War II, Simenon spent several years in the United
States and Canada. There, he produced some of his finest works,
including the 1947 ``Letter To My Judge'' and ``The Snow Was Dirty.''
   In the early 1960s, Simenon wrote up to six books a year on his
electric typewriter, picking the names of his characters from
international telephone books.
   Suffering from the ear problem, he put away the typewriter in
1972.
   In the United States, Simenon divorced his French-born first wife
of 27 years, Regine, and married Denise Quimet, a Canadian. They
settled in Switzerland and separated in 1969 but never divorced.
   Simenon said he found complete happiness only after meeting
Teresa, his wife's Venice-born chambermaid 20 years his junior. They
moved into a plainly furnished farmhouse in Lausanne.
   The author was cremated Wednesday with only closest family
present, a Lausanne funeral home said. According to his wish, his
ashes were scattered under a cedar tree outside his house beside
those of his daughter, Marie-Jo.
   Simenon is survived by three sons. His fortune is estimated in
the hundreds of millions of dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1423EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-FootballPool     09-06 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Football Pool,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ticket Sales Begin in Football Betting Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's only state-run football pool
based on the point spreads of NFL games began taking bets today.
   ``The system is up and running,'' said Oregon Lottery Director
Jim Davey. He said retailers sold about $1,100 worth of bets
statewide in the game's first three hours, which he called ``pretty
good.''
   The National Football League has threatened legal action against
the state, charging that the pool, called Sports Action, will hurt
the integrity of professional football.
   But Oregon's move has inspired other states to consider offering
such pools. The pool was created as a way to generate money for
athletics and scholarships at Oregon's colleges.
   The point spreads are to be made each week by Michael ``Roxy''
Roxborough, an oddsmaker in Nevada. Sports Action bets can be made
as late as Sunday afternoon each week, provided that the games being
played haven't started.
   Players can bet on four to 10, or all 14, NFL games each week.
Wagers can be for $1-$5, $10 or $20 on each entry form.
   ``I imagine the betting will pick up toward the weekend,'' Davey
said. ``The first NFL game isn't until Sunday morning, so people
have lots of time to think about it.''
</TEXT>
