<FIRST>r w AM-Ros-Lehtinen     09-06 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ros-Lehtinen,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepper's Successor Sworn in; First Cuban-American in Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, the first Cuban-American
to serve in Congress, was sworn in Wednesday as a Republican member
of the House from Florida.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, 37, succeeded the late Democratic Rep. Claude
Pepper, giving the House 176 Republicans and 255 Democrats. There
are four vacancies.
   In a brief maiden speech on the House floor, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen
said:
   ``As a Cuban-American whose family has fled the horrors of
communism, I think that this day serves to solidify the belief and
the truth that the United States truly is the land of opportunity,
where all of our dreams can be made possible if we try hard enough.''
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen was elected over Miami attorney Gerald Richman
in a special election last month. Pepper had represented the 18th
district since it was created in 1962.
   Her election was considered a victory not only for
Cuban-Americans, but also for the Republican National Committee,
which had targeted the seat. President Bush campaigned for Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen.
   A former state legislator who left Cuba as a child with her
parents, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen is married to Dexter Lehtinen, the U.S.
attorney in Miami.
