<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--SpaceStation     09-06 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Space Station,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Delivers First Space Station Data Management System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An early version of the data computing system that
eventually will fly aboard the Freedom Space Station was delivered
to NASA, the makers of the system said Wednesday.
   The delivery by IBM is the first computer hardware and software
for Freedom's data management system.
   Engineers at NASA and its contractor companies will use it to
test their design for the space station's other subsystems.
Programmers will use it as a working model on which to write and
test software programs.
   The system will provide data processing and local communications
for the station's basic operations and its payloads.
   ``The data management system is the integrating element of Space
Station Freedom _ the `glue' that connects the many different
systems and helps them work together,'' said Michael W. Dawkins,
general manager of the IBM Systems Integration Division facility in
Houston that is developing the onboard computer system.
   IBM performed the work for McDonnell Douglas Space Systems Co., a
major contractor for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
