<DOCNO> AP890906-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1451EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SchoolTakeover Bjt   09-06 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Takeover, Bjt,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston University Takes Over Chelsea School System</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHELSEA, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chelsea High welcomed back its students
Wednesday with signs in English, Spanish, Cambodian and Vietnamese
reflecting its melting pot demographics. The signs also greeted a
newcomer, Boston University, which will run Chelsea's troubled
schools for the next decade.
   ``A lot of things are still tentative, but the students and
faculty are looking forward to change,'' Principal Mary Raimo said
of the unprecedented takeover of a public school system by a private
institution.
   Change will not come quickly to 80-year-old Chelsea High or the
five other aging schools in this poor community. Although there are
immediate plans for a school for chronic truants, computer labs and
new curricula, the university has loftier, longer-term goals.
   Officials talk of fostering children's education by schooling
parents in reading, nutrition and child care. The talk is of
creating an atmosphere that stresses education long before children
walk into school for the first time.
   ``This is not a cute little project involving some classrooms,''
said Peter Greer, Boston University's dean of education who will
oversee the management team. ``We're talking about a philosophy that
education can emancipate the underclass in the United States.''
   But, the university faces significant hurdles. Many in this
community of 26,000 remain wary about surrendering their children's
education to academicians. The teacher's union and Hispanic parents
have filed suit challenging the agreement. Others fret the
university won't raise the $2 million to $3 million a year it
promised for special programs.
   ``The money was supposed to come in hand over fist, but we
haven't seen it,'' said Elizabeth McBride, chairwoman of the Chelsea
School Committee.
   The unique agreement between the university and Chelsea follows
years of hard times for 3,500-student school system. An influx of
immigrants from Latin America and Southeast Asia swelled the school
population; declining tax revenues cut school budgets.
   Chelsea now spends $1,600 less per student than the national
average. Test scores, graduation rates and teacher salaries are
among the lowest in Massachusetts.
   The situation led to meetings with John Silber, the president of
Boston University who has long sought to use his school's resources
in public education. After months of negotiations among the school
committee, aldermen and the state Legislature, an agreement was
reached in June giving the university control of the schools.
   The school committee has advise and consent powers over BU
programs. It can negate university plans with a two-thirds vote but
cannot overrule personnel decisions.
   ``I feel that it's taking away the power of elected officials,
taking away voters' rights,'' said Mrs. McBride, who six of her
children through the community's schools.
   But if Chelsea residents have lost some political control over
their schools, BU wants to get them involved in a much more intimate
way.
   The university experimented with a literacy program this spring
for mothers and their young children. Twenty-three families met with
teachers and tutors two-hours a day for several weeks. While
children were introduced to reading, their mothers improved their
own reading and learned how to teach their children.
   ``If we're successful we will help parents be aware they instill
the love of learning,'' said Jean Paratore, an associate BU
professor who heads the program.
   The program is a precursor to BU's plans for greater involvement
of the family in education. Greer talks of adult classes on
nutrition, parenting, child care and even pre-natal care.
   ``Even if you pour zillions of dollars in classrooms and
teachers, it isn't going to work unless you have healthy students
supported by their parents,'' said Greer, former superintendent of
Portland, Maine's, schools.
   Yet money is an issue. BU officials talked of raising $50 million
through the life of its contract with Chelsea. While more money is
expected, only $726,000 in pledges were in hand by late August,
leaving many programs on hold.
   And there are other anxieties. Chelsea's teachers are mindful of
Silber's stormy relations with his university's unions; Hispanics,
fearful the new management might end bilingual education, went to
court to try to stop the takeover.
   Some rough road has been smoothed over for now. The BU management
team has several bilingual experts, including Diana Lam, a
Peruvian-born bilingual expert, picked to be Chelsea's new school
superintendent. The union has signed an interim contract with BU
that gives teachers an average bonus of $1,300.
</TEXT>
