<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1514EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-CrackBabies     09-06 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Crack Babies,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>``Deeply Touched'' President Visits Youngest Victims of Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Little Edward saw the hospital room that has
been his home almost since birth 4{ months ago suddenly fill with
bright lights and big people, and he did what comes naturally to
infants.
   He cried.
   And President Bush, touring District of Columbia General
Hospital's ward for babies abandoned at birth by crack-addicted
mothers, did what comes naturally to a father of six and grandfather
of 11.
   He picked Edward up and cradled him against his shoulder.
   ``What's the matter with you? What in the world's the matter with
you?'' asked the president in a soft voice.
   Instantly, the baby stopped bawling and flashed a big smile.
   ``You just want a little attention, don't you? See, it works,''
the president, garbed in a blue hospital gown, told his health
secretary, Louis Sullivan.
   For Bush, the visit Wednesday to the pediatrics ward of D.C.
General was a chance to dramatize his new national strategy to fight
a menace that finds its youngest victims still in the womb.
   Edward and a dozen other infants at D.C. General are so-called
``boarder babies'' abandoned after birth by mothers addicted to
drugs.
   The babies, even after being cured of their own drug
dependencies, still must wait for months until foster care can be
found for them.
   At least one of the children has tested positive for the HIV
virus, which causes AIDS.
   Bush, out of sight of cameras, toured other rooms where the
hospital staff was nursing tiny, underweight infants to health, and
caring for others for whom the prognosis was grim.
   Dr. Stanley Sinkford, the chief of pediatrics, showed Bush one
infant who had bacterial meningitis, a swollen brain and has already
undergone several operations. The mother, who left a home phone
number that turned out to be a local barber shop, has not been found.
   In the room of an infant who tested positive for the AIDS
antibody, Bush asked, ``Does that baby have a chance to get well?''
   ``We don't know,'' Sinkford replied.
   In the intensive care nursery, Bush peered at the tiny, frail
babies hooked up to intravenous lines and monitors.
   ``What's this guy's problem?'' Bush asked about one infant.
   ``Just born too soon,'' said Sinkford.
   Twenty percent of the 2,025 babies born at D.C. General last year
were exposed to drugs in the womb, mostly cocaine, hospital
officials said.
   Fourteen to 15 percent are low-weight births, below the 5{-pound
mark that signifies danger. That is double the national rate.
   Edward and a dozen other boarder babies generally are healthy,
but homeless. They are not eligible for adoption because the mothers
never relinquished their legal rights before abandoning them,
hospital officials said.
   Marilou King, chairwoman of the D.C. General Hospital Commission,
said the hospital is considering opening an orphanage on its grounds
to meet the problem. Each boarder baby costs the hospital an average
of $100,000 a year.
   ``They cannot get maternal love in a hospital setting,'' said Dr.
Mehnur Abedin, the neonatologist in charge of the nursery.
   Later, back at the White House, Bush told reporters, ``I was
deeply touched by seeing these abandoned babies.''
   ``The commitment of these nurses and these doctors to these kids
that are born without hope is so encouraging. The only love they may
ever get in their lives is when they're a month old, and we've got
to change that,'' Bush said.
   He said it underscores the need for community involvement and
voluntary efforts to solve the drug problem.
   He promised to ``work my hardest'' to make the national drug
strategy work, but said, ``It's at the level of love, and the level
of local education and parental concern, neighbor involving with
neighbor ... in the life of another, that this problem is going to
be solved.
   ``I'm absolutely convinced of it. And I'm more convinced of it
than ever after holding in my arms one of those abandoned babies,''
he said.
</TEXT>
