<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--SchoolFood     09-06 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--School Food,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Finds Answer to School Food Complaints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENID, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Principal Barbara Erwin has found a way to
overcome gripes about the cafeteria food and get most pupils to at
least try everything they're served _ eating out with the principal.
   That's the top reward at Hayes Elementary School in a system
based on the number of paper tokens a class earns.
   ``We have four lunchroom rules, and one of them is that they must
take two bites of everything on their plates,'' Mrs. Erwin said.
``If they obey all four rules for five days, everyone in their room
gets a stick of bubblegum.''
   From there, students can advance to a sack of popcorn, a candy
bar or a poster until the final prize _ lunch at the end of the
school year with Mrs. Erwin at a hamburger shop.
   The other rules are no loud talking until the lunch is finished,
clean up the table and the area and no ``fussing on the
playground,'' Mrs. Erwin said.
