<FIRST>u w PM-US-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0637 09-06 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0637,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Blames Christian Leader For Embassy Pullout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds last 3 grafs, Abdallah Bouhabib, with comment by Lebanese
ambassador.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States blamed a Christian military
commander today for forcing the evacuation of the American embassy
in Beirut by threatening to expose Ambassador John McCarthy and his
staff to a ``good dose of Christian terrorism.''
   While vowing that the United States would not abandon Lebanon
forever, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler also cited
as a reason for the pullout a reported statement by Gen. Michel Aoun
to a French newspaper that ``perhaps he should take 20 American
hostages.''
   She gave no indication when the 40 Americans might return to
their posts or if the United States had any new diplomatic
approaches to seek an end to the 15-year civil war that has torn the
Middle Eastern country apart.
   ``We have a responsibility to insure the safety of our
personnel,'' the spokeswoman said. ``We plan to go back to Beirut as
soon as conditions permit. The evacuation does not represent
diminution of our intention to try to help Lebanon in its time of
trouble.''
   Some 1,000 demonstrators backing Aoun had blocked the embassy,
while a protest leader threatened that the blockade would be moved
closer to the building and U.S. personnel could enter and leave only
``at their own risk,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   The unidentified leader warned that ``an indefinite next step
would take place'' today, she said, and a telephone caller
threatened to shoot down the U.S. helicopter that brought supplies
and messages to the embassy.
   ``As Gen. Aoun's threats and implications about the U.S. grew
nastier, the department and the embassy were in close touch through
the Labor Day weekend,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   After talking to McCarthy by telephone, Secretary of State James
A. Baker III met at 11 a.m. Tuesday with President Bush, who
approved their recommendation to evacuate the embassy.
   Bush, Baker, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, national security
adviser Brent Scowcroft, White House chief of staff John Sununu and
Assistant Secretary of State John Kelly then met in the afternoon to
discuss implementing the decision, Ms. Tutwiler said.
   She said there was unanimous agteement on the move, despite
previous administration statements that the Beirut embassy had to
remain open despite the fighting between Christian and Moslem forces
in order to play a diplomatic role in trying to attain a cease-fire.
   ``We regret having to evacuate the embassy and the actions by
Gen. Aoun and his followers that made it necessary,'' Ms. Tutwiler
said.
   In an angry statement directed at the Christian leader, the U.S.
spokeswoman said, ``We were told yesterday by reliable journalists
on the ground that Gen. Aoun said that Lebanon needed a good dose of
`Christian terrorism.' and that ``on Friday, Sept. 2, Aoun told the
French newspaper Figaro that perhaps he should take `20 American
hostages.'''
   Abdallah Bouhabib, the Lebanese ambassador to Washington,
disputed the U.S. assessment.
   ``We think that there was no danger whatsoever for the American
diplomats there,'' he told The Associated Press. ``There have been
no real threats. The demonstration was democratic, like any
demonstration.''
   The ambassador, who said he was notified of the evacuation
Tuesday night, described the demonstration as ``a result of
frustration of asking for more assistance from a friendly
superpower.''
</TEXT>
