<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-ComptrollerRace     09-06 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comptroller Race,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lesser-Knowns Hope for Second Place</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-known state assemblyman from Queens is
spending $400,000 this week to become a well-known state assemblyman
from Queens. A slightly better-known former schools chancellor is
spending $220,000.
   Their objective: to approach the fame of the very well-known
Elizabeth Holtzman. And, starting last week, she's spending $500,000.
   Such is life in the city comptroller's race, a contest for the
second most-powerful citywide elective office that has been
overshadowed by a close mayoral election and dominated by Holtzman,
a Brooklyn district attorney.
   But it is a fight the assemblyman, Alan Hevesi, and the
ex-chancellor, Frank Macchiarola, are waging with vigor. Jointly
they hope to hold Holtzman under 40 percent in the Democratic
primary, forcing a runoff. Individually each hopes to finish second
and thus emerge as her runoff opponent.
   The eventual Democratic nominee will face only token opposition
in the general election Nov. 7.
   ``We have a shot. Can't ask for more,'' Hevesi, 49, an 18-year
member of the state Assembly, said this week. ``We think the whole
thing will crystallize three days before the election.''
   With the primary this Tuesday, that leaves little time.
Macchiarola popularity polls put him in the teens. Hevesi has only
single-digit support, although Wednesday he was endorsed by a fourth
candidate, Assemblyman Jerrold Nadler, who dropped out.
   But while Holtzman leads solidly, she slipped to 37 percent in a
New York Newsday poll conducted last week and released Wednesday _
the first time she has fallen under the 40 percent threshold.
   ``If she gets under 40 the guy who comes in second has got a very
good chance of beating her,'' said Norman Adler, a veteran political
strategist. ``Liz is a mile wide and an inch deep. The only thing
people know about her is her name.''
   Holtzman, 47, made her name as a congresswoman in the 1970s, when
she served on the House committee on Watergate and on the Budget
Committee. She ran for the U.S. Senate in 1980, narrowly losing to
Republican Alfonse D'Amato, and won office as Brooklyn district
attorney in 1982.
   She was frontrunner from the start in the race for comptroller, a
seat vacated after 16 years by Harrison J. Goldin, who is running
for mayor. The comptroller, as the city's chief fiscal officer,
conducts audits and manages $30 billion in pension funds.
   Holtzman has conducted a confident campaign, steering clear of a
televised debate and dismissing Macchiarola, Hevesi and Nadler as
``the gang of three.''
   ``My candidates attack me for having name recognition as if it
were a disease,'' she said this week. ``It's not simply name
recognition that I have. It's what people know about me and
associate with me _ that I've worked hard, vigorously and well for
the people of this city.''
   But her opponents mention other attributes: a brittle public
persona and a reputation for staff disharmony. ``She has one major
problem,'' declared Nadler. ``Her atrociously incompetent conduct of
the D.A.'s office.''
   Less biased analysts have reached conclusions that are tamer but
still damaging. To serve as an effective comptroller ``will take
political grace and skill,'' The New York Times editorialized last
month. ``Those are not the first words that come to mind about Ms.
Holtzman.'' It endorsed Hevesi.
   So did two other dailies, the Daily News and New York Newsday,
points being hit by Hevesi in an avalanche of television ads
unleashed Tuesday. New Yorkers who miss it on the tube may catch it
in their mail: Hevesi is sending out 350,000 postcards this week
touting his endorsements.
   ``Nobody's ever heard of me,'' he said. ``After $400,000, a lot
of people are going to have heard of me.''
   Macchiarola, 48, who started his $220,000 television blitz last
week, has enlivened the race with ads touting him as ``the fighting
professor'' _ he's a business professor at Columbia University with
a combative style. In one debate, he called Holtzman ``thick.''
</TEXT>
