<FIRST>r a AM-GiamattiBurial     09-06 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Giamatti Burial,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giamatti Buried Among Former Yale Presidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version also on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A. Bartlett Giamatti, major league
baseball commissioner and former president of Yale University, was
laid to rest Wednesday after a private graveside service.
   The grave was in the Grove Street Cemetery, traditional burial
site for Yale presidents. Entrance to the cemetery was guarded
during the service, and the gates were locked immediately after
mourners left.
   At least 50 relatives and friends, including Yale President Benno
C. Schmidt Jr. and Mayor Biagio DiLieto, attended the 25-minute
service. The Rev. Harry B. Adams, the Yale chaplain, officiated.
   Giamatti served as president of Yale from 1978 to June 1986
before becoming president of baseball's National League. He became
baseball commissioner in April.
   Fay Vincent, deputy baseball commissioner, was named acting
commissioner until a successor is named.
   Giamatti, who was 51, died Friday after suffering a heart attack
at his summer home on Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts. He is
survived by his wife, Toni, and three children.
   The service was kept private at the request of the Giamatti
family. A public memorial service was planned, but no date was set.
   Most of Giamatti's 18 predecessors as president of Yale are
buried in the cemetery, which dates from 1796. The cemetery, located
along the Yale campus, also contains the graves of such famous men
as Eli Whitney and Noah Webster.
   Giamatti spent half his life at Yale, first as student, then 12
years as a teacher and then eight years as president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
