<FIRST>u a AM-People     09-06 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city that came to the rescue of Jessica
McClure when the child fell down a well in 1987 now wants to honor
similar heroic efforts in other towns and has asked ``Dear Abby'' to
help spread the word.
   Mayor Carroll Thomas wrote Dear Abby columnist Abigail Van Buren
asking her to pass it around that Midland is seeking nominations for
its new Community Spirit Award.
   The award will be presented next month to a city or town whose
residents pitched in to achieve a mission, much like Midlanders came
together in October 1987 to rescue the 21-month-old Jessica after
two days in an abandoned water well.
   Abby threw in her own nomination: Residents of her hometown of
Sioux City, Iowa, for pitching in to help victims of a plane crash
July 19. But Thomas said Tuesday the award is for 1988 events.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An artwork on exhibit at a state-run gallery
depicts Gov. Mario Cuomo as a puppeteer and has an official fuming
that tighter admissions procedures are needed.
   The work, showing Cuomo pulling the strings on efforts to build a
radioactive waste dump, is not appropriate for the display that
opened last Friday at the Vietnam War Veterans Memorial Gallery,
said Thomas Tubbs, a state Office of General Services spokesman. The
gallery is in the Empire State Plaza, a complex of government
buildings.
   The OGS plans to draw up formal review policies for artists who
want to display works in the future, said Tubbs, who also is a
Vietnam veteran.
   ``The Vietnam memorial was meant to commemorate my fellow
soldiers who were killed in Vietnam and those missing in action,''
Tubbs said Tuesday.
   The artist, Norman Roth, of Moon Beach in Cayuga County, said OGS
officials pressured him to remove his work.
   Tubbs denied that Roth was asked to remove the artwork and said
the piece will remain until the exhibit closes in mid-October.
   The governor was steering clear. His spokesman Tom Conroy said
Cuomo has not seen the work but that he would not call for its
removal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi arms dealer Adnan Khashoggi, his usual
globe-hopping curtailed by federal authorities, says he's happy
nonetheless while free on $10 million bail awaiting trial on
obstruction of justice and mail fraud charges.
   ``Everything is marvelous, just great,'' Khashoggi told an
Israeli reporter for a rare interview carried by the New York Post.
``People come up and shake my hand. Everybody in the street
recognizes me.
   ``Everybody is pleased to meet me. When I'm out, they won't even
let me pay for meals. There is no need to worry about me.''
   Under his bail agreement, Khashoggi must stay in Manhattan and
wears an electronic ankle bracelet to keep federal officials
appraised of his whereabouts. Khashoggi allowed the reporter to
visit his $26 million apartment in the Olympic Tower on Fifth Avenue.
   Khashoggi, who is being tried in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, is charged with having helped Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos
plunder the Philippine treasury. He faces up to five years in jail
and a $250,000 fine on each of the two charges.
   Khashoggi blames his indictment on the former U.S. District
attorney in Manhattan.
   ``It is Rudolph Giuliani who started this whole business. He is
dying to be mayor of New York and for this he has to prove how
active he is, how tough, a real fighter for justice,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump, whose name already adorns two
casinos, a Manhattan skyscraper, an air shuttle, a bicycle race and
a board game, scrapped plans to go video Wednesday due to a
contractural snag, a publicist said.
   The billionaire developer was to join Thursday with executives
from Lorimar Television and Warner Brothers to announce plans for
``Trump Card,'' a new television series, but the deal fell through,
said Barry Stagg, spokesman for Warner Bros. Television.
   ``The announcement is off,'' said Stagg. ``There are last minute
contractural points that have to be worked out.''
   Stagg said the negotiations would continue, although there would
be no announcement on the show's status until next week at the
earliest. The shows intended format was not revealed.
