<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1547EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     09-06 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Anti-Apartheid Group Criticizes Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading anti-apartheid advocacy group
lambasted President Bush on Wednesday for not condemning the South
African government and not supporting the escalating defiance
campaign by the black majority.
   Transafrica urged the Bush administration to prevent the
rescheduling of $21 billion that South Africa owes U.S. banks. The
loans are due next June.
   ``Bush has been an extraordinarily indecisive president,''
Randall Robinson, executive director of Transafrica, told a news
conference. ``We can't afford an American president who fears taking
a moral position.''
   Bush has not made any statement since the defiance campaign began
several weeks ago with boycotts and demonstrations at segregated
public places. It was capped Wednesday with a general strike to
protest Wednesday's South African legislative elections, from which
blacks were excluded.
   At the White House, officials said Bush sent a letter several
weeks ago to Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, a leading black South
African foe of apartheid. Tutu was tear-gassed by police and briefly
detained last week.
   The officials said the note expressed U.S. support for a
negotiated power-sharing agreement between blacks and whites.
   The State Department, meanwhile, criticized the South African
elections, with spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler saying the voting
``offers only part of the South African community a chance to voice
its views. The majority must be given an opportunity to peacefully
voice theirs.''
   Robinson called the State Department comments ``inadequate
utterances that give comfort to the South African government.''
   The only way to bring the South African government to the
negotiating table is to convince it that failing to do so would be
too costly, he said.
   The Bush administration is wrong to assume that acting President
F.W. de Klerk is more liberal than his predecessor, P.W. Botha,
Robinson said. De Klerk is ``smoother, brighter and better
educated'' but is ideologicallly just as segregationist, Robinson
added.
   The administration has invited De Klerk to visit the United
States and become the first South African leader on an official
visit in 30 years.
</TEXT>
