<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Glance     09-06 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Glance,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Facts and Figures on South Africa's Election for a New Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures
on Wednesday's parliamentary elections in South Africa, where the
governing National Party faced its toughest challenge from white
opposition parties on the left and far right.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHAT WAS AT STAKE:
   A total of 763 candidates contested 166 seats in Parliament's
dominant white chamber, 80 seats in the chamber for people of
mixed-race, and 40 seats in the chamber for Indians. The two junior
chambers have no power to overrule the white chamber on matters of
national policy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHO COULD VOTE:
   According to government figures, 3,170,667 of the country's 5
million whites were registered to vote, as were 1,775,751 of the
roughly 3 million mixed-race people and 665,870 of the estimated 1
million Indians.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHO COULD NOT VOTE:
   None of South Africa's 28 million blacks was allowed to vote in
national elections. They can vote only for municipal officials and
for the administrations of the country's 10 tribal homelands.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   KEY COMPETITORS:
   Because the Indian and mixed-race chambers have little power,
most attention focused on the white House of Assembly, where the
National Party held 123 of the 166 elected seats. It faced strong
challenges from the far-right Conservative Party, which held 22
seats, and the anti-apartheid Democratic Party, which controlled 20
seats. One seat was held by a now-defunct moderate party.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHERE THEY STAND:
   The Conservatives favor a strengthening of segregation laws and
oppose political rights for blacks. The Democrats favor abolishing
all segregation laws and granting universal political rights, with
some provisions for ensuring that whites and other minority groups
have a voice in government decisions. The National Party has
proposed a five-year plan for bringing blacks into the political
system on a limited basis. It wants to ensure that blacks cannot
overrule white interests, and it wants to maintain segregated
schools and neighborhoods for whites who want them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
