<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1550EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DisabilitiesAct     09-06 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disabilities Act,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Nears Consideration of Disabilities Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics mounted a last-minute challenge
Wednesday to legislation aimed at assuring the nation's 37 million
disabled the same protections minorities were given a quarter of a
century ago.
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the National Federation of
Independent Business spelled out their disagreements with the
Americans With Disabilities Act in a joint news conference held as
the Senate neared consideration of the measure.
   They were pushing for amendments aimed at removing alcohol and
drug addicts from coverage under the act, lowering the penalties for
violations and exempting the smallest of businesses from lawsuits by
customers, clients and visitors.
   Students at Washington's Gallaudet University for the deaf, known
for an activist spirit that forced a change of its administration,
rallied to support the bill, gathering in front of the Capitol
before fanning out to lobby their homestate senators.
   The students support provisions requiring phone companies to
provide telecommunications services for the deaf, and at no higher
cost than regular service.
   Critics of the act say the cost of compliance _ including
modifying movie theaters, buses and restaurants to accommodate the
disabled _ is beyond estimation.
   The act would prevent against job discrimination because of
handicaps, a ban on discrimination in public accommodations,
including buses and restaurants, and enforcement through the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission.
   Not only alcohol and drug addiction, but also affliction with
AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ would be considered a
disability.
   The measure had wide sponsorship in the Senate and cleared the
Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee last month by a unanimous
vote. A House measure has been introduced but has yet to receive
hearings in any of the four committees that have jurisdiction over
it.
   The White House has also voiced support for the bill, saying it
uses ``reasonable measures, phased in over time.''
   Co-sponsor Tom Harkin, D-Iowa., speaking to 70 Gallaudet
students, likened the position of the disabled to that of blacks and
women before the landmark Civil Rights Act.
   ``You know before 1964 if you were black, or a woman or maybe
even Jewish, if you went into a place of business, they could throw
you out or not hire you ... But today, 25 years later, it is still
legal in this country to discriminate on the basis of handicap,'' he
said.
   I. King Jordan, president of the deaf university, pointed to
other landmark legislation from which the disabled are excluded. He
said that the 8 million to 9 million hearing- or speech-impaired
Americans have yet to benefit from the ``fleet interstate telephone
system'' created by the Communications Act of 1934.
   At the news conference, Chamber of Commerce attorney Nancy Fulco
said the requirement of ``reasonable access'' is too vague to be
defined anywhere but in court.
   ``Through its lack of fundamental guidelines and parameters for
businesses, along with its vague language, the measure promotes
lawsuits as a way of handling disputes between employers and the
disabled,'' she said.
   She said it will take the courts 20 years to resolve the
questions.
   ``This bill, as written, is a lopsided piece of legislation
loaded with traps and pitfalls that will be almost unavoidable by
small businesses. ...,'' said John Sloan, president of the
570,000-member National Federation of Independent Business. ``The
ADA bill would impose costly requirements on businesses and provide
for unlimited damage awards.''
   The federation said it could live with the bill if drug and
alcohol addicts were eliminated from protection; the maximum penalty
for the first violations reduced to $1,000 and $5,000 instead of
$50,000 and $100,000 and businesses with 15 or fewer employees were
exempted from lawsuits by customers, visitors and clients alleging
discrimination under the act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
