<FIRST>r a AM-Gambino-Drugs     09-06 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gambino-Drugs,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Heroin Kingpin Convicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reputed drug kingpin Francesco Gambino and
four associates have been convicted for their roles in a
Sicilian-based network that imported and sold millions of dollars
worth of heroin between 1984 and 1988.
   Gambino, 48, of New York City, was found guilty Tuesday by a
federal jury on charges of conspiring to smuggle and distribute
heroin. Gambino and his co-defendants face up to 30 years in prison.
No sentencing date was set.
   Also convicted were Ignazio Antonino Mannino, on charges of
conspiring to import and distribute heroin; Emanuele Salvatore
Mannino and Grace Pulitano Mannino, both on the two conspiracy
charges and a charge of money laundering; and Enzo Varisco, on a
charge of conspiring to distribute more than five kilograms of
cocaine.
   One defendant, Carlo Fodera, was found innocent. Varisco was
found innocent of conspiring to distribute heroin.
   District Judge Louis C. Bechtle revoked Gambino's bail and
ordered him taken into custody. Gambino had been confined to his
house, wearing a security bracelet and having his telephone calls
monitored.
   His attorney, David Breitbart, said the conviction would be
appealed. He contended during the trial his client had been targeted
because authorities mistakenly believed he was related to the late
New York mob boss Carlo Gambino.
   Authorities have said 68 people were charged in the United States
and 133 in Italy after a three-year FBI undercover operation in
which agents traveled to Italy and posed as interested buyers who
discussed making major drug buys.
</TEXT>
