<UNK>Many Burmese Dissidents Arrested, Some Tortured, U.S. Says</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Burmese opposed to the government
have been arrested over the past seven weeks and some are believed
to have been tortured in detention, the State Department said
Wednesday.
   ``The United States government condemns these acts of
oppression,'' department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said.
   ``We hope the Burmese government will take immediate steps to end
the torture of those under detention and release all political
prisoners.''
   The arrests began July 20, just before the start of
commemorations of last year's pro-democracy demonstrations. The
protests were forcefully suppressed, and about 3,000 Burmese are
believed to have died.
