<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-USDrugs     09-06 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US Drugs,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Says Don't Send U.S. Troops Aboard to Fight Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet spokesman Wednesday declared support for a
U.S. campaign to combat international drug trafficking but said
American troops should not be sent to other countries to do it.
   ``It's one thing for states to join efforts for a mutual fight
against narcotics,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim P.
Perfiliev. ``It's another to send military regiments to another
country.''
   Perfiliev's remarks at a government news briefing came the day
after President Bush announced a $7.9 billion plan to fight drug
sales and use.
   The United States has already given military hardware to the
government of Colombia, center of the world cocaine trade, to help
fight drug trafficking.
   Bush also said he was ready to ``make available the appropriate
resources of America's armed forces'' to other countries to help cut
drug production.
   Without referring directly to Bush's proposals, Perfiliev
expressed Soviet backing for U.S. and Colombian efforts to fight the
drug business.
   ``However, it's impossible not to note that there are attempts to
send American armed forces to that country,'' he said. ``Such an
action would be nothing less than an intervention into the internal
affairs of another state.''
