<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Yugoslav Communist Chief Kicked Out of Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Communist Party leader Bosko
Krunic has been stripped of his party membership after being accused
of separatist leanings, an official report said Wednesday.
   Krunic was ousted along with three other Communist leaders from
Vojvodina, a province in the Serbian republic, the state news agency
Tanjug said. All were accused of showing separatist tendencies.
   Under its populist leader Slobodan Milosevic, Serbia has
strengthened its control over its nominally autonomous provinces of
Vojvodina and Kosovo.
   Kosovo is dominated by an ethnic Albanian majority that resisted
the changes in riots that left 24 dead last spring.
   Communists allied with Milosevic took over the Vojvodina
organization after mass demonstrations in the province's capital,
Novi Sad, a year ago.
   Krunic, 59, was one of several Old Guard politicians who stepped
down in the national party elite in the past year during an official
drive to rejuvenate the leadership.
   He held the annually rotating presidency of the League of
Communists in 1987.
   Krunic was also member of the 23-man ruling presidium, or
Politburo, of the party until last year.
