<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Chronology     09-06 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Chronology,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chronology of U.S. Involvement in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief chronology of U.S.
involvement in Lebanon.
   July 15, 1958: President Dwight Eisenhower sends U.S. Marines to
Beirut at the request of Christian President Camille Chamoun to
quell an uprising by Chamoun's rivals. However, the Marines never
took part in any fighting, and they were quietly withdrawn soon
afterward.
   Aug. 25, 1982: Following Israel's June 1982 invasion, 800 U.S.
Marines, part of a 5,400-man peacekeeping force with British, French
and Italian units, go ashore to oversee the evacuation of Israeli,
Syrian and PLO forces from Beirut. The U.S. force was later
increased to 1,800 men.
   April 19, 1983: A Shiite Moslem suicide bomber rams an
explosives-packed van into the seaside U.S. Embassy in west Beirut,
killing 63 people, including 17 Americans.
   Oct. 23, 1983: A Shiite suicide bomber attacks the U.S. Marine
base near Beirut airport, killing 241 men. Another suicide bomber
hits a French paratroopers' base, killing 58 men.
   Dec. 5, 1983: U.S. Navy fighter-bombers attack Syrian missile and
artillery batteries in Lebanon, inflicting ``significant damage,''
after reconnaissance planes are fired on.
   Dec. 14, 1983: The battleship USS New Jersey bombards Moslem
positions with 250 shells from its 16-inch guns as the situation
deteriorates.
   Feb. 26, 1984: As Lebanon's civil war breaks out again, the
Marines are pulled back to U.S. warships off Beirut, beginning the
final withdrawal after an ill-fated 22-month peacekeping operation
in which 264 U.S. servicemen were killed.
   Sept. 20, 1984: Suicide bomber hits U.S. Embassy annex in north
Beirut, killing 12 people and wounding 96, including the U.S.
ambassador.
   March 16, 1985: Four armed kidnappers drag Terry Anderson, the
chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, from his
car in Beirut. He is the longest held of 16 foreign hostages in
Lebanon, eight of them Americans.
   Sept. 6, 1989: Staff of U.S. Embassy evacuates after hundreds of
Christian protesters besiege the facility to demand that the United
States help the Christians in their 6-month-old battle with Syrian
forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
