<DOCNO> AP890906-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ForgedFranklins     09-06 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forged Franklins,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post Office Will No Longer Accept $100 Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Florida's post offices will no longer accept
$100 bills because 93 fake ones were unwittingly accepted by Miami
postal workers in three days last week.
   ``In the one-year period just before this, only 120 counterfeit
bills of all denominations were passed at the postal offices,'' said
Karen Schultz, spokeswoman for the Miami division of the Postal
Service.
   Most of the phony bills were used to buy money orders, and
officials suspect one person is responsible. So far, no other post
office in the division has been hit by the counterfeiter, Schultz
said.
   Last year, $1.9 million worth of counterfeit bills were passed in
the Miami area, said Secret Service special agent Allan Cramer. That
puts Miami ahead of $1.8 million passed in New York and $1.4 million
in Los Angeles.
   The Miami division of the Postal Service is considering buying
counterfeit detectors for its 155 offices in Broward, Palm Beach,
Dade, Monroe, Lee, Hendry and Collier counties, said Schultz.
   The detector machine, which costs $200 to $1,000, works on the
premise that an educated user will be able to see the magnetic or
fiber contents of genuine bills, said Paul Hackenberry, assistant
special agent in charge of the Secret Service's Miami office.
   But expert counterfeiters can fool the machine and its user, he
said.
   ``We do believe these bills were manufactured outside the United
States,'' Hackenberry said. ``The person was passing those bills by
using them at the post office. If (counterfeiters) go somewhere and
have a successful pass, they continue going to a place like it.''
</TEXT>
