<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-06 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOIS BLANC ISLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Second-grader Brandon Schlund had
the honor of ringing the bell and raising the flag when school
opened on this island in the Straits of Mackinac.
   He also was first down the slide at recess, first to answer the
math questions, first to finish lunch.
   Brandon is the only school-age child on Bois Blanc Island, where
school-for-one began Tuesday in the one-room Pines School.
   ``I like it fine,'' he said.
   Teacher Lani White said Brandon will do fine with his studies,
but he'll miss something by not having playmates.
   Clover Schlund agreed, even though she sees some humor in her
son's status. He'll have a problem with the teeter-totter, she noted.
   ``It bothers me, the social part,'' she said. ``Academically,
we've pretty well been guaranteed that he'll be the smartest kid in
school.''
   The island school had four students last year, but three moved.
In the last 35 years, the student body has never numbered more than
13.
   Island children attend the Pines school through the eighth grade.
For high school, they move in with friends or relatives in
Cheboygan, five miles across the water.
   The school has a budget of about $49,000, including $27,000 for
White's salary, said School Board President Judy Wriska. On the
average, other districts in Michigan spend less than $4,000 per
child.
   Up to 2,000 people summer on Bois Blanc, but the winter
population is fewer than 50.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secret to long life is to be
``born with a lot of vitality,'' says a woman who celebrated her
105th birthday with congratulations from more than 30 friends and
relatives.
   Sadie Purnell received a letter of congratulations from President
Bush and his wife, Barbara, and a citation from Gov. Edward D.
DiPrete at her party Tuesday, held one day after her birthday.
   ``How grand I am,'' she declared at the height of the party.
   Mrs. Purnell told stories of her childhood in Waterville, Maine,
where she was the oldest of 15 children. She told of playing hide
and seek on the banks of the Kennebec River, of wearing snowshoes to
a school run by Ursuline nuns, and of feasting on her mother's
pancakes.
   At 15, she began working as a weaver in the textile mills, where
she later met her husband, Francis, who died in 1963.
   Mrs. Purnell moved to South Kingstown about 2{ years ago to live
with Richard Purnell, one of her 10 grandchildren.
   Purnell said his grandmother has 17 great-grandchildren, 13
great-great-grandchildren and three great-great-great-grandchildren.
