<FIRST>r a AM-LittleProblems     09-06 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Little Problems,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little People Liberation Responds to Dwarf Throwing With Anthem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Billy Barty and his Little
People Liberation have battled ``attitudinal and architectural
barriers'' for years, but the bizarre barroom sport of dwarf
throwing is too much to bear.
   ``It's a problem because it's very demeaning,'' Barty said of the
growing entertainment phenomenon. ``They are trying to spread it and
we are trying to get little people away from that.
   ``I can't deprive anybody from making a livelihood. But when
you're talking about people in bars that drink and throw _ that's
sad. I think it should be outlawed.''
   The 3-foot-9-inch Barty made his remarks after a news conference
to announce the upcoming release of the Little People Liberation
anthem recording and video ``From Where I Stand.''
   ``We should be looked up to. We should not be judged by our size
but for the space between our ears,'' said Barty, flanked by 15
other dwarfs who were introduced by Barty.
   They were identified as a lawyer, electronics technician,
stuntman, circus performer, actors and actresses. Barty then
introduced an Internal Revenue Service secretary _ his daughter,
Lori.
   ``My son would be here but he's 5-foot-11,'' said Barty, whose
movie credits include ``The Day of the Locust,'' ``Under the
Rainbow,' ``Foul Play,'' ``Willow'' and the upcoming ``UHF'' and
``Lobster Man From Mars.''
   The anthem has a ``We Are the World'' gospel flavor featuring
singer Carl Anderson and is designed to unite people on behalf of
the disabled. A toe-tapping Barty moved his lips to synchronize with
the lyrics as it was played for reporters.
   ``It is a positive outlook toward life,'' Barty said of the
recording and video being released next month. Proceeds will go to
the Billy Barty Foundation, which funds scholarships and other
programs for little people.
   ``The song is a message of dignity, determination and joy. The
toughest part is for the bigger world to understand. Don't judge us
by our size,'' Barty said.
   Barty, 65, founded Little People of America in 1957 to help
dwarfs. He said there were 1.5 million little people in the United
States and 200 types of dwarfism.
   One of his biggest concerns is creating a barrier-free
environment, the implementation of such innovations as windows that
crank open and voice-activated controls.
</TEXT>
