<FIRST>r a AM-GreenRiverKillings     09-06 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green River Killings,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Green River Suspect Indicted on Firearms Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury on Wednesday indicted
the man police have labeled a suspect in the Green River serial
killings on charges he possessed a firearm while a fugitive,
authorities said.
   William Jay Stevens II, 38, is serving a sentence for escape in
the King County Jail after walking away from a work-release facility
while serving a term for possessing stolen property in 1981. He is
due to be released Sept. 25.
   The Green River Task Force, investigating the deaths or
disappearances of at least 40 young women, described Stevens as a
``viable suspect'' after his arrest here in January.
   The description was contained in an affidavit used to obtain a
search warrant for two Spokane residences where Stevens had lived.
That search yielded 1,800 videotapes and police material, including
uniforms and weapons.
   Stevens was a third-year student at Gonzaga University Law School
at the time.
   He has not been charged in any of the Green River killings. It
was not immediately clear how the charges issued Wednesday might
affect his release.
   U.S. Attorney John Lamp had no immediate comment on Wednesday's
indictment.
   The Green River murders, which take their name from the south
King County river where the first victims were discovered, involve
the deaths of as many as 48 young women in the Seattle and Portland
areas during 1982-84.
