<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1746EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0646 09-06 0939</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0646,0963</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Evacuates Last Diplomats from Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs with McCarthy, staff arriving in West Germany,
quotes, details. Picks up graf 8 pvs, `The Movement ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador and his last 29
American staff members were forced out of Lebanon on Wednesday by
Christians, including about 1,000 massed outside the embassy, who
claim the United States supports Syria.
   Two helicopters landed at the compound about 7:30 a.m. and a
third hovered overhead, apparently providing cover, while the 30
Americans were evacuated, a witness said.
   It is the first time an American ambassador has been pulled from
Lebanon since the sectarian civil war began 14 years ago, and the
move at least temporarily ended the American diplomatic presence in
the country.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler angrily blamed the
Christian army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun, for the move, saying he
threatened to expose U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy and his staff to
a ``good dose of Christian terrorism.''
   She said that before the evacuation, an unidentified telephone
caller had threatened to shoot down the U.S. helicopter that brought
supplies to the embassy and that an unidentified protest leader said
people in the embassy entered and left ``at their own risk.''
   The Americans will return when ``conditions permit,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said.
   On arrival at the U.S. military's Rhine-Main Air Base outside
Frankfurt, a weary McCarthy told reporters Wednesday night that ``as
soon as those questions of security and safety can be resolved ...
it would be important for us to resume the work that we were doing
in Beirut.''
   McCarthy and his staff flew in on a U.S. Air Force C-130
transport plane from Cyprus. They are expected to leave West Germany
for the United States on Thursday but no further details were
immediately available.
   ``It just seemed to me that in the last several days it was no
longer possible for me to guarantee to Washington that the safety of
my staff was secure and it was for that reason that we left,''
McCarthy said.
   ``But as soon as those questions of security and safety can be
resolved, it seems to be that it would be important for us to resume
the work that we were doing in Beirut.''
   In Christian east Beirut, youths who had blockaded the gates of
the embassy compound for 24 hours dispersed at 1 p.m.
   The Movement for Supporting Liberation threatened in a statement
to resume the embassy siege if McCarthy returned before Washington
recognized Aoun's Christian Cabinet as the ``legitimate Lebanese
government.''
   Aoun, who has fought an artillery war with Syrian troops six
months, said of the evacuation: ``It seems the American Cain
couldn't endure the stare of the Lebanese Abel, so he left.''
   Aoun accuses the United States of supporting the presence of
40,000 soldiers in Lebanon, which he calls an occupation army. The
Syrians are in the country under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   Syrians and Christians exchanged intermittent artillery fire in
and around Beirut on Wednesday, killing one person and wounding
three.
   By police count, 828 people have been killed and 2,455 wounded
since the fighting began March 8 between the 20,000 men of Aoun's
Christian army units and a Moslem alliance led by the Syrians.
   McCarthy arrived a year ago, but to avoid extending recognition
to either Aoun's government or the competing Moslem Cabinet of
acting Premier Salim Hoss, he did not present his credentials.
   In Aoun's statement, issued in English, the U.S.-trained general
said: ``I am not surprised at all by the apparently precipitate
departure of our American guests early this morning.
   ``I used the term `guests' since, as the American ambassador did
not see fit to present his credentials to my government, his status
and that of his officials was, strictly speaking, that of visitors.
   ``Such puzzling and petulant behavior by Mr. McCarthy merely
reflects the nature and conduct of the U.S. State Department's
policy toward that part of Lebanon free of Syrian occupation.''
   An-Nahar, an independent Beirut newspaper, said an undisclosed
number of American diplomats left Beirut on Saturday after Aoun told
a news conference the United States had ``sold Lebanon to Syria.''
   He claimed U.S. policy was ``dictated exclusively by concerns
over the eight remaining American hostages in Lebanon.''
   The eight are among 16 Western captives, most believed to be in
the hands of Shiite radicals loyal to Iran. Held longest is Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   A resident of Aoukar, the Christian suburb where the embassy is
located, said: ``Two helicopters landed at the embassy compound
around 7:30 a.m. while the third, which appeared to be armed with
machine guns, hovered overhead at a medium altitude in an apparent
protection mission.
   ``Several people boarded the helicopters seconds after they
landed. They also loaded big sacks and several bags on the aircraft,
which took off a few minutes later.''
   Keith Peterson, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Cyprus, said:
``This move was in response to deteriorating local circumstances
which no longer permitted the embassy to function effectively. The
United States is not abandoning Lebanon. ... its personnel will
return when the situation permits.''
   American diplomats moved to the Beirut facility, an embassy
annex, after a Shiite Moslem suicide bomber rammed a van packed with
explosives into the seaside embassy in Moslem west Beirut on April
19, 1983, killing 17 Americans and 46 other people.
   A suicide bomber attacked the east Beirut annex on Sept. 20,
1984, killing 12 people and wounding 96, but the embassy remained
there.
</TEXT>
