<FIRST>r w AM-Cocaine-Colombia     09-06 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Colombia,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Prices Climb As Crackdown In Colombia Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine prices in Miami rose in the past few
weeks, but it's still unclear whether the Colombian government's
crackdown on narcotics traffickers slowed the flow of the drug into
the United States, the Drug Enforcement Administration said
Wednesday.
   The retail price of cocaine in South Florida has gone from an
average of $11,000 to $16,000 per kilogram to about $19,000 to
$20,000, based on sales of five to 15 kilograms, DEA spokesman Frank
Shults said.
   The DEA was not aware of any change in price to individual
cocaine users, as agents did not make any such spot check purchases,
Shults said. Instead, they bought in quantities of five, 10 and 15
kilograms, he said.
   The increase in prices, Shults cautioned, has been noticed for
the past three weeks, since slightly before Colombian President
Virgilio Barco issued emergency measures that allow for the
extradition of alleged drug traffickers to the United States to
stand trial and for the seizure of the traffickers' property.
   Barco launched the nationwide attack on drug traffickers
following the Aug. 18 assassination of leading president candidate
Luis Carlos Galan, a foe of the drug trade.
   ``We have not made any judgment about the impact of the events in
Colombia about the availability of cocaine in the United States,''
Shults said. The DEA is ``reviewing intelligence trends and various
other indicators and we'll be making that assessment,'' he said.
   However, Shults said that even if cocaine is not becoming scarcer
because of a disruption in the drug traffickers' operations, some
retailers who are raising their prices may be capitalizing on
buyers' fears that the drug is becoming harder to obtain.
   ``It may just be individual entrepreneurs capitalizing on
perceived market pressures,'' he said.
   Since Barco announced the emergency measures, drug traffickers
have launched a ``total war'' on the government, including bombings
in Medellin _ home to one of the world's largest drug cartels _ and
in the capital city of Bogota, and a shooting spree at the Bogota
airport.
   While the raw material _ coca leaf _ for most of the U.S. supply
of cocaine is grown in Peru and Bolivia, Colombia is the base for
the major traffickers who process the leaf into cocaine and
distribute it overseas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
