<SECOND>AM-Eastern Strikers,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Airline Strikers Rally At Capitol, March to White House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the AFL-CIO, other union leaders
and several members of Congress joined striking Eastern Airlines
workers at the end of a 26-day, 3,000-mile march Wednesday to
support the six-month-old walkout.
   Several hundred members of unions representing pilots, flight
attendants and mechanics paraded to the White House after a rally of
speeches, songs and chants against Texas Air Corp. owner Frank
Lorenzo on the west steps of the Capitol.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland demanded that the Senate bring to
a vote a measure to force resolution of the strike. The House
already has approved such a bill after President Bush refused to
follow a National Mediation Board recommendation in March that he
appoint an emergency board to investigate the labor dispute.
   Appointment of such a board would have banned a strike for 60
days.
   ``We're in a tough battle against one of the worst employers in
the country,'' Kirkland said.
   ``We know which side the president of the United States is on.
He's made that abundantly clear,'' said Kirkland.
   The rally came at the end of a march and caravan that started in
Miami on Aug. 12. Thirteen Eastern employees were introduced who,
leaders said, traveled the entire route. Hundreds of others
participated in mile-long relays of a symbolic picket sign along the
East Coast route that included New York and Boston.
   The unions accuse Lorenzo of planning to strip away Eastern's
assets until the airline is dead. Lorenzo said he is gradually
building it back up to a major carrier and has been adding flights
and personnel since filing for court protection from creditors and
reorganization under bankruptcy laws.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., saying ``working men have to stick
together'' to fight for the Eastern workers, said he would push for
Senate approval of the emergency legislation.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., said the strikers were ``fighting for
justice for all American workers.'' He said Lorenzo was trying to be
a ``modern-day robber baron.''
   Rep. Charles Hayes, D-Ill., said congressional inaction would be
support for Lorenzo.
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., put on a red shirt that urged a boycott
of Eastern and Lorenzo-owned Continental Airlines, and said, ``I
believe Frank Lorenzo is vicious and greedy.''
</TEXT>
