<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1816EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     09-06 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Former Prime Minister Reported Offered Government Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki has
offered his communist predecessor, Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, a post in
the new government, the state PAP news agency reported Wednesday.
   The full list of nominees to the first non-communist-led
government in the East bloc will be made public Thursday, a
secretary in Mazowiecki's office said.
   A brief PAP dispatch said Mazowiecki received Kiszczak at his
office Wednesday and offered him a position, but did not say what
position or if Kiszczak accepted.
   An army general who for eight years headed the Interior Ministry
with control of the police, Kiszczak would appear a likely candidate
to head either the Interior Ministry or the Ministry of Defense.
   Two communist party leaders also met with Mazowiecki on Wednesday
and said a good atmosphere prevailed but ``certain details'' remain
unsettled and require more talks Thursday, according to PAP.
   The party Politburo was reviewing the proposed government makeup
and will inform Mazowiecki on Thursday of its final stance on taking
part in the coalition, PAP said.
   Longtime Solidarity activist Mazowiecki was elected prime
minister on Aug. 24. He has crafted a coalition Cabinet giving the
largest share of ministerial portfolios to members of his movement,
followed by the communist Polish United Workers Party, the United
Peasant Party and the Democratic Party, according to legislative
officials.
   The Democrats said they were offered three ministries. The
Peasants confirmed their acceptance of four. The communists are
offered at least four, legislative sources said, and Solidarity
would take the rest.
   There are currently 16 ministries but the number could change.
   The sources spoke on condition of anonymity.
   One source said it appeared Solidarity would get two of the most
highly contested posts _ foreign affairs and chairmanship of the
committee that administers state television and radio.
   The Democrats and Peasants each will also be given a deputy
premiership, leaders of those parties said. The two minor parties
provided the swing votes needed to shift the government power away
from the communists for the first time since World War II.
   The Sejm, or lower house of parliament, elected Kiszczak as
premier on Aug. 2, but President Wojciech Jaruzelski accepted his
resignation Aug. 19 after Kiszczak failed to put together a
communist-led ``grand coalition'' government.
   Jaruzelski then accepted Solidarity leader Lech Walesa's proposal
to let Mazowiecki assemble a Solidarity-led government in coalition
with the Peasants and Democrats.
   Mazowiecki will meet Thursday with members of the Solidarity
parliamentary caucus to present his choices for approval, caucus
leader Bronislaw Geremek said. Some Solidarity lawmakers have
complained about the tight secrecy that has been kept on the
government formation.
   Geremek said the final list of nominees would be given to Sejm
speaker Mikolaj Kozakiewicz after the meeting. Kozakiewicz said Sejm
commissions will hold hearings for three days to consider the
candidates, and full Sejm will vote on them next Tuesday.
   ``We know it is not going to be the government of our dreams, but
a result of many concessions,'' said a commentary Wednesday in the
pro-Solidarity Gazeta Wyborcza newspaper.
   Mazowiecki met Wednesday with communist parliamentary leader
Marian Orzechowski and Central Committee Secretary Leszek Miller,
who has been representing the party in coalition talks.
   PAP quoted them as expressing the conviction later that remaining
items will not prevent a Sejm vote on the government Tuesday.
   The communists were promised the ministries of defense and
interior from the start. A legislative source close to the
negotiations said they also would get transportation and either the
Ministry for Foreign Trade or the Office of Economic Planning.
</TEXT>
