<DOCNO> AP890906-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1818EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strike     09-06 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strike,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijanis To Continue Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Azerbaijanis will continue a general strike,
originally called for three days, until a top Soviet official visits
the area, a leading activist in Baku said Wednesday.
   Ekhtibar Mamedov, spokesman for the People's Front political
movement, said by telephone from the southern republic's capital
that hundreds of thousands of people attended a rally late Wednesday.
   The People's Front wants Azerbaijan to reassert full control over
the Nagorno-Karabakh region, which now is being governed from
Moscow, and to recall its national parliament representatives.
   Neighboring Armenia also claims Nagorno-Karabakh, whose
population is predominantly Armenian, and violence has torn the
region for 18 months.
   Mamedov said the strike, scheduled to end Wednesday, would
continue until President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Vice President
Anatoly I. Lukyanov or Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov visit the area.
   He said the People's Front wants such a visit because ``the
republic's government is not in a position to solve this question''
of Nagorno-Karabakh. If no-one comes, Mamedov declared, the
political movement may change its platform to call for independence
rather than greater autonomy.
   Abdul-Rakhman Vezirov, head of the republic's Communist Party,
recommended more complete Kremlin control over Nagorno-Karabakh
region.
   Vezirov made the statement in an interview released in Moscow by
the Foreign Ministry. It contradicted a claim made by Activist Aiden
Amirbekov late Tuesday that Vezirov wanted control returned to
Azerbaijan.
   Official media have given wide coverage to ethnic disputes in the
Baltic republics and in Moldavia, which borders Romania, but have
said little about the strike in Azerbaijan.
   The People's Front says the strike has affected 95 percent of
factories in Baku and paralyzed rail transportation throughout the
republic. Journalists for the official Azerinform news agency have
said the strike is not so widespread.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said a strike by
Russian-speaking workers in Moldavia against a law making Moldavian
the official language continued despite appeals by the local
leadership and a national commission.
   Strikers met with a national legislative commission and the
Moldavian party chief, president and premier, Tass said.
   The strikers want Russian as a second official language in the
republic. Of the republic's 4.2 million people, 64 percent are
ethnic Moldavian and 36 percent Ukrainian, Russian, Bulgarian,
Jewish and Turkish.
</TEXT>
