<FIRST>u a AM-BeachRiot     09-06 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beach Riot,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department To Investigate Virginia Beach Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for WASHINGTON-dated AM-Beach Riot listed on News Advisory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department said Wednesday it has
begun an investigation of complaints that law enforcement officers
used excessive force to quell a Labor Day weekend riot at the
Virginia Beach oceanfront.
   ``We've received at least three complaints,'' said Tom Love, an
FBI special agent in Norfolk.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Burstion-Wade said the FBI and the
department's civil rights division had formally opened a criminal
investigation into possible deprivation of civil rights.
   She said the department was reviewing published accounts and
videotapes of the riot, which broke out early Sunday during
Greekfest.
   The annual college student gathering drew more than 100,000 young
people from predominately black East Coast colleges to the
oceanfront over the holiday weekend. Police and National Guard
troops carrying clubs dispersed the crowd after about 100 downtown
stores were damaged by looters and vandals.
   ``We welcome the investigation,'' said Virginia Beach Mayor
Meyera E. Oberndorf. ``I thought that our police used extraordinary
restraint.''
   Preliminary police counts showed that 1,235 people were charged
with 1,346 offenses, most of them involving traffic violations,
public drinking or disorderly conduct. Police arrested 220 people.
At least 43 people were injured, including 30 police officers or
National Guardsmen.
   Merchants who suffered millions of dollars in property damage
said they were not sure how to prevent a recurrence next year, but
some said they would consider closing Labor Day weekend.
   ``I do not want to see a return of this group or any group this
large,'' said William L. Dillon, owner of Abbey Road Restaurant and
president of the Virginia Beach Restaurant Association.
   Several motel owners said tourists had canceled reservations
after hearing about the rioting.
   Steve Luchik, general manager of the Holiday Inn on the Ocean,
said his hotel has lost more than $30,000 from cancellations in the
past few days.
   ``Now I'm getting groups cancelling, not only individuals,''
Luchik said, explaining that a Chicago business organization just
canceled its reservations.
   ``Their last words to me were, `When things cool down there,
we'll reconsider.' I said, `Well, it's over.' They didn't care,''
Luchik said.
   ``We've got to promote a safe, comfortable, relaxing atmosphere''
to lure tourists back, said James Capps, president of the Virginia
Beach Hotel and Motel Association.
   Flo McDaniel, executive director of the innkeepers' association,
said it could take years for the city to restore its tarnished image.
   ``We still have the surf. We still have all the things going for
us we had before,'' she said. ``What we have gotten is about $100
million in adverse advertising.''
</TEXT>
