<FIRST>r w AM-PennyStockFraud     09-06 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Penny Stock Fraud,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Penny Stock Swindles Are No. 1 Threat to Small Investors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American investors have been cheated out of at
least $2 billion a year by crooked schemes involving low cost, high
risk penny stocks, according to a survey by state securities
regulators on Wednesday.
   ``Penny stock swindles are now the No. 1 threat of fraud and
abuse facing small investors in the United States,'' said the report
on a 50-state survey by the North American Securities Administrators
Association (NASAA).
   The report comes just as Congress turns to examine the problem.
   The House telecommunications and finance subcommittee has
scheduled a hearing Thursday on the effect of penny stock swindles
on small investors.
   ``The likelihood of losing money in penny stocks now runs at
about 90 percent,'' said Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., the
subcommittee chairman. ``Penny stocks make a night at the casino
look like a shrewd investment,'' he added.
   Markey's subcommittee was scheduled to hear testimony from a
convicted penny stock swindler with alleged organized crimes ties, a
Powder Springs, Ga., couple who were victimized by penny stock scam
artists and John Baldwin, director of the Utah Division of
Securities and president of NASAA, a Washington-based organization
of state-level securities regulators.
   Penny stocks, inexpensive but highly risky securities that
usually aren't listed on stock exchanges, are legal, but they are
usually issued by new companies with an untested or uneven earnings
history.
   While their price, a few cents up to a few dollars, makes them an
attractive to small investors with limited funds, they pose a risk
because information is often hard to obtain and fraudulent claims
are difficult to dispute.
   ``The penny stock industry increasingly is dominated by utterly
worthless or highly dubious securities offerings that are
systematically manipulated by repeat offenders of state and federal
securities laws,'' the NASAA report said.
   The report went on to note that investors in legitimate penny
stocks ``are believed to lose all or some of their investment 70
percent of the time and the presence of fraud pushes up that figure
to 90 percent.''
   While penny stock fraud is not new, the report noted, it has
grown from the the phony mining stock scams of the 1940s and 1950s
that were confined mainly to the Far West, to widespread interstate
schemes.
   In Florida, only 5 percent of the registered brokers specialize
in penny stocks but they accounted for 40 percent of investor
complaints in fiscal year 1988-1989.
   According to the 50-state survey NASAA conducted:
   _Pending state-level probes of penny stock schemes rose 97
percent from 1987 to 1988, from 375 to 737;
   _The number of investigations into penny stocks that state
regulators have concluded jumped from 262 in 1987 to 395 in 1988;
   _Consumer complaints about penny stocks have risen from 1,767 in
1987 to 2,660 in 1988.
   ``Several states have indicated that their offices have been
swamped so far in 1989 with new penny stock investor complaints,''
according to the 98-page report.
   The surge in investor complaints has been echoed in Securities
and Exchange Commission statistics. The federal agency, which
oversees the markets in stocks, bonds and other securities, said it
received 1,510 penny stock complaints in all of fiscal year 1988 and
has already gotten 2,462 in the first half of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
