<FIRST>r w AM-Giuliani'sSuccessor 1stLd-Writethru a066sWriter 09-06
0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Giuliani's Successor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nominates Manhattan Lawyer as U.S. Attorney</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with comment from Giuliani, Obermaier; inserts byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Otto G. Obermaier, a Manhattan defense lawyer
who specializes in white-collar cases, was nominated Wednesday to
succeed Rudolph Giuliani as U.S. attorney for the Southern District
of New York.
   President Bush announced his nomination of Obermaier in a news
release. Obermaier said he was ``delighted'' to be nominated.
   Giuliani stepped down Jan. 31 to run for the Republican
nomination for mayor of New York, Since then, Benito Romano has been
the acting U.S. attorney.
   Obermaier, 53, was recommended for the job in January by Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., over the objections of Giuliani.
   Giuliani opposed Obermaier because several of his firm's clients
are targets of federal insider-trading investigations. Giuliani said
he would present his views to the Justice Department, which reviews
a candidate for a federal prosecutor's job before the president
sends the nomination to the Senate for its approval.
   On Wednesday, spokesman Charles Perkins said Giuliani ``wishes
him well in the confirmation process'' and ``believes he's qualified
for the position.''
   Shortly after his nomination, Obermaier said he did not think
that his work as a defense lawyer would create conflicts for him as
a federal prosecutor. He said he would step aside if, as U.S.
attorney, he encountered a case in which his firm had a role.
   ``I don't think they're all that numerous, but clearly I'm
ethically obligated to do that,'' he said.
   Obermaier was quoted in the National Law Journal in 1987 as
saying securities violations were being handled too often by
prosecutors as crimes rather than by the Securities and Exchange
Commission as civil matters.
   On Wednesday, he said that his comments ``certainly represented
the thinking at the time.'' He said he could not name any recent
Wall Street cases that he believed had been wrongly prosecuted.
   As U.S. attorney, Giuliani was at the forefront of investigating
Wall Street scandals, prosecuting numerous cases of insider trading
and stock manipulation.
</TEXT>
