<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Bribery     09-06 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Bribery,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Uzbek Premier Given 9 Years for Bribery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former premier of the Uzbekistan republic was
convicted of bribery Wednesday and sentenced a labor camp for nine
years in the latest episode of a corruption scandal that led to the
Kremlin.
   Tass said a court sitting in Moscow found N. Khudaiberdiev,
premier from 1971-84, guilty of taking more than 15,000 rubles in
bribes and giving bribes of 50,000 rubles. The ruble figures are
equivalent to $23,000 and $80,000 at the official rate of exchange.
   Several regional party officials in Uzbekistan have been executed
for corruption since trials began last year.
   Testimony linked Khudaiberdiev to a 50,000-ruble bribe given Yuri
Churbanov, son-in-law of the late President Leonid I. Brezhnev, who
was convicted in December and given a 12-year prison sentence, the
official news agency reported.
   It said the court ordered Khudaiberdiev's property confiscated
and sent him to a strict-regime labor camp.
   The defendant was quoted as telling the court bribery had so
enveloped the Uzbekistan government and Communist Party that
officials had to participate ``in order to live and work more or
less normally.''
   Two prosecutors, Telman Gdlyan and Nikolai Ivanov, became heroes
by uncovering the trail of corruption that led from Uzbekistan to
Brezhnev's Kremlin, where Churbanov was first deputy interior
minister.
   After both were elected to the new parliament this year, however,
their tactics came under criticism and they were taken off the case.
   Tass said supporters of Gdlyan and Ivanov attended
Khudaiberdiev's trial, and the judge had to caution them to stop
interfering.
</TEXT>
