<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees     09-06 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Diplomats Try to Dissuade Would-be Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German diplomats set up office near
a refugee camp Wednesday to try to persuade thousands of their
countrymen they had nothing to fear at home and to give up dreams of
a new life in the West.
   West Germany meanwhile expressed hope a solution to the refugee
crisis was near.
   By late Wednesday, about 5,600 East Germans hoping to flee West
had registered to do so, said officials of West German charities who
have helped to care for the refugees since mid-August. Hungarian
charity officials said a sixth refugee camp had been opened, with
more planned if needed.
   Thirty East Germans, apparently frustrated at waiting for a
promised freedom convoy from Hungary to the West, fled illegally
Tuesday night to Austria, Red Cross officials there said.
   The number going over the border zoomed in recent days,
indicating refugee desperation over recent discouraging Hungarian
statements hinting that the start of an organized mass exodus could
be weeks away.
   Hungary has partially cleared the border of barbed wire and other
barriers.
   West German officials had seemed optimistic last week that mass
transit westward could begin in days. They now are more cautious,
but several suggested that a move west still was not too far away
for the East Germans.
   The official MTI news agency quoted West German Ambassador
Alexander Arnot as saying ``the refugee situation will be resolved
in the forseeable future.''
   In Bonn, where West German officials have been negotiating with
hardline communist East German leaders over the refugee standoff,
government speaker Hans Klein said East Germany showed no
flexibility.
   But Foreign Ministry spokesman Juergen Chrobog said Bonn remains
confident of a solution soon.
   Hungary has angered East Germany, its Soviet bloc ally, by
effectively breaking an agreement obliging it to return all East
Germans trying to flee.
   It has also pledged they would be allowed to leave for West
Germany, which grants them automatic citizenship. But Budapest's
communist leaders are thought to be seeking at least grudging East
German acquiescence before giving the go-ahead for the mass exodus.
   Few young working East Germans can travel to the West legally,
but are relatively free to go to Hungary. More than 6,000 East
Germans have fled through Austria to West Germany since Hungary
began clearing its westernmost border in May.
   East Berlin promised refugees they face no persecution if they
return.
   First Secretary Dieter Grahmann of the East German Embassy on
Tuesday began distributing leaflets at the Zugliget refugee camp
repeating his country's promises, but left quickly after an angry
crowd gathered. He returned Wednesday, and set up with a colleague
in a car trailer across from the camp.
   Around them were cars of East German refugees _ some with bumper
stickers of a European cigarette company declaring ``Let's Go
West,'' or of a West German charter airline saying ``Nothing Like
Getting Out of Here.''
   Small groups gathered near the trailer shortly after it was
manned at 9:45 a.m., but no one approached and several would-be
refugees were openly derisive.
   ``They must really be stupid to come here,'' said a heavy-set
East German from Dresden. ``But I guess they have no choice, it's
either victory or Siberia for them.''
   Grahmann told reporters any refugees were free ``to discuss the
situation'' with him or a colleague.
   But several East Germans said after the trailer closed for the
day at noon that the two diplomats had had little to do.
   ``I didn't see one person going in there, outside of Western
journalists,'' said the Dresden man, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. The East German Embassy said the trailer would reopen
Thursday.
   Hungarian charity official Csilla von Boeselager said camp
residents were asked to refrain from ``unwise actions'' against
diplomats or trailer.
   Hungarian Red Cross officials at nearby Csilleberc camp said an
East German diplomat carrying leaflets was barred entry, because
``it would have been difficult to guarantee the safety of said East
German,'' MTI reported.
</TEXT>
