<FIRST>u w AM-Strohs-Forests     09-06 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Strohs-Forests,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stroh Officials Drops Sponsorship Of Audubon Specials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Stroh Brewery Co. said
Wednesday the Detroit-based company was withdrawing its sponsorship
of National Audubon Society television specials but insisted the
action had nothing to do with a threatened boycott by Northwest
loggers.
   ``We sought to keep these issues separate and unrelated,'' Peter
Stroh, said in a statement, adding the decision to drop
underwiriting of the series reflected the company's mounting
financial problems.
   Northwest loggers, upset with an upcoming program on the region's
ancient forests, had begun a loosely-organized campaign in which
they threatened to boycott the brewery's products unless Stroh
dropped its support for the specials.
   Environmental sources, who asked to remain anonymous, had earlier
said that Stroh requested that changes be made in the program,
``Ancient Forests: Rage Over Trees,'' and when the Audubon Society
refused the company decided to drop its $600,000 in underwriting.
   ``It had been the intention of the Stroh Brewery Co. to first
resolve the issue in the Pacific Northwest regarding the upcoming
special before discussing our ability to continue underwriting the
World of Audubon Specials,'' Stroh said.
   Stroh said his company was ``diligently'' looking for financial
partners and ``the fact we were reviewing our sponsorship of these
specials was due to questions raised from our ongoing discussions
with other brewers.
   ``However, in light of the confusion and uncertainty which has
arisen since the issues became intertwined, we have decided it would
be best for us and for the National Audubon Society to announce we
are now going to relinquish our sponsorship of future programs
already produced in order to facilitate the Audubon's search for a
successor sponsor.''
   The timber industry and environmentalists have been locked in a
bitter struggle for months over future logging in the Northwest's
old-growth forests, which provide prime habitat for the northern
spotted owl.
   The Audubon Society is among the environmental groups that have
sought to have the owl protected as a threatened or endangered
species and logging in the ancient forests halted.
   Audubon Society officials have insisted that the special on the
ancient forests, which will be shown on cable television on Sept. 24
and on public television later, was ``fair and balanced.''
   Stroh has provided about half the funding for the four-show
series with the balance coming from Turner Broadcasting System.
   Kirsten White, a Turner spokeswoman, said Wednesday that her
company had also received calls from loggers concerned about the
content of the show.
   White said Turner had no plans to drop the show.
   ``It will still air,'' she said.
</TEXT>
