<FIRST>u i AM-AuschwitzConvent 2dLd-Writethru a0728 09-06 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz Convent, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0728,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Commission Says More Talks Needed on Auschwitz Convent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with negotiator comment after interview quoting
Glemp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic Church commission said
Wednesday more talks are needed to resolve the issue of the convent
at the Auschwitz death camp, which has severely strained relations
with the world's Jews.
   Cardinal Franciszek Macharski, whose archdiocese includes the
camp, has angered Jews by refusing to honor an agreement of Feb. 22,
1987, to move the convent to an interfaith prayer center farther
away.
   In a statement released by the official news agency PAP, the
Commission for Dialogue with Judaism said: ``The conflict around the
Carmelite convent ... has led to an almost complete breakdown of
Christian-Jewish dialogue in the world.
   ``Resumption of dialogue seems impossible without solving this
conflict. All this confirms the urgent need of building the
(interfaith) center. However, we state with regret the idea of the
center has not received appropriate interest and understanding on
the Jewish side.
   ``Taking up talks in the spirit of the Geneva meetings, without
additional conditions, will allow, we trust, the finding of
realistic possibilities of building the center.''
   The commission of clergy and lay intellectuals said, ``There is a
special obligation to take advantage of all possible means to remove
the existing tensions and conflicts'' because of the camp's
significance as a memorial.
   An estimated 4 million people died at Auschwitz, 2.5 million of
them Jews. The Carmelite convent of 14 nuns is in a former theater,
used by the Nazis as a storehouse, just outside the fence.
   Jews say it is deeply offensive to have Chrisitan symbols,
including a tall wooden cross, at a place where millions of Jews
were killed in the Nazi extermination program.
   According to the commission, Cardinal Macharski's statement
refusing to uphold the 1987 agreement was not inconsistent with
previous church positions. It said Macharski felt obliged to act
because polemics and violent protest had become a threat to the
interfaith center.
   In a newspaper interview published Saturday in Italy, Cardinal
Jozef Glemp, Poland's Catholic primate, said he agreed the nuns
should not be moved and indicated he would like more negotiations
with Jewish leaders.
   Theo Klein, who led the Jewish delegation at the Geneva talks,
said renegotiation was out of the question.
   Cardinals Godfried Danneels of Brussels, Jean-Marie Lustiger of
Paris and Albert Decourtray of Lyon, who signed the agreement along
with Macharski, issued a joint statement saying it must be carried
out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
