<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Poland     09-06 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Poland,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simon Introduces Aid Package For Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to ease the debt burden of Poland's
new non-communist government and to provide an aid fund of up to
$300 million a year was introduced on Wednesday by Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill.
   The proposal, which is significantly larger than the $100 million
in U.S. assistance proposed earlier this year by President Bush,
also would include $25 million to modernize Poland's telephone
system.
   Simon told the Senate his request is based on conversations in
Poland last year with Solidarity union leader Lech Walesa and other
Polish leaders and officials.
   ``I think it is important that the United States act and act
swiftly and act generously,'' Simon told the Senate. ``If Poland can
shift over to a free-enterprise system, that will affect Hungary and
eventually the Soviet Union as well. It is going to change the
political map of the world.''
   Simon said his proposal would suspend interest on Poland's debt
to U.S. financial institutions for three years and reduce it for an
additional two years.
   Poland, Simon said, has a $39 billion foreign debt, of which some
8 percent is owed to U.S. banks.
   He said diplomatic representatives of at least two other nations
with outstanding loans to Poland have expressed interest in the plan
to ease interest payments.
   The Simon proposal calls for the creation of a revolving fund of
$300 million a year over a three-year period.
   He said $100 million of the total would be earmarked for
agricultural purposes, especially grain production.
   He said the plan includes safeguards permitting the president to
suspend the aid program at any time.
   ``This is not a substitute for Poland facing its own problems,''
Simon said.
   ``But what we have now is a very critical time period in which we
have to move,'' he said. ``America must come through.''
</TEXT>
