<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0685 09-06 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa's Appeals Received Cautiously by German Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Thatcher comment, details.
Picks up graf 9 pvs, `Changing over ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German businessmen and
bankers told Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Wednesday they are
willing to help revive Poland's economy, but said the Poles want too
much too soon.
   Walesa said he understood the caution, but renewed his appeal for
more West German investment.
   ``The banking experts at the moment still have reservations
because the conditions in my country are not good,'' he said to
journalists after meeting with the Eastern Committee, an influential
industry organization that coordinates business dealings in the East
bloc.
   Walesa said he told the committee: ``We want to work intensely
with you. We want to invite you to help build ... a different
economic system.''
   Otto Wolff von Amerongen, head of the Eastern Committee, said,
however, that ``wishes on the Polish side'' for a comprehensive
program of new credits cannot be met.
   In London, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's office said she had
urged the United States, West Germany and France to give Poland more
support. A spokesman said she sent messages to President Bush,
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and President Francois Mitterrand saying:
   ``There is a historic opportunity for the West to help Poland's
reforms succeed and demonstrate that a country can successfully make
the transition from communism and from an entirely state-run
economy.''
   Wolff, the Eastern Committee chairman, told journalists ``all
relevant political forces in Poland should themselves reach a
consensus over the necessary program to cure the economy.''
   ``Western capital aid should only be one element'' of the
program, he said, adding that the new, Solidarity-led government
cannot expect quick investment by West Germans because of the huge
financial risk involved while Poland is overhauling its its economy.
   ``Changing over from one system to another is more difficult than
starting from scratch, as is the case here,'' Wolff said. ``It would
be an illusion to believe this could be achieved quickly.''
   Nonetheless, Wolff promised Walesa he could count on West German
assistance in rebuilding the Polish economy.
   He said his committee would be consulting with Polish joint
venture specialists about ways to improve their country's investment
climate.
   Walesa arrived in West Germany on Tuesday for five days of talks
with politicians and businesspeople to center on economic aid and
reform in Poland.
   Poland's economy suffers from widespread shortages, more than 100
percent annual inflation, a $39 billion foreign debt, and
unprofitable and outmoded industries.
   Earlier in the day, in a speech to labor union officials, Walesa
appealed to Western countries to ease terms of Poland's foreign debt.
   He also said Solidarity is under tremendous pressure from the
Polish people now that it controls the government.
   ``Our country is a total economic catastrophe,'' Walesa said in a
speech before the national coordinating committee of the powerful
German Federation of Labor Unions.
   Since Solidarity activist Tadeusz Mazowiecki became the East
bloc's first non-Communist government leader last month, Poles have
turned their hopes for improved living standards to the trade union.
   ``Some doubt whether Solidarity really has an economic program. I
want to give these people an answer. We know full well what we are
striving for,'' he said.
   Before Walesa spoke, Ernst Breit, chairman of the Federation of
Labor Unions, called on the West German government to make a quick
decision on financial assistance for Poland.
   Referring to Nazi Germany's invasion of Poland 50 years ago that
started World War II, Breit said, ``Germans have a moral
responsibility to take the leading role in helping Poland achieve
economic stability.''
</TEXT>
