<FIRST>u w AM-Oceans-Atmosphere 1stLd-Writethru   09-06 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oceans-Atmosphere, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0699,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Boosts NOAA Spending</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS start of fiscal year in 2nd graf from ``1990'' to Oct.
1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday approved the spending of
up to $529 million next year for ocean and coastal programs, far
more than President Bush had asked for the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration.
   The measure, sent to the Senate on a 343-44 vote, included $197
million for research, nearly double Bush's request for the fiscal
year that begins Oct. 1, and $173 million for coastal managment,
mapping and pollution monitoring.
   The research money includes $64 million for the Sea Grant program
and $14 million for the National Undersea Research program, neither
of which was funded in Bush's budget request. Another $8 million was
authorized for Great Lakes water quality and environmental research.
   On a voice vote, the lawmakers added a provision authorizing $54
million over the next five years to build a marine research center
in Baltimore, Md.
   In separate action, the House also provided $2.6 billion over the
next three years for the National Weather Service, a new nationwide
network of Doppler weather radar systems, and research into how to
improve prediction of tornadoes and hurricanes, acid rain, ozone
depletion and climate change. The vote on that measure was 380 to 1.
   Of that amount, $866 million is for operation of the Landsat
satellite program, the Geostationary satellite system and the polar
orbiting satellite program.
</TEXT>
