<FIRST>r a AM-MaritalSodomy     09-06 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marital Sodomy,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Georgia Sodomy Law Cannot Be Applied to Consenting Married
Couples</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY L. CARTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia's 156-year-old law that makes it a
felony for a husband and wife to engage in sodomy cannot be applied
to consenting married couples, a judge ruled Wednesday.
   ``Government has no business with a married couple's private
consensual sexual practices,'' wrote DeKalb County Superior Court
Judge Robert Castellani.
   In his five-page decision, Castellani said James D. Moseley had
been imprisoned illegally more than 18 months after being convicted
for violating that law.
   Moseley, 35, a carpenter, had been sentenced to two years. He was
ordered released on bond by Castellani last week pending his
decision.
   ``This court believes the petitioner's right to marital and
domestic privacy has been violated by the sodomy law as applied to
him,'' Castellani wrote.
   Moseley had been charged with two counts of rape, two counts of
aggravated oral sodomy and two counts of aggravated anal sodomy in
February 1988 after his common-law wife, Bette Roberts, filed
complaints against him, saying he had forced himself on her after
they were separated.
   He denied using force but testified that the couple had engaged
in oral sex with Ms. Roberts' consent. He was acquitted on five
counts but was convicted on a lesser charge of oral sodomy.
   Castellani noted that during recent U.S. Supreme Court
considerations that upheld application of the sodomy law against
homosexuals, both the majority analysis and state Attorney General
Michael Bowers ``recognize the problems in applying this law to
married consenting couples.''
   ``Insofar as (the judge) holds as a matter of law that the sodomy
statute can't be applied to a married couple, that ... is exactly
what we had said,'' Bowers said Wednesday.
   But he said a decision on whether to appeal the ruling would be
delayed until he has a chance to examine it fully.
   The state had argued that Moseley should remain in jail because
``the record ... supports an inference the victim did not consent to
the sodomy,'' Castellani wrote. But the judge said the jury's
acquittal of Moseley on the rape and aggravated sodomy charges meant
it decided no force had been involved.
   ``We're very pleased with (the) decision. Our client is now
free,'' said Julie Edelson, one of the American Civil Liberties
Union lawyers who argued Moseley's case in court.
   Moseley could not be reached for comment Wednesday. Telephone
messages left for him with the ACLU were not returned.
   He had said last week that Ms. Roberts had filed charges against
him as part of a lengthy domestic dispute.
   ``I only did what she wanted me to do, and then she used it
against me to get custody of the kids,'' he said. He said he was
granted no visiting rights to see his sons.
   Ms. Roberts responded by repeating her assertions that Moseley
forced himself on her.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0203 </DOCNO>
