<FIRST>r w AM-Barry-Thornburgh     09-06 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Thornburgh,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Declines To Meet With Washington Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh will not meet
with Mayor Marion Barry to discuss news leaks in a grand jury probe
into Barry's ties to a convicted drug dealer, a spokesman for
Thornburgh said on Wednesday.
   ``It's not appropriate for the attorney general to meet with him
at this time,'' Thornburgh spokesman David Runkel said.
   He declined to elaborate.
   Barry, angered over news reports that former city employee
Charles Lewis has told prosecutors he and Barry smoked crack cocaine
together, had said he wanted to meet with Thornburgh to ask him to
investigate alleged Justice Department leaks to the news media.
   Thornburgh's refusal to meet with Barry is the second legal
disappointment for the mayor in as many days. On Tuesday, U.S.
Attorney Jay B. Stephens said that he is forbidden by law from
releasing Barry's testimony before a federal grand jury
investigating his ties to Lewis.
   Barry, who spent more than five hours testifying on his visits to
Lewis' hotel room last December, had sought to release the testimony
in an effort to prove that he had truthfully denied using drugs with
Lewis.
   Barry has steadfastly maintained he is not the target or the
subject of the Lewis probe, but Stephens cited a law that bars the
testimony of potential witnesses from being released prior to a
trial.
   Barry spokeswoman Lurma Rackley said the mayor has not received a
formal denial from Thornburgh on their proposed meeting and will not
comment until he has.
   Thornburgh is already investigating whether Justice officials
leaked information on a preliminary FBI investigation into alleged
payroll irregularities in the office of Rep. William H. Gray III,
D-Pa.
   The news reports, which came in late May as Gray was positioning
himself to run for House Democratic whip, prompted Gray to charge
that the leaks had been politically motivated.
   Thornburgh promptly wrote a letter to Gray telling him the matter
would be investigated, although he rejected Gray's request that an
independent prosecutor be appointed to look into the matter.
   Gray ultimately was elected to the whip's post, which is the
third-ranking House leadership post, while Justice officials are
still trying to determine the source of the news leaks.
   Stephens has already asked the Justice Department to investigate
whether the reports on Lewis were leaked from his office.
</TEXT>
