<FIRST>u i AM-SoccerViolence 3rdLd-Writethru a0755 09-06 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Violence, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0755,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 116 British Soccer Hooligans on Rampage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 10 beginning: `British soccer ...' to include ban
not applying to national team. Picks up graf 11 pvs, `Wedensday's events
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they arrested 116 British
soccer fans who rampaged through Stockholm's shopping district
Wednesday before a World Cup qualifying match.
   Police Inspector Gunnar Skold said 71 other people were arrested,
including four Britons, outside Rasunda Stadium during and after the
Sweden-England game, which ended in a 0-0 tie. One of those arrested
was hospitalized.
   ``It was less than we had expected,'' Police Superintendent Sture
Hoglund told Swedish television.
   Hoglund said about 1,000 British fans watched the game at the
stadium from a separate standing area and no incidents were reported.
   Skold told The Associated Press the fans seized in downtown
Stockholm probably would not have been admitted to the game in any
event because most of them had no tickets and appeared drunk.
   The rowdies, apparently teen-agers for the most part, ran through
the shopping area shouting abuse, slapping passers-by and ripping
clothing from stores' outside display racks. Police with riot
shields gave chase and scuffled with them.
   Skold said the arrested Britons would be sent home as soon as
possible.
   Scattered incidents of brawling and vandalism were reported
earlier in restaurants and on trains, as about 2,000 visitors
filtered through the city awaiting the match.
   The Swedes had prepared for a dose of British soccer hooliganism
after one fan drowned Monday when he jumped overboard from a ferry
in the North Sea that was bringing hundreds of fans to Stockholm.
British police said he was under the influence of drugs and panicked
when companions sprayed him with a fire extinguisher.
   British soccer clubs were banned from playing in European club
competition after their fans were blamed for a 1986 riot-sparked
stampede in Belgium that killed 39 specators, mainly Italians. The
ban did not apply to the national team.
   Wednesday's events in Stockholm could affect a decision earlier
this year by the UEFA, the French-based European soccer clubs'
governing body, to readmit the British clubs next year if
troublemakers are brought under control.
   Security was unprecedented for a Swedish sporting event. Police
assigned 600 officers to the stadium in suburban Stockholm, and
Swedish Radio said authorities were ready to stop the match if
trouble broke out.
   The Swedish Football Association said that at the request of its
British counterpart, it withheld nearly 4,000 tickets it normally
would have put on sale in Britain.
   ``The (British) FA told us they didn't want any tickets sold in
England because of the trouble with hooligans when England has
played in other countries abroad,'' said Lena Linborg, the
association's ticket manager.
   Specators were to subjected to body searches, and television
cameras were placed to monitor the crowd. Riot fences surrounded the
stadium.
   Five Britons were arrested Monday after they rampaged through a
restaurant. Three were released and two were held on charges of
assault and causing serious damage.
   On Wednesday, about 20 fans helped themselves to beer at a
self-service cafe without paying. One was apprehended by a patrolman
and the rest fled.
   Ferry companies and travel agencies refused to accept group
bookings from Britain to Sweden preceding the match. The Tudor Arms,
which claims to be the only English pub in Stockholm, closed its
doors to avoid trouble.
   ``Everybody recognizes there is a problem with the hooligans in
England,'' the British charge d'affaires, Brian Austin, said in a
radio interview.
   Austin, responding to calls in the Swedish media to expel the
British soccer fans, said it is difficult to distinguish between
``people who want to see the match and who genuinely like football,
and the other sort.''
</TEXT>
