<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     09-06 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Squabbling Over Vice Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A split in the main opposition bloc
appeared to widen Wednesday over the choice of a former Sandinista
labor minister as its vice presidential candidate in February
elections.
   The National Opposition Union asked the Supreme Electoral Council
to extend by two weeks the Friday deadline for applying for legal
recognition as a bloc, Silviano Matamoros of the National
Conservative Party said Tuesday.
   The request indicated the coalition was not sure how many of its
14 parties, ranging from communists to conservatives, would stick
together for the Feb. 25, 1990, general election.
   Since the Opposition Union picked its ticket on Saturday, the
leading topic for radio talk shows, television and newspapers has
been the choice of politician Virgilio Godoy over businessman
Enrique Bolanos.
   Few people have disputed the choice of Violeta Barrios de
Chamorro, publisher of the opposition newspaper La Prensa, as the
Opposition Union's presidential candidate.
   How the discord is resolved will greatly influence, if not
determine, the election results. Only a united opposition could
unseat the Sandinista government.
   None of the 20 opposition Nicaraguan parties could
single-handedly win a race. Three parties outside the Opposition
Union have announced their own candidates but their power is
considered negligible.
   President Daniel Ortega is expected to run for re-election but
the government has yet to announce its ticket.
   The two figures at the center of the Opposition Union feud are
trying to avoid a split.
   Godoy, an able politician, is lobbying all sides trying to glue
the bloc back together.
   Bolanos is avoiding the public light.
   When asked to comment on the Opposition Union infighting, Bolanos
said: ``It's not prudent. My opinion is of no import at this time.
... I'm simply observing, nothing more.''
   He said he might speak publicly on Friday during ``Free
Enterprise Day,'' designated by the Superior Council of Private
Enterprise. He is a former president of the council.
   Godoy, president of the Independent Liberal Party, said he was
talking to various parties ``to see how we can contribute to avoid''
further squabbling.
   ``I think we'll be able to overcome this (so) that the blood
won't reach the river,'' Godoy said.
   Cracks in the Opposition Union began to show late Saturday, just
minutes after Godoy was chosen with Mrs. Chamorro. The ticket
obtained 10 votes out of a possible 14.
   Leaders of three parties abstaining left the meeting after the
final vote. One party's ballot was annulled.
   On Tuesday, Matamoros said the Opposition Union's politicial
council was reviewing the votes because there was a dispute over the
way a fifth party marked its ballot.
   Godoy is linked to an unpopular system of salary levels created
while he was labor minister from 1979 to 1984.
   The business community felt wages for workers were too high,
professionals thought their salaries were too low and most people
thought the issue was best decided between employer and employee.
   Godoy was thought to balance the ticket with Mrs. Chamorro, whose
membership in the Nicaraguan aristocracy pleases conservatives.
   But some have said Godoy's politics are too far to the left.
</TEXT>
