<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Plane     09-06 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Plane,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crews Rescue Survivors of Plane That Crash-Landed in Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SERRA DO CACHIMBO, Brasil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue helicopters on Wednesday
airlifted to safety the survivors of a Varig jetliner that
crash-landed in the Amazon rain forest, killing at least 10 of the
54 people aboard.
   ``It's incredible that we came out alive,'' said Regia Acevedo,
who was thrown from the plane Sunday night with her husband when the
Boeing 737-200 went down about 1,050 miles northwest of Rio de
Janeiro.
   The plane ``seemed to bounce'' when it first hit the tops of
100-foot trees, survivors said. It cut a 120-foot by 300-foot swath
through the jungle and both wings were ripped off but the fuselage
remained nearly intact, they said.
   ``It was as if a giant claw had scratched the body of the plane.
First there was a deafening screech and then a silence, and then
absolute darkness,'' said Ms. Acevedo, 29.
   ``I thought, `My God, I'm going to die!'' said Jose Maria
Gadelha. ``Suddenly there was a flash of lightning, I lost
consciousness, and when I woke up I was outside the plane and
alive.''
   ``We were ready to die but the hand of God guided our descent,''
said Epaminondas de Sousa Chaves, 36, one of four people who walked
through the jungle to a remote ranch Tuesday to report the location
of the plane.
   Medical teams first reached the crash site Tuesday night, but
officials decided to wait until first light Wednesday to start
removing survivors.
   The survivors were taken 28 miles to a ranch, where a
Brazilian-made, twin-engine Bandeirante plane took off from a dirt
airstrip and flew to the Serra do Cachimbo air force base, 185 miles
away in neighboring Para state, said an air force spokesman, Col.
Jose Maria dos Santos.
   He said two passengers died Wednesday, bringing the death count
to 10. He said a man trapped in the wreckage died Wednesday morning,
while a woman airlifted from the crash site died later on a rescue
plane en route to Brasilia.
   Passenger Marinez Coimbra said those killed were sitting closest
to the cockpit. ``Those in the front suffered the worst,'' she said
in a televised interview.
   Six people were in serious condition.
   The plane disappeared Sunday after taking off from Maraba on the
last leg of a regularly scheduled flight between the southeastern
city of Sao Paulo and Belem.
   An Air Force Ministry spokesman, Col. Ronaldo Borges, said the
pilot had reported problems in the navigational system and the plane
strayed far off course.
   Epaminondas de Sousa Chaves said the plane had been flying in
circles for 90 minutes before the crash.
   ``The captain ... said that he was having trouble finding
Belem,'' he said. ``I got nervous then and started praying.''
   ``Minutes later, with a calm voice, the pilot asked for
forgiveness and told us ... we had 15 minutes of fuel left and he
couldn't see a single clear spot in the jungle.
   ``Suddenly, the engines shut down and I don't know if 10, 15 or
one minute passed. It was agony.''
   The Brazilian airline did not give the cause of the accident.
Varig president Helio Smidt did not rule out a navigational error,
but said, ``We shouldn't jump to quick conclusions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
