<SECOND>AM-Italy-Terrorists,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Abu Nidal Member Arrested in Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian police arrested a member of the Abu Nidal
terrorist group during a major sweep aimed at breaking up remnants
of the Italian Red Brigades, authorities said Wednesday.
   Khalid Hassan Hussein Birawi Thamer was one of 11 people arrested
in the month-old operation against the Red Brigades that has
involved both Italian and French police.
   Thamer, 29, a Jordanian, was arrested Tuesday in Rome, police
said. Three Italians believed to be Red Brigades members were also
arrested Tuesday, police said at a news conference Wednesday.
   Thamer was arrested at Frankfurt airport in February 1985 with 23
pounds of explosives, as well as detonators and falsified documents
identical to those used in attacks by the Abu Nidal Palestinian
group.
   He was extradited to Italy on charges of involvement in Abu Nidal
assaults, but authorities released him from prison in August 1988.
   Abu Nidal's group has been blamed for more than 100 attacks
across Europe, Asia and the Middle East since 1972.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, split from Yasser
Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization in 1973.
   Police did not clarify the alleged connection between Thamer and
the Red Brigades, a leftist group that carried out scores of violent
attacks in the 1970s and early 1980s aimed at toppling the Italian
government.
   Thamer and the three Italians arrested Tuesday were charged with
subversive association and participation in an outlawed group,
police said.
   The Italians were identified as Caterina Calia, 29, detained in
Rome; Riccardo Maria Antonini, 37, arrested in the northern city of
Viareggio; and Alberto Marino, 23, detained in Cesa in southern
Italy.
</TEXT>
