<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     09-06 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka President Asks Restraint in Dealing with Extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa on
Wednesday asked security forces to restrain themselves when dealing
with Sinhalese extremists who are trying to topple his government,
officials said.
   ``In other words, the president told the military and police not
to shoot first, treat those arrested under law, and win the
confidence of people,'' the government officials said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Opposition politicians, human rights groups and residents accuse
the military of killing hundreds of civilians during crackdowns on
extremists of the People's Liberation Front. The government denies
it, but senior officials privately admit killings by pro-government
vigilante groups.
   Premadasa's appeal came at a meeting in Colombo with senior
military, police and intelligence officers, the officials said.
   ``Premadasa advised them to act firmly against terrorism, but to
always remember they are dealing with their own brothers and
sisters,'' they said.
   The officials said the meeting was called to brief officers on a
proposed meeting of all political parties on Sept. 13 aimed at
resolving this island nation's ethnic troubles.
   Premadasa invited the Front to the meeting. It has not yet
responded. The ultranationalist group rejected earlier government
peace offers.
   Military officials said Wednesday that in the latest crackdown,
security forces arrested 224 suspected Front members since Monday
and that 153 militants surrendered.
   The arrests were made in central and southern Sri Lanka, the
Sinhalese heartland where the militant campaign is centered.
   The northeast is ravaged by a Tamil insurgency for an independent
nation that the government tried to end with an India-sponsored
peace accord in 1987.
   The accord, supervised by Indian peacekeeping troops, angered the
Sinhalese militants, who complained it conceded too much to the
minority Tamils. They began a violent campaign that the government
says has claimed 5,000 lives. The militants also said the Indian
presence compromised Sri Lanka's independence.
   The 6-year-old Tamil war has killed 11,000 more people, including
1,000 Indian soldiers.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, say they are discriminated in jobs
and education by the mainly Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people, the
Sinhalese 75 percent.
   India became involved because of political pressures from its own
60 million Tamils, most of whom live in southern Tamil Nadu state. A
narrow strip of sea separates Tamil Nadu from Sri Lanka.
</TEXT>
