<FIRST>r a AM-LesbianSlaying     09-06 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lesbian Slaying,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Testifies She Killed Lesbian Lover in Self Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman on trial for the murder of
her lesbian lover testified Wednesday that she shot to death her
companion of 11 years to defend herself from abuse.
   The so-called ``battered spouse'' syndrome is being used by
defense attorneys in the first-degree murder trial of Annette Green,
the first time in which the psychological state has been applied to
a lesbian case, attorneys say.
   ``I never wanted to do anything to her. I never wanted to hurt
her,'' Ms. Green testified. ``I was just trying to defend myself.''
   Ms. Green, 30, had been beaten and tormented for years before she
fired a single shot from a .38-caliber pistol into the head of her
live-in lover Ivonne Julio, 32, last October, defense attorney
William Lasley contends.
   Palm Beach Circuit Judge Tom Waddell ruled Tuesday to allow the
battered spouse defense in the lesbian case, saying the type of
relationship made no difference.
   The defense has been used successfully before to excuse women who
killed their male lovers.
   Neighbors, friends and co-workers have testified that Ms. Green
often was beaten viciously by Ms. Julio, and suffered broken bones,
bruises and black eyes. They said the fatal shooting followed a
night of arguing between the couple at a Halloween party.
   Ms. Green testified that after the shooting she was shocked at
what she had done and even considered suicide.
   ``I had the gun to my head,'' she testified. ``Why did I have the
gun to my head? I was going to kill myself ... because I loved her.''
   Mary Ann Dutton-Douglas, a psychologist at Nova University in
Fort Lauderdale who specializes in battered women cases, testified
Tuesday that the shooting should be interpreted as a response to
years of abuse.
   ``I believe that she was trying to figure a way out of the
situation,'' Ms. Dutton-Douglas said. ``But she was backed into a
corner.''
   Earlier efforts by Ms. Green to leave failed because Ms. Julio
would find her at work or win her back by promising to change, Ms.
Dutton-Douglas said.
   ``Leaving didn't mean her partner would leave her alone,'' Ms.
Dutton-Douglas said.
   Assistant State Attorney Robert Johnson questioned the
reliability of Ms. Dutton-Douglas' conclusions, suggesting that Ms.
Green could have falsified answers to psychological tests to appear
to be suffering from the syndrome.
   Closing arguments are scheduled for Thursday.
</TEXT>
