<SECOND>AM-Iowa-Hartwig Family,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hartwig Family Will Fight Navy Report Finding In Iowa Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iowa Inquiry</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY76</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a sailor implicated in the April
19 turret explosion aboard the USS Iowa hopes to clear his name in
court.
   A Navy investigation into the April 19 explosion in the
battleship's No. 2 gun turret found foreign material in the
immediate area of the blast, according to sources familiar with the
Navy's report to be made public Thursday.
   The sources said ``an unlawful and illegal act'' by gunner's mate
Clayton Hartwig is pinpointed in the Navy's report as the probable
cause of the blast.
   Kathy Kubicina, Hartwig's sister and the Hartwig family's
spokeswoman on the investigation, expects lawyers representing the
family to file a lawsuit after the report is released, but she would
not provide details of the legal plans Wednesday night.
   She said the Navy has promised to send an official to brief the
family Thursday morning.
   The family hired lawyers June 1. Two lawyers held a briefing Aug.
3 outside the federal courthouse in Cleveland, during which they
outlined the Hartwig case.
   At that briefing, lawyer Krieg Brusnahan said Hartwig had no role
in the Iowa disaster, adding: ``We have a possible theory as to the
cause of the blast that we will release after the Navy's report has
been released.''
   ``This is nothing I didn't expect,'' Ms. Kubicina said from her
residence Wednesday night. ``I fully expected the Navy to try and
pin this on my brother. ...
   ``It makes me wonder where the Navy investigation would have
turned to if I hadn't written the letters to the officers aboard the
Iowa in seeking help.''
   She contacted Iowa officers after learning about an insurance
policy Hartwig held that named Iowa crewman Kendall Truitt as
beneficiary. She said her brother and Truitt had been close friends
but their friendship had waned.
   ``I now know the (Naval Investigative Service) conducts witch
hunts for homosexuality in the Navy,'' she said. ``But then, I just
wanted Ken to turn the money over to my parents, and I wrote the
officers for help. I guess they gave the letters to the NIS.
   ``I knew there was nothing legally we could do (about the
insurance policy). I thought they would be able to persuade him,
because Truitt and my brother were no longer friends.''
   Ms. Kubicina has said her brother, to the best of her knowledge,
was not a homosexual. She previously has released romantic letters
he wrote to a woman she knows.
   ``None of the guys on the Iowa believe my brother blew up the
turret,'' she said. ``As far as I'm concerned, the report is another
hurdle for us to get over. We are definitely filing suit.''
</TEXT>
