<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     09-06 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Cristiani Says Salvador Peace Talks Begin Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Cristiani said
Wednesday that the government and leftist rebels will begin peace
talks next week, the first such talks in two years.
   He told a news conference his government accepted a rebel
proposal made Tuesday that first exchanges be held in Mexico between
Sunday and Sept. 14. But he cautioned the contacts would be
essentially preparatory.
   Marxist-led rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front have waged an insurrection for nearly 10 years against a
series of U.S.-backed governments. The war has killed an estimated
70,000 people, mostly civilians.
   ``This meeting next week is to make the preparations for and
provide the beginning of a dialogue process, and it is not something
from which substantive conclusions and accords are going to emerge.
It is to come to agreement in general terms on how to carry out the
process within which substantive subjects will be addressed,'' he
said.
   Cristiani said contacts in coming days would determine exactly
when and where the talks would take place.
   Cristiani, a rightist who took office June 1, said he would swear
in the government commission to the talks Thursday. He declined to
identify members, but leaks have indicated the delegation will
include two Cabinet ministers.
   The government and rebels held two rounds of unsuccessful peace
talks in 1984 and further talks in October 1987.
   ``The time has passed for propagandistic or tactical dialogue,''
the president said. He said the new talks will have the serious aim
of finding peace and incorporating the rebels ``in the peaceful life
of the country.''
   Rebel commander Ana Guadalupe Martinez said in Mexico on Tuesday
that the guerrillas want Monsignor Arturo Rivera Damas, the Roman
Catholic archbishop of San Salvador, to be moderator for the talks.
   Rivera Damas is touring Europe and the United States until
mid-September, and Cristiani said his participation in initial
exchanges ``is physically impossible.''
   The rebels have also insisted that delegates from the
Organization of American States and United Nations be present.
   Talks with the government of former President Jose Napoleon
Duarte, a centrist Christian Democrat, failed to advance the search
for peace.
</TEXT>
