<FIRST>u a AM-AgentsShot 1stLd-Writethru a0748 09-06 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agents Shot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0748,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Agent Shot, Another Wounded in Shoot-Out with Alleged Alien Smugglers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CORRECT that employers offered cash for
an illegal alien, sted aliens, provide details; picks up 7th graf, `One
of ...; SUBS last graf with 3 grafs to UPDATE with suspects' identities.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undercover U.S. Border Patrol agent was
shot to death and his partner wounded Wednesday while posing as
employers offering cash for an illegal alien farmhand, investigators
said.
   The smugglers opened fire on the agents as they tried to make
arrests at a convenience store parking lot in Fresno, police said.
Four people were arrested after authorities sealed off the
residential neighborhood and searched on foot and with a helicopter.
   The dead agent was identified as Keith Connelly, 42. Agent Ted
Jordan, shot in the chest, was in serious condition at a hospital,
authorities said.
   The two had arranged through an informant to make the swap at the
convenience store, said chief U.S. Border Patrol Agent J. William
Carter. The informant did not tell agents that the smugglers would
be armed, Carter said.
   The informant was the illegal alien with whom the agents first
made contact on Saturday. He was among those arrested.
   ``The exchange would have been that our agents would have
consummated the deal by paying the smugglers a fee'' of about $500
for a farm laborer, Carter said. ``The deal went sour about 1:40
a.m.''
   One of the downed agents fired at the suspects before backup
agents arrived and began shooting, Carter said.
   Two suspects sped off in a station wagon, and two others ran in
opposite directions, said Sgt. Jerry Dyer, head of a SWAT team that
sealed off the area. It was not known if any suspects were shot, but
Dyer said one was bleeding.
   The suspects' car, with a shattered window and a bullet hole in
the driver's door, was abandoned a few blocks away. A .357-caliber
Magnum revolver and a .380-caliber automatic were recovered, Carter
said.
   Residents, awakened by helicopter spotlights and SWAT officers
combing the neighborhood, said they saw the suspects climbing over
fences and running between bushes.
   ``God, what a night of hell,'' said Mark Dawson, 22. ``I was
awake. I couldn't sleep, and I heard all the gunshots. One of them
came through the back yard. I saw him climbing up over the telephone
pole in the backyard corner near my fence.''
   Police arrested Rosura Rodriguez, 22, of Los Angeles hiding near
the shooting scene less than an hour later, and two other suspects
were captured by 5 a.m. The final suspect was dragged out of a side
yard around 7:20 a.m., witnesses said.
   The other suspects were identified as Lorenzo Macias Arreola, 41,
and Florentino Nunez Mujica, 31, both of Los Angeles, and Albert
Serrano Saldana, 18, of Costa Mesa. Carter would not say which one
was the informant.
   All four were booked on suspicion of murder and other,
unspecified charges.
</TEXT>
