<DOCNO> AP890906-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 2239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-EarhartSearch     09-06 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earhart Search,0631</SECOND>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-member team of American aviation
historians arrived Wednesday hoping to solve the riddle of where
Amelia Earhart disappeared on her 1937 attempt to make the first
trans-Pacific flight.
   The International Group of Historic Aircraft Recovery based in
Wilmington, Del., plans to leave Suva on Monday for two remote
islands in the South Pacific hoping to find evidence that Earhart
crashed there.
   The group, led by Richard Gillespie, has chartered a converted
Japanese trawler, the 125-feet, 100-ton Pacific Nomad, to reach the
Phoenix Islands of McKean and Nikumaroro in the Kiribati
archipelago, 1,000 miles northeast of Fiji.
   U.S. Embassy official Robert Benzinger said the group had
``fairly persuasive'' evidence that Earhart went down much further
eastward than previously thought.
   ``The group is arriving with very thorough, well-documented
research,'' said Benzinger. ``They have two basic theories about
where Earhart crashed, and if they find the evidence it will be
sensational.''
   Meanwhile, an Australian woman pilot, Gaby Kennard, is attempting
to fly solo around the world in a single-engine plane as a tribute
to Earhart, whose exploits achieved legendary status in the United
States.
   Kennard, a 44-year-old mother of two, flew this week to Atchison,
Kan., Earhart's hometown. Kennard is a member of the 99 Association
of Women Pilots, which Earhart founded.
   She expects to complete the journey to Australia via Europe, the
Middle East and Asia later this month.
   Benzinger said that the government of Kiribati, a group of 33
islands straddling the equator, gave permission for the month-long
expedition.
   Kiribati, formerly the Gilbert and Ellice islands, was a major
battleground during World War II and has a population of about
61,000.
   Theories abound about why Earhart crashed after setting off for
Howland Island in 1937 from Wau, Papua New Guinea, to the north of
Australia.
   Howland lies north of the Phoenix Islands and has an airstrip
that Earhart had planned to use as a refuelling stop on the flight
to Hawaii with a navigator.
   Various theories suggest Earhart crashed on the then-Japanese
controlled Marshall Islands in Micronesia and that she was executed
after stumbling onto a military base.
   Benzinger, himself an amateur aviation hobbyist, said the
American expedition hopes to show that Earhart crashed much further
eastward, about 1,500 miles east of the islands then controlled by
Japan.
   ``There are two theories,'' he said. ``The first one requires
that you assume the plane was extremely off-course to the north,
which would mean the plane carried at least two more hours worth of
fuel than was previously thought.
   ``If you put yourself in the navigator's position of trying to
reach Howland Island and not making it, you would try to find the
nearest logical place to put the plane down and that would include
McKean and Nikumaroro atolls.''
   Benzinger said that research by the Americans shows that the U.S.
Coast Guard in Hawaii received distress signals from the plane after
it crashed and that the SOS now had been pinpointed approximately to
McKean and Nikumaroro.
   Benzinger, who has been in constant touch with the group, said
the expedition believes Earhart and her navigator died from thirst
or injuries some days after the crash. The wreckage of the plane
probably has been swept away by a hurricane, he said.
   McKean is a half-mile long, about 800 yards wide and only 17 feet
high. Nikumaroro, also known as Gardener, has a rim of land a
quarter-mile-wide around its V-shaped lagoon. Both islands are
uninhabited.
   Benzinger said the expedition was equipped with diving gear and a
sidescan sonar system which might detect wreckage of Earhart's plane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 2252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MartinezReturned 3rdLd-Writethru   09-06 0718</FIRST>
