<FIRST>r a AM-SneakerStudy 1stLd-Writethru a0713 09-06 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sneaker Study, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Comfort Still Rules in `Sneaker Revolution'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, grafs 7-8, `The six-month ...,' to CORRECT spelling
of ``footwear.'' A version moving on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Back in the days when a sneaker was a smelly
construction of canvas and rubber, statisticians told us the typical
American household had 2.5 children.
   Now, that's the average number of pairs of athletic shoes owned
by every man, woman and teen-ager in the United States, according to
a nationwide study by a sportswear trade group.
   The Athletic Footwear Association said it also discovered that
while some consumers are troubled by the escalating prices for
athletic shoes, comfort is still the top priority amid the space-age
designs and physics-lab features that have pushed the prices of many
top brands over $100.
   ``For a long time _ and in the last 10 years in particular _ the
whole idea about sneakers has heen evolving,'' said Gregg Hartley, a
spokesman for the North Palm Beach-based group. ``Today, it's
recognized that there are different sneakers for different sports,
but they can be fashionable, too.''
   The ``sneaker revolution'' has also altered our vocabulary, said
Hartley. The generic sneaker has been replaced by classifications
such as running shoes, aerobic shoes and even mall-walking shoes.
   ``Just about the only thing called sneakers these days is a $7.99
pair found in a discount store,'' he said.
   The six-month survey of 1,200 people, which began in November and
was released Tuesday by the footwear association, which represents
more than 100 manufacturers worldwide. The survey had a margin of
error of plus or minus 2 percent.
   Athletic shoe sales have grown about 15 percent a year and now
comprise about 40 percent of the total footwear sales in the United
States. About half of the $9 billion U.S. market is shared by Nike
Inc. and Reebok International Inc.
   The study found that young black males are the top sneaker
buyers, with an average of 4.8 pairs. Adults 18 to 35 were next with
an average of 4.1 pairs. Older adults owned 1.4 pairs on average.
   Men paid an average of $34 a pair and women spent $26, according
to the survey.
   Although 83 percent of all respondents said comfort was the
principal factor in buying an athletic shoe, teen-agers put fashion
first.
   The study found that 93 percent of all Americans over 12 own at
least one pair of athletic shoes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
