<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 4thLd-Writethru a0798 09-06 0947</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0798,0974</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Colombia Puts Price on Two Cocaine Kingpins, Martinez Extradited</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with U.S. marshal saying Martinez
will appear in court Thursday in Atlanta, background on U.S. investigation.
Picks up graf 6 pvs, `The Justice ...' Minor editing to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MED1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday put a
$250,000 price tag on the heads of Colombia's top two reputed
cocaine cartel bosses, and a U.S. official said a reputed drug
financier was extradited to the United States.
   Eduardo Martinez Romero was flown Wednesday night on a DEA plane
out of Colombia bound for the United States, said Drug Enforcement
Administration official Frank Shults.
   ``He's in the air; coming into the United States sometime in the
early morning,'' Shults said from Washington. Another U.S. official
said Martinez was being flown to Atlanta to appear before the U.S.
District Court.
   ``All I can tell you is he'll be at the federal building tomorrow
(Thursday),'' said U.S. Marshal Lynn Duncan in Atlanta.
   U.S. and Colombian officials in Bogota declined comment late
Wednesday on the reported extradition, the first since Colombia
declared war on drug traffickers 2{ weeks ago.
   U.S. officials in this capital, speaking on condition of
anonymity, have predicted even greater bloodshed in this
violence-wracked country if anyone is extradited because the cartel
has warned it would kill 10 Colombian judges for each person sent
out. Drug traffickers in particular fear extradition.
   The last Colombian trafficker to be extradited was Carlos Lehder,
a leader of the Medellin cartel who was sent to the United States in
early 1987 and is serving a life sentence in the federal prison in
Marion, Ill.
   Martinez, 35, was indicted in Atlanta as a result of an
investigation code-named Operation Polar Cap that federal official
said disclosed at least $1.2 billion in money laundering of cocaine
profits through U.S. and foreign banks.
   Martinez had faced summarry extradition under emergency measurres
since his arrest Aug. 20. Barco ordered his ``administrative
extradition'' to the United States.
   The Justice Ministry announced on national TV that the reward on
Pablo Escobar and Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha would be paid to anyone
providing information leading to the arrest of one or both men, and
showed ``wanted'' posters of the two.
   The television later reported without elaboration that Martinez
had been extradited.
   Escobar and Rodriguez Gacha, now in hiding, are also wanted in
the United States. Both are said to be billionaires and were on the
list of the 12 most wanted Colombians that was issued last month by
the U.S. government. Martinez was not on that list.
   The government also announced that under present emergency
legislation in the fierce anti-narcotics fight it can, if necessary,
fire mayors and place cities under temporary military control. This
could happen, a proclamation said, in case of ``abnormal
situations.''
   President Virgilio Barco on Wednesday thanked President Bush for
backing Colombia in its drug war, but said the United States and
other developed countries with lots of drug users have more to
answer for than cocaine-producing Colombia.
   Bush on Tuesday night announced a $7.9 billion war on drugs and
said specifically that Colombia will get U.S. anti-drug aid.
   ``This is a very favorable start,'' Barco said in a statement
responding to Bush's announcement.
   ``Colombia certainly needs international help so it can fight its
own battle against internationally organized drug trafficking.''
   He added, however, that such help, including possible military
support mentioned by Bush, ``cannot be a substitute for the
responsibility each nation has for controlling the various links in
this criminal chain.''
   The Colombian president said that ending drug use ``is a
responsibility of the whole international community. We hope that
other countries assume the responsibility that corresponds to them.''
   A Defense Ministry spokesman in Bogota said police and soldiers
had made more than 2,042 raids since Aug. 18, when Barco invoked
emergency powers after the assassination of Sen. Luis Carlos Galan,
the leading presidential candidate and an outspoken foe of the drug
lords.
   The United States has a list of 12 so-called ``Extraditables,''
the men said to be Colombia's most important drug kingpins. All but
economist Martinez are at large. Cartel bosses said they would
rather die in Colombia than go to jail in the United States.
   Acting Justice Minister Carlos Lemos said Wednesday this South
American country cannot fight the drug barons successfully unless
the United States, the world's biggest cocaine consumer, curbs its
appetite.
   Bush made the same point Tuesday night.
   The Defense Ministry said police and soldiers had seized 880
properties, including some palatial estates, and hundreds of
vehicles and aircraft in its war on narcotics traffickers.
   Police in Medellin, home of the most powerful cocaine cartel,
said they were searching for a couple suspected in the latest
bombing in the cartel's counterattack _ an explosion in a restaurant
that injured four people, including two U.S. journalists.
   Colombians reacted favorably to Bush's speech, and the country's
largest newspaper said an editorial Thursday would carry the
headline, ``We Are Not Alone.''
   In addition to the hundreds of homes, office buildings and other
real estate believed owned by cocaine barons, authorities had
confiscated 1,190 weapons, more than 20,000 rounds of ammunition,
499 vehicles, 48 boats and 358 aircraft, the Defense Ministry
spokesman said..
   He said more raids and seizures were taking place daily. By
custom, the spokesman's name was withheld.
   Violence in Colombia continued Wednesday. Two men shot and killed
Luz Amparo Gomez, 30, a lawyer, on Bogota's north side, police said.
   Ms. Gomez had defended a local politician who had been wounded in
a fight involving the smuggling of Colombian emeralds.
</TEXT>
