<FIRST>u a AM-RetardedServices     09-06 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retarded Services,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Defers Decision on Philadelphia Request for More Funds for
Retarded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state-forced cutback in a program for 4,000
mentally retarded Philadelphians living with relatives threatens
them with the prospect of ``regression and institutionalization,''
the city argued in court Wednesday.
   State officials countered that they merely allocate money that
the Legislature provides _ in this case, a $7.5 million shortfall in
the state's allocation for a city program of vocational education,
day care and therapy.
   Commonwealth Judge James Crumlish Jr. did not say when he would
rule on the city's request for an injunction against Gov. Robert
Casey and Public Welfare Secretary John White.
   The city's lawsuit contends that until the programs are restored,
the retarded will suffer ``irreparable harm (and) risk regression
and possible institutionalization.''
   ``We contend that state law provides that those persons who got
the services before should continue to get them,'' said Deputy City
Solicitor Richard Gold said.
   Leona Fialkowski was one of two mothers who testified that the
cutback already has hurt their children.
   ``We are starting to see regression in David in his efforts in
walking and self-help,'' said the woman, whose son is 27. ``He needs
attention to maintain what he has.''
   The city successfully challenged a state cutback in court last
fiscal year, but earlier this year, a federal appeals court held
that the U.S. Constitution does not give the retarded the right to
the same level of treatment provided institutionalized patients.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals court acknowledged that its
ruling could force more people into hospitals at greater cost to
taxpayers.
   According to testimony at Wednesday's hearing, about $20 million
of a total of $120 million for the state was allocated to
Philadelphia. By state law, the state must pay 90 percent of the
cost of services for the retarded.
   Assistant Attorney General Gwen Mosley, representing the
defendants, said she does not doubt Philadelphia needs more money,
but questioned whether the city is entitled to it under the law.
   ``We say it is not,'' she said. ``We can allocate only what is
appropriated by the Legislature, and we must distribute it fairly.''
   Joseph Gueltier, director of the state Bureau of Mental
Retardation, said Philadelphia has about 14 percent of the state's
total population and is getting about 18 percent of the money
allocated for non-residential programs.
   Attorney David Ferleger disagreed. ``These people have the right
to these services, and the state must fund it,'' he said. ``The
state has intentionally underfunded Philadelphia year after year
after year.''
   Ferleger represents the Philadelphia Police and Firemen
Association for Handicapped Children, which joined the city's
lawsuit.
   If Crumlish rules for the city, Ferleger said he will ask the
judge to expand the program to all retarded people living at home in
Philadelphia, affecting an additional 3,800.
   ``We aim to give people with retardation and their families a
chance to have a normal life in their own homes, instead of being
forced by the state into large institutions which will be the result
if the shortfall continues,'' he said.
   ``Nobody needs an institution when they can live in their own
home.''
   The expansion would cost the state $30 million, Ferleger said.
</TEXT>
