<DOCNO> AP890906-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0811EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:Jimmy'sTown Adv11   09-06 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Jimmy's Town, Adv 11,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Mon PMs, Sept. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Historic Buildings Preserved in Drawings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four illustrators and a historian are
capturing the flavor of Plains, the friendly town that gained world
renown in 1976 when Americans elected a peanut farmer to serve as
their 39th president.
   Under a program known as the Historic American Building Survey,
the five have been working since June 12, studying and sketching
historic buildings that eventually may be included in the Jimmy
Carter National Historic Site.
   ``It's a privilege to work on this project,'' said architect John
Westberg of Tempe, Ariz. ``He's making a difference on this planet.
He seems less concerned about his own life than what he can do for
other people.''
   Westberg, 35, the team's leader, said residents have been helpful
and seem to appreciate the efforts to preserve the town's heritage.
The five were chosen from hundreds of applicants and are paid by the
National Park Service. Their headquarters is an apartment next to
the one Carter and his young wife, Rosalynn, rented in 1953 when he
returned from the Navy.
   They have attended Sunday Bible classes given by the former
president and met with the Carters at the couple's home on Church
Street. They've spent weeks taking precise measurements of Carter's
high school, his boyhood home in nearby Archery, a former store
operated by the Carter family, the apartment, and the century-old
depot that served as Carter's 1976 campaign headquarters.
   The Park Service already owns the depot and high school, but is
negotiating for the boyhood home and store. The Carters have donated
their home, but will continue to live in it.
   From photographs and sketches, Westberg and three others will
prepare detailed ink drawings of the five buildings for the National
Archives. The Carter home was not included in the building survey.
   ``It takes a lot of care,'' said Dana Peak, as she inked a
cornice of the high school. ``The drawings may be scrutinized by a
lot of people,'' Westberg said. ``It's very important that they be
accurate.''
   Ms. Peak, a June graduate of the University of California, Davis,
said there's a strong feeling of community in the Sumter County town
of 650. ``The people have been friendly and supportive.''
   ``The people are very enthusiastic about the Jimmy Carter
Historic Site,'' agreed architect Jason Breyer, 25, of Fargo, N.D.
   Dale Waldron, 21, of Preston, Conn., a student at the Rhode
Island School of Design, said he welcomed an opportunity to meet the
former president. ``I found him very open. He's very visible. He
goes to a lot of meetings.''
   The fifth team member, historian Elizabeth Barthold of Crofton,
Md., spends her time interviewing residents and wading through real
estate records at the Sumter County Courthouse in Americus.
   ``People here are really proud of Plains and they want to
share,'' she said. ``They feel it is special and they're interested
in having it recorded.''
   Ms. Barthold is preparing reports on 23 historic buildings in
Plains, including the five that are to become a part of the National
Historic Site. She also is studying a pond house that belonged to
Miss Lillian, the president's mother, a former hospital where Carter
was born and a service station made famous by the president's late
brother, Billy Carter.
   ``At first I was so amazed that Jimmy Carter, president of the
United States, came from here. But the Carters are just incredible
people.''
   Ms. Barthold was impressed by the functional design of the old
homes. They sit on brick pillars for ventilation and protection from
moisture. Many have high steep roofs, high ceilings and hallways
running through their entire length for more efficient cooling on
hot summer days.
   Westberg said the high school is typical of hundreds built during
the 1920s with a central entrance, wings on each side and an
auditorium in the back.
   ``It's disintegrating fast,'' he said. ``Water has gotten into
the outside walls and it's rotting the floor and ceiling away.''
   The Park Service runs a museum in the depot and has earmarked
$200,000 to preserve the high school. About 4,000 tourists visit the
town each month, just a fraction of the multitudes who flocked here
during the Carter presidency.
   Westberg and the others will remain in Plains through Friday. All
their work, including rough sketches, ink drawings and reports, will
become a part of the official history of Plains, maintained by the
National Archives.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs, Sept. 11</NOTE>
