<FIRST>a a AM-BlueBanjo Adv13   09-06 0985</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blue Banjo, Adv 13,1018</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Wed AMs, Sept. 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Flashers, Drugs and Death: Business as Usual at Yakima Bar</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   There's a certain kind of bar in the tough part
of town, any town, where business goes on pretty much as usual no
matter what happens. If a couple regulars don't show up, no one pays
any attention. If it turns out they're lying in the alley out back,
nothing happens. And if they're dead?
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LUIS CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Death dropped in at the Blue Banjo one
Sunday, and nobody even noticed.
   Richard O'Bennick and Frank Woodworth lay by the back steps for
more than six hours on a 90-degree day before anyone realized they
weren't asleep.
   Two nights later, the jukebox blared a Johnny Cash song about a
Dallas bordello. A haggard group of men lounged in the alley behind
the Blue Banjo, talking and sharing a jug. On the sidewalk out front
drug deals went down.
   Business as usual.
   Inside, a couple of Mexican farmworkers played pool on a ragged
blue-slate table. A half-dozen men sat at barstools, laughing once
in a while and trading jokes with the bartender.
   A blonde woman with a bandage wrapped around her hand and missing
a front tooth danced a little as she walked from the jukebox to her
table. A man strutted behind her, mimicking. She turned and swiped
him on the shoulder. They laughed.
   O'Bennick and Woodworth used to come in, when they had cash.
   ``They certainly take these fellows' money readily enough and
give them alcohol. They're friends as long as they have money,''
said Roger Phillips, who runs the 100-bed Union Gospel Mission.
   Robert MacLemore, a cook across town at the Blue Ox restaurant
and O'Bennick's sometime drinking buddy, took a seat at the orange
formica-topped bar. ``He would go up and try to bum for money, and I
got to know him. He would always be glad to see me coming. He knew I
always had money on me, you see.''
   MacLemore last saw O'Bennick the Wednesday before he died, and
gave him all of his bus fare so the transient could buy a quart of
beer. MacLemore walked to work. O'Bennick ``was a nice person, he
really was. But he was lonely. He had something down inside of him
that was eating him away,'' he said.
   O'Bennick ``had a lot of good in him,'' said Phillips, whose
mission was the dead men's last address. He ``always carried a
trombone around and talked about playing it,'' though Phillips never
actually saw him blow a note.
   MacLemore remembered Woodworth as a quiet, heavy-set man who
walked around on crutches and loved to drink wine. ``He was older.
Well, he looked old, but he wasn't as old as I am. He was in his
late 40s, maybe early 50s.''
   After two autopsies and tests for poison, the cause of
O'Bennick's and Woodworth's deaths on Aug. 6 remains a mystery. The
men's bodies sat in the late-summer heat, a jug of Almaden Blush
Chablis between them, long enough to start decomposing before
anybody knew they were dead.
   Yakima County Coroner Leonard Birkenbine wasn't surprised. ``You
go down there, there's always somebody lying down like that.''
   The tavern, with a blue neon sign that's read ``lue Banjo'' as
long as anyone could remember, is in the tough section of Yakima, a
central Washington town of 50,000 that is best known for apples,
cherries and vineyards but is fast developing a reputation as a
rural drug center.
   In a block wedged between a residential district and a restaurant
strip are the Blue Banjo, another tavern and a long-vacant building
with barred doors.
   ``We did have an extensive problem some time ago down there,''
said police Capt. Don Blesio. ``For the most part the problem has
been reduced considerably, but we're suffering from the cocaine and
heroin problems that exist.''
   ``It's tough there, it really is,'' MacLemore said. ``You can get
hurt there. You can get killed there.''
   Bob Briggs, who said he was released from the Washington state
penitentiary in Walla Walla that day after serving eight years for
burglary and auto theft, watched the Blue Banjo scene from the
corner barstool.
   ``I asked where the toughest place in town was, and they told me
the Blue Banjo. So I figured I'd better come try it out,'' he said.
``It couldn't be any tougher than Walla Walla.''
   The bar is a popular spot. Patrons wander in, some for draft beer
at 50 cents a glass, some for the two-for-a-quarter cigarettes. In a
cubbyhole behind the bar two shelves are filled with fortified wines
like Thunderbird, MD 20-20 and jugs of White Port, O'Bennick's
favorite.
   While MacLemore and others talked about O'Bennick and Woodworth,
a young woman walked in and ordered a beer. The bartender asked for
identification and instead of producing a driver's license, she
lifted her shirt and exposed her breasts. She was kicked out.
   ``We get that all the time,'' said the bartender, a burly man
with a gravelly voice who asked that his name not be used. ``I've
got to kick her out or the cops would bust me for promoting
prostitution.''
   Two men staggered in and tried to order beer. They were kicked
out, too.
   ``He was like that,'' the bartender said of O'Bennick as they
lurched out.
   The cash register rang almost constantly after the bartender gave
last call at 11:45 p.m. MacLemore downed one for the road and walked
out through the shifting crowd outside.
   ``Coke? Coca?'' two men asked, making little sniffing motions.
   MacLemore ignored them and walked to the back of the building,
where a lone man rummaged through a trash bin. The homeless
jug-sharers had left. The spot where O'Bennick and Woodworth died
was empty.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for AMs, Sept. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:DallasSymphony Adv08   09-06 0958</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Dallas Symphony, Adv 08,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Sept. 8, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Symphony Hall a Class Act</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: In 3rd graf, Friday is Sept. 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ANDREA WEISGERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hailed as a first-rate concert hall but criticized
as a multimillion-dollar extravagance, the new home of the Dallas
Symphony Orchestra is, all agree, a class act.
   The Morton H. Meyerson Center, designed by I.M. Pei and detailed
down to its washroom faucets, seats 2,065 people, some in
second-level boxes costing between $10,000 and $30,000 with a
99-year lease if paid within five years. Tickets are extra.
   Its gala opening Friday, with performances by Van Cliburn,
Mstislav Rostropovich and Leontyne Price, was breathlessly awaited
by the arts community and the Dallas symphony supporters who, 10
years ago, began toying with the idea of a new home for the Dallas
Symphony.
   ``The opening of a major concert hall anywhere is a major event
because it's a shrine, it's a temple,'' said Matthew Sigman,
associate editor for Symphony Magazine.
   The center was conceived by a small group of symphony supporters
who toured concert halls around the world for ideas. In 1982, Dallas
voters approved a $28.6 million bond issue to help pay for the hall.
The rest of the original estimated cost of $49.5 million was to come
from private donations.
   The price tag has swelled through delays, cost overruns and
lavish extras to anywhere from $81.5 million to $108 million.
   The $81.5 estimate includes construction costs for the symphony
hall alone. The $108 million estimate includes the land, the
building, the organ, an underground garage, an adjacent park, a
commemorative sculpture and arch and overtime costs to finish the
canopies over the stage. Add financing charges and the cost of a
nearby garage that will be used by concertgoers and the tab rises to
just under $200 million.
   The city also will pay more than $2 million a year in annual
maintenance and debt service.
   Pei, designer of the John F. Kennedy Library in Boston and the
East Wing of the National Gallery of Art in Washington, was no
stranger to the Dallas skyline. He had designed four buildings here
before he was tapped for the project, and he was not likely to do
his first symphony hall on the cheap.
   He designed the music hall as a rectangle, sitting at an angle
inside a square, surrounded by segments of circles. The Dallas
Museum of Art and the Dallas skyline are visible through $6 million
worth of glass panes that make a sweeping curve of the lobby. There
is a 4,463-pipe organ, Italian marble and artificially weathered
limestone.
   After he was commissioned in 1982, at a fee that would total more
than $10 million, Pei told the developers that the 25,000 square
feet of land they had procured for the hall would not be enough. The
city began negotiations for more land nearby _ land that had
escalated as much as 10 times in value when word spread that the
hall was to be built there.
   Eventually, the symphony center would require 260,000 square
feet, at a total land cost of $16.1 million.
   Each new detail _ whether from Pei or the city or the symphony _
drove up the cost. Those pushing quality had an ally in Texas
billionaire H. Ross Perot, who contributed $12 million to the
project with the stipulation that if quality were sacrificed, he
wanted his money back.
   Perot also refused to hand over the money unless the center was
named for Morton H. Meyerson, president of Perot's Electronic Data
Systems Inc. and a member of the group that first envisioned the
hall.
   When budget considerations threatened the thick wood paneling
that Pei wanted for the music chamber (plaster and concrete were
originally proposed), Leonard Stone, executive director of the
symphony, warned that the Perot grant could be in trouble.
   ``Ross is expecting wood,'' Stone wrote in a 1986 memo to
symphony president Bill Schilling, ``and if Ross found out that wood
was excluded, he would feel that we violated the spirit of the
agreement we entered into when we accepted his gift.''
   Wood it was _ more than 1,100 panels of African and American
cherry _ 918 trimmed with brass inlays in the music chamber. Another
216 squares will grace the stage walls.
   Instead of brick and carpet in the lobby, Pei wanted marble and
limestone _ limestone that had to be given an artificially weathered
look before it was put in the hall.
   The construction brought with it widely reported disputes among
the architect, the organ designer _ C.B. Fisk _ and an acoustics
expert, Russell Johnson of Artec Consultants, Inc.
   Johnson downplays the disagreements. ``One does not expect that
an acoustical advisor, a theater planning consultant and an
architect are going to immediately agree on every detail,'' he said.
``We feel that the collaboration was very warm and very close and
very successful.''
   In fights with the symphony, Johnson protested using filled block
instead of poured concrete, and protested reducing roof or ceiling
thicknesses and installing vents in the auditorium floor. The hefty
construction is one factor he cites as essential to acoustical
quality, as was the decision to build a small scale hall.
   Other features of the Dallas hall _ 85-foot high music chamber,
movable canopies, soffit in the upper levels and acres of special
fabrics in the chamber _ are important to good acoustical design, he
said.
   The quality of the acoustics won't really be known until the
first note is played to an audience. Nonetheless, Johnson is not
worried. ``I have had a full night's sleep every night for the last
seven months,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 2142EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Kelly Adv11   09-06 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Kelly, Adv 11,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Sept 11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Words and Songs That Linger</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Kelly's songs could take place anytime,
anywhere: the 19th century in Australia, Europe in the 1940s,
contemporary America.
   Bus trips, history books and old girlfriends provide inspiration.
With his band, the Messengers, Kelly sings of love in vain, mystery
trains and hearts too big for the body.
   His influences include rock 'n' rollers Chuck Berry and Lou Reed,
bluesmen Muddy Waters and Howlin' Wolf, and author Raymond Carver,
whose short story, ``So Much Water, So Close to Home,'' provides the
title for Kelly's third album.
   ``He definitely showed me how to write economically,'' how to
convey a lot of information in a short space, Kelly said of the late
writer. ``His voice often has the ring of true speech. That's
something I've tried to do with my songs.''
   His songs are often three-minute stories, condensing days, even
years, into just a few stanzas. But if Kelly believes in writing
words that linger, the melody, he insists, comes first.
   ``I wouldn't want people to think of songs just in terms of the
lyrics. By making the words fit the melody, you open your stories up
to chance. Sometimes the melody is going to make your story go
somewhere. I don't sit to write a story in a song; it's usually the
other way around.''
   He contrasts bitter lyrics and happy music, singing
``Everything's Turning to White'' so sweetly that only careful
listeners will pick up Kelly's rendition of Carver's bitter story
about a man's indifference to a young girl's death.
   Myths are also important, whether his own or someone
else's.``Pigeon-Jundamarra'' is based on a true story about an
Aboriginal resistance hero from the late 19th century who kills his
former masters and heads for the hills. Kelly added his own twist.
   ``He knew the country so well and had knowledge of this extensive
cave system,'' the musician said. ``He was very hard to catch and
became almost supernatural. People believed he could never be caught
by a white man's bullet. ``It was surprising that the song turned
out very short and was written from the point of view of the officer
chasing him. I started with a formal story in my mind; the officer
chasing him is just a fictional character. There was certainly no
Officer O'Malley.''
   Kelly, born in Australia, grew up listening to rock 'n' roll,
playing the trumpet and writing short stories. By age 18, he was
ready to take up the guitar and write songs.
   ``I knew that I wanted to write so I was keeping a journal, but
it took me a couple of years before I actually wrote a song. It was
in F and G and sounded a bit like (Bob Dylan's) `Percy's Song.'''
   He began his career in 1976, working in bands in Melbourne and
gradually meeting the musicians who became the Messengers: Steve
Connelly, Michael Barclay, Peter Bull and Jon Schorfield.
   ``I've known Steve and Michael for a while because we all lived
in Melbourne for a stage and we've seen each other in bands,'' Kelly
said.
   ``I moved up to Sydney in 1984 and we worked together as a trio.
That was also the time I met Peter, who was playing in another band
at the time. We made an acoustic record and Michael sang on it.''
   He made a solo album, ``Post,'' in 1984, but began to acquire a
real following with ``Gossip,'' a double album released two years
later that featured the Messengers. Trains were there from the
start. ``Last Train to Heaven'' recalls a time when trains were a
symbol of unavoidable fate, that could take away your true love
forever or provide your escape to a better world.
   ``It's a symbol of death in dreams,'' Kelly added. ``Freud always
listed one of the death symbols as a train. I sort of unconsciously
absorbed it. I didn't realize it until later that I wrote so often
about trains.''
   The ballad ``Cities of Texas'' was written on a bus, one that
pulled into Dallas during the first American tour. Kelly sings with
the deepest longing, like a man saying goodbye.
   ``I guess it's like the kind of longing you have for something
you feel is going to pass away,'' he said. ``You walk into Dallas
and you walk up to a building and touch it, it's solid, seems like
it's going to be around for a long time. But seeing it from a
distance, it's like, `Here today, gone tomorrow.'
   ``Dallas made a big impression on me. The city seemed to shimmer
with all the glass reflected. It's a song of mourning, so beautiful
but it's going to go away.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
