<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 2145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-`AlienNation     09-06 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-`Alien Nation,' Adv 16-17,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16-17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions of Sept. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Heady Career Move for Eric Pierpoint in `Alien Nation' ^With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a hot TV sound stage, Eric Pierpoint was
even warmer with his ears and the top of his head covered by a
molded appliance that transforms him into a large-domed ``newcomer''
on Fox Broadcasting's ``Alien Nation.''
   Pierpoint plays George Francisco, an alien from a planet 300
light years away who joins the Los Angeles police. He's teamed up
with earthling detective played by Gary Graham for this new action
drama based on the movie.
   ``They took a mold of my head and sculpted this head cover,'' he
said. ``It comes down to my cheeks and eyebrows. It takes an hour
and a half to get it on because it has to be blended around the
edges. It has to be just right with no wrinkles so that it
photographs well.
   ``It's very hot and it muffles your hearing about 50 percent. It
puts you in your own little world. You have to pay careful
attention. You hear little shuffling noises whirling around in your
head.''
   Pierpoint and Graham were doing a scene in which they question a
``newcomer'' prostitute. The sound stage was on the cramped second
floor of an old warehouse in an industrial district of Los Angeles.
It was last used by ``Cagney &amp; Lacey.''
   The new series debuts Monday on Fox after ``21 Jump Street,'' as
the two shows open a new night for the so-called fourth network. The
previous Sunday night slot for ``21 Jump'' has been taken over by a
spinoff series, ``Booker.''
   Executive producer Kenneth Johnson, who previously produced
``V,'' adapted the ``Alien Nation'' series from the movie starring
James Caan and Mandy Patinkin. It's set in Los Angeles in the 1990s
and is a police drama involving some of the 250,000 ``newcomers''
trying to find a place in society after their space ship has
crash-landed. (That must have been some ship.) Called ``slags,''
they run into some resistance and prejudice from earthlings.
   The ``newcomers'' are brainy and a bit quirky. George is very
earnest about playing the game right. He and his family are trying
very hard to fit in as middle class.
   ``Ken Johnson called me in January and asked if I wanted to do
`Alien Nation,''' Pierpoint said. ``I thought he wanted me for the
earthling role. When he said he wanted me to play George I said I'd
have to see the movie again. I said, `You're absolutely right. I
have to do George.' Still, it's a bit of a stretch for me and I was
very nervous about it.
   ``Doing this kind of a character is a risk. I've needed some help
to tell me when I'm too broad or too funny or too unreal. Some of it
just comes from the things that happen. We're coming up with a lot
of things. When he gets a cold he blinks. When he's tense his feet
get sore. He gets drunk on sour milk and when he makes love he hums.
We've gotten a lot of jokes around the set on that.''
   Prior to starting the series, Pierpoint walked around Union
Station in makeup talking to people. Some people got nervous, but he
found if he spoke with authority people answered his questions. Some
thought he was deformed and one person walked up and said, ``Alien
Nation.''
   This is the third series for Pierpoint, the son of CBS News
correspondent Robert Pierpoint of ``CBS Sunday Morning.'' He was in
``Hot Pursuit,'' which ran briefly on NBC in 1984. Ken Johnson was
the producer of that show, too. He also spent a season on ``Fame''
as the drama teacher.
   ``I've done a lot of guest shots,'' he said. ``I was on `In the
Heat of the Night' and `Beauty and the Beast.' I had a recurring
role on `Hill Street Blues' in which I had a brief fling with Betty
Thomas. I was in a remake of `Invaders From Mars.' I was the
general's right-hand man. I got nailed by the Martians.''
   As a youth, he occasionally tagged along with his father to the
White House and presidential vacation stops: Hyannisport, Mass.;
Austin, Texas; and San Clemente, Calif. He attended the University
of Redlands and afterward worked in a government-sponsored arts
program for children. He later got a master of fine arts degree and
traveled abroad with a Shakespeare company.
   ``I worked in the theater mostly until 1982,'' he said. ``Then
you reach a point where you want to be paid. I found I couldn't buy
a house on $300 a week, so I got into television.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 16-17</NOTE>
</DOC>
