<DOCNO> AP890906-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Andersen-Waterhouse Bjt   09-06 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Andersen-Waterhouse, Bjt,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merger Talks to Continue Between Arthur Andersen and Price Waterhouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Andersen &amp; Co. and Price Waterhouse have
major hurdles to overcome if they are to form the world's largest
accounting firm, but analysts say they expect the two will forge
ahead with plans to merge.
   The firms announced Tuesday that they are continuing their
exploratory merger talks, which began about two months ago.
   The two had hoped to reach agreement by early this month. But one
industry analyst said that given the complexities involved, the
lengthy talks are understandable.
   ``What's clear is that the two firms desire to merge,'' said
James Emerson, publisher of Emerson's Professional Services Review,
a Bellevue, Wash.-based publication that follows the Big Eight
accounting firms.
   ``The question is whether they can mechanically put the deal
together in a way that makes sense for their clients, employees and
partners,'' he said. ``I think the benefits are so significant that
they ... will work out their differences and will agree to the
merger in principle in the very near future.''
   The talks between Andersen, the nation's No. 1 accounting firm,
and Price Waterhouse, the No. 5 firm, come against a backdrop of
other mergers within the Big Eight.
   Ernst &amp; Whinney has agreed to combine operations with Arthur
Young &amp; Co., while Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells is joining forces with
Touche Ross &amp; Co.
   On July 6, Chicago-based Andersen and New York-based Price
Waterhouse announced that they had entered into 60 days of formal
talks to explore the feasibility of mergering their worldwide
operations.
   In a joint statement Tuesday, Price Waterhouse Chairman Joseph E.
Connor and Andersen Chief Executive Lawrence A. Weinbach said ``the
initial period of discussion has been beneficial.''
   The executives said talks so far ``have concentrated on exploring
a combination that would add value to client service, capitalize on
shared values of commitment to quality ... and provide enhanced
opportunities to personnel of both firms.''
   Andersen spokesman Jack Ruane and Price Waterhouse spokeswoman
Deborah Rothschild both said they could not comment further because
the firms had agreed to keep details of the discussions confidential.
   Some potential obstacles to a merger include how to reconcile the
firms' compensation and retirement systems and foreign operations,
as well as how to handle merging Andersen's very successful
consulting business with Price Waterhouse's, analysts say.
   ``Andersen's consulting partners are the most resistant to this
merger,'' said Arthur Bowman, editor of the Atlanta-based Bowman's
Accounting Report.
   Andersen Consulting is involved in dozens of joint ventures with
International Business Machines Corp. to develop computer
integration products for clients. The computer maker is Price
Waterhouse's largest audit client.
   ``IBM is a big question,'' Bowman said. ``There are definite
conflicts of interest that have to be resolved before they can do a
merger.''
   Federal Securities and Exchange Commission rules bar an
accounting firm from participating in joint ventures with one of its
audit clients because of possible conflicts of interest.
   Bowman said partners in both firms had indicated to him that
there was more work to be done than they realized. But he said the
merger could be worked out by the end of this month.
   ``After 60 days, if they didn't want to merge, they would
certainly have known that, so at least they are moving forward,''
Bowman said.
   Bowman said the U.S. Justice Department had started looking at
the ramifications of an Andersen-Price Waterhouse combination, which
would create the world's largest accounting firm. Together they
would have $5 billion a year in worldwide revenue, which $2.7
billion of that coming from U.S. operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 0217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Japan-USTrade Bjt   09-06 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US Trade, Bjt,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Agree Americans Need To Change Spending Habits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American officials did not dispute Japanese charges
made during trade talks that U.S. spending habits and the nation's
budget deficit are part of the cause of the bilateral trade
imbalance.
   The United States should save more, cut its budget deficit and
encourage longer-term thinking by its business leaders, Japanese
officials told their American colleagues Tuesday in talks on
structural solutions to the Japanese trade surplus.
   American officials attending the talks said they would seriously
consider Japanese suggestions for improving U.S. export
competitiveness, including a call for increased spending on
work-force training and education and more emphasis on the long-term
implications of business decisions.
   Japanese officials said the huge U.S. budget deficit and low
savings rate were major causes of the more than $50 billion
bilateral trade imbalance.
   Economists say that when Americans do not save enough to pay the
U.S. government budget deficit, the government must borrow from
foreigners, including Japanese, who get the money to lend by selling
goods to the U.S.
   As long as Americans prefer to buy Japanese goods rather than put
their money in the bank, and Japanese prefer to save their money
rather than spend it, the imbalance will continue, the economists
say.
   American and Japanese trade policymakers generally agree that
barriers to specific products, the focus of trade negotiations in
the past, now account for only a small part of the imbalance. Most
of the imbalance is caused, they say, by macroeconomic factors such
as savings rates and government spending patterns.
   ``We agreed with a great deal with the suggestions of our
Japanese colleagues, and hope they will take just as seriously our
suggestions,'' said Richard McCormack, undersecretary of state for
economic affairs and the leader of the U.S. delegation. ``When our
Japanese colleagues said our savings rate is too low we were in
total agreement with them.''
   In talks Monday, American officials told Japan it should
encourage people to spend rather than save, streamline its
complicated distribution system, and loosen the tight-knit business
ties that often exclude newcomers.
   The U.S. officials stressed that talks on eliminating the
structural causes of the trade imbalance, dubbed the ``structural
impediments initiative,'' were expected to produce concrete results
on both sides of the Pacific.
   McCormack said the United States had already established a
working group to study the U.S savings rate. He said some progress
had been made in encouraging Americans to save more, raising the
personal savings rate from 3.2 percent of the U.S. gross national
product in 1987 to 5.4 percent this year.
   Both Japanese and U.S. participants declined to comment on
specific policy changes that might result from the talks, which are
slated to resume in Washington Nov. 6-7.
   ``We hope and expect ... some changes could be implemented before
the interim report next spring,'' McCormack said. ``I myself am
optimistic that these talks will result in tangible changes.''
   Japanese officials, who on Monday were urged to increase public
spending to improve the quality of life in Japan and to end
exclusionary business practices that limit entry into their markets,
were more reserved in their comments.
   ``Although we haven't come up with any concrete answers to those
questions raised by either side, I think it was significant that
each side has come to know the other's point of view,'' said
Michihiko Kunihiro, deputy foreign minister for economic affairs.
   The response of Japanese officials to the U.S. recommendations
was mixed.
   Construction Minister Shozo Harada said the U.S. call to increase
the amount of Japan's land available for residential housing
construction was ``realistic'' and ``urgent.''
   But Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told Japanese reporters
``there is no need to obey the U.S. calls.''
   Hashimoto said the U.S. tactical approach of emphasizing how the
structural reforms they suggested would benefit Japanese consumers
put his government in the uncomfortable position of having to
``explain why such improvements cannot be done.''
   The U.S. officials said the structural reforms they suggested
would both reduce the trade imbalance with Japan and give Japanese
consumers access to a wider variety of products at lower prices.
   Spending more on highways, parks, sewers and medical facilities
in Japan, they said, would improve the quality of life for ordinary
Japanese and redistribute the nation's massive wealth.
   The two nations turned to a structural approach to trade reforms
after success in lifting trade barriers such as tariffs failed to
eliminate Japan's huge surpluses with the United States and other
industrialized nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
