<FIRST>r f PM-InsiderTrading     09-06 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insider Trading,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Wall Street Professional Formally Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former executive of Wall Street's Goldman Sachs
&amp; Co. has pleaded guilty to a felony mail fraud charge for trading
on inside information.
   The plea on Tuesday by Robert M. Freeman, the former head of risk
arbitrage at the prestigious investment house, was part of an
agreement with federal prosecutors announced Aug. 17. Risk arbitrage
is the speculative investment in stocks of possible takeover targets.
   In entering the plea, Freeman became one of the most prominent
people to plead guilty in the aftermath of the Ivan Boesky insider
trading scandal that rocked Wall Street nearly three years ago.
   Freeman admitted that he used inside information when he ordered
the sale of Beatrice Companies Inc. stock in January 1986.
   ``I knew it was wrong at the time, sir,'' Freeman told U.S.
District Judge Pierre Leval.
   He could be sentenced to up to five years in prison, $1.86
million in fines and additional restitution. Leval scheduled
sentencing for Nov. 16.
   The 47-year-old securities professional read a seven-page
statement that detailed the events on which his guilty plea was
based.
   He said he received confirmation of a rumor from Martin Siegel,
then a vice president at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., about a problem with
the planned leveraged buyout of Beatrice by the investment firm of
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   ``When Martin Siegel confirmed the rumor I did not believe that
he was authorized by KKR to do so, and I knew I was not entitled to
trade on that information,'' Freeman said.
   After the conversation on Jan. 8, 1986, he said he ordered the
sale of certain Beatrice securities in a company account, in a
customer's account and in his own personal account.
   The government alleges that the sales resulted in the avoidance
of $930,000 in trading losses.
   Siegel, who later worked for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., was
implicated in the Wall Street insider trading scandal by Boesky, now
serving a three-year prison term. Siegel pleaded guilty in February
1987 to securities fraud charges and agreed to cooperate with the
government.
   He implicated Freeman, who was taken into custody at his office
in front of shocked co-workers.
   U.S. Attorney Benito Romano announced Freeman's plea agreement
last month.
   Freeman resigned from Goldman Sachs before his plea agreement was
announced. He said in a letter to his employer that he decided to
plead guilty to end what he called the nightmare that the 2{-year
investigation had caused him and his family.
   His plea agreement prohibits Romano's office from bringing any
additional criminal charges against Freeman but does not preclude
the Securities and Exchange Commission from seeking civil penalties.
   At the court proceeding, Leval asked Assistant U.S. Attorney John
McEnany how much restitution Freeman faces.
   McEnany said the exact figure had not been calculated, but with
prompting from the judge, said it could go as high as $50 million.
   Freeman's attorney, Robert B. Fiske Jr., said McEnany's
estimation was ``off the wall.'' Fiske said Freeman may only have to
pay back $466,000, which is the amount of losses he personally
avoided in the transactions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
