<FIRST>r f PM-Arby's-Posner     09-06 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arby's-Posner,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arby's President Fired After Break With Posner Over Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Arby's Inc. franchisees intends to
pursue a $200 million buyout of Miami financier Victor Posner
despite the dismissal of Leonard H. Roberts as the fast-food chain's
president and chief executive officer.
   ``The offer still stands,'' said Dezanne Phillips, spokeswoman
for the group of eight franchisees known as R.B. Partners Ltd.
``This, from R.B. Partners' point of view, kind of fuels the fire,''
she said.
   Roberts was fired a few hours after releasing a sharply worded
letter Tuesday announcing his resignation as vice chairman of the
board and a director of Posner's DWG Corp. That company owns 60
percent of Chesapeake Financial Corp., of which Arby's is a wholly
owned subsidiary.
   The letter was highly critical of Posner and of his decision not
to discuss the proposed buyout with R.B. Partners.
   ```We are not in a position to comment in detail on Mr. Roberts'
letter because of pending litigation, but it is our opinion that
statements in the letter are untrue in all material respects,'' said
DWG Senior Vice President Renee Mottram.
   She said Roberts was fired by Arby's board ``by reason of his
recent actions.'' No successor was immediately named, but Ms.
Mottram said one would be announced soon.
   Roberts, in an interview Tuesday before the dismissal was
announced, had said he intended to stay on as president and chief
executive officer of Atlanta-based Arby's, which has about 2,100
outlets nationwide.
   ``I'm trying to protect Arby's,'' he said. ``I don't think Arby's
has any future under Victor Posner.''
   Roberts said later he was not surprised by the firing.
   ``I knew I had to take certain risks to stand up to a gentleman
like Posner...,'' he said. ``I feel good about my separation from
Posner, but I feel concerned about Arby's. ... Arby's needs to be
sold from Victor Posner.''
   Roberts was named CEO of Arby's in July 1985 after 11 years at
Ralston Purina Co. Before that, he headed product development
programs at Armour &amp; Co. and the Central Soya Co.
   Last week, Posner rejected the R.B. Partners offer of $200
million in cash for the Arby's chain, saying DWG has ``no interest
in pursuing such a sale.''
   Roberts said Posner's refusal even to talk with R.B. Partners
went against the wishes of some other DWG board members, including
himself. Roberts, in his letter, accused Posner of trying to bully
the board into seeing things his way.
   R.B. Partners, whose members operate more than 500 of Arby's
outlets, last week expressed concern over Posner's existing legal
and financial problems.
   Posner pleaded no contest in 1987 to federal income tax evasion
and was sentenced to five years probation, with the condition that
he repay his back taxes, penalties and interest and create a $3
million homeless fund.
   Howard Hansen, a restaurant industry analyst at Kidder Peabody in
New York, said Tuesday that Roberts had been a ``catalyst'' for
Arby's recent success, which included an increase of 16 percent in
sales and an 11 percent growth in number of new units in fiscal 1989.
   ``They've been successful with their marketing _ the hamburger
alternative and the chicken club sandwich that's been very
successful,'' Hansen said.
   In 1988 Arby's operating profit was $20.7 million on $153.8
million in revenue, he said. Since 1985 _ the year Roberts arrived _
900 new restaurants have been built and sales of increased 50
percent.
   In a letter dated Monday to Arby's franchisees, four of Arby's
top executives, including Roberts, described a meeting Saturday in
Miami with Posner in which a plan was announced to replace the
existing management team.
   DWG's Ms. Mottram said the decision Tuesday affected only Roberts.
   Joe Smaltz, chairman of the 500-member Arby's Franchise
Association, said he was ``shocked and outraged'' at the decision to
fire Roberts, crediting him with turning the company into a highly
profitable one.
</TEXT>
