<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     09-06 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0316</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined broadly today amid
uncertainty over the outlook for Federal Reserve policy and interest
rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 22.61 to 2,722.07 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 306 up, 676
down and 504 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 31.68 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said a belief was spreading among investors that the
Federal Reserve was unlikely to relax its credit policy further any
time soon, given a stronger-than-expected economy.
   ``At a minimum, the Fed is not going to provide the fuel to drive
the market further,'' said Hugh Johnson at First Albany Corp. in
Albany, N.Y.
   Johnson also said portfolio managers at investing institutions
seemed to be in a wary mood.
   ``Institutional money managers have had an exceptionally good
year, and they're all trying to figure out how to protect their
gains. Most of them don't have many alternatives other than to sell
stocks,'' he observed.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down [ at
49~; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down \ at 39|; Eastman Kodak,
down \ at 47}, and Procter &amp; Gamble, down } at 127.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 1.34 to 194.50. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 1.00 at 383.53.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 7.41 to 2,744.68.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 826 down, 613 down and 523 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 145.18 million shares, against 133.30
million in the previous session.
