<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1037EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Shrimpers-Turtles 1stLd-Writethru f0013 09-06 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shrimpers-Turtles, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0013,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shrimpers Say Regulation Could Endanger Their Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 7, In July, to CORRECT mammals to sea animals.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf Coast shrimpers say a new federal
regulation requiring them to use a device to protect endangered sea
turtles may endanger their business.
   ``What I fear is that the Louisiana shrimper will become extinct
before the Kemp's ridley sea turtle,'' Rep. Jimmy Hayes, D-La., said
Tuesday in response to the Commerce Department regulation.
   By Friday, shrimpers must install a ``turtle excluder device,''
or TED, in their nets to allow turtles to swim free. Failure to do
so could result in a maximum $20,000 fine.
   Environmentalists say the action will save thousands of sea
turtles captured in the nets from drowning, but they contend it
should have come months ago to protect such endangered species as
Kemp's ridley, leatherback and hawksbill and threatened species such
as the loggerhead and green sea turtles.
   Shrimpers complain that while the requirement will save the
turtles, it also will significantly reduce their catch of shrimp _
perhaps as much as one-third _ and may force some to stop fishing.
   ``It's going to drive a lot of people out of business,'' said
Jimmy Russell, president of a shrimpers association along the Texas
coast near Brownsville and Port Isabel. ``I wouldn't be surprised if
they have a lot of people tell them they're not going to do it.''
   In July, when the government first tried to force shrimpers to
install the TEDs _ oval-like metal grates that divert large sea
animals such as turtles out of the net _ shrimpers in Texas and
Louisiana blockaded waterways and threatened bodily harm to anyone
who tried to force them to use the devices.
   ``We're not going to have any more blockades,'' Tee-John
Mialjevich, president of the Concerned Shrimpers Association, said
Tuesday night. He said the group will go to court in an attempt to
reverse the regulation.
   Some shrimpers say TEDs will cut a boat's daily catch by as much
as one-third. However, a Commerce spokesman said that side-by-side
tests have shown losses to be only 2 percent to 5 percent, and
environmentalists argue that if the nets are operated properly
losses should be no greater than 2 percent.
   Undersecretary of Commerce John A. Knauss said ``the only way to
ensure protection'' of the vanishing species of turtles is by using
the trap-door devices.
   ``There is no other choice,'' he said, adding that attempts to
protect the turtles by limiting the length of time that shrimpers'
nets are in the water didn't work.
   The Commerce decision came under a court directive requiring a
solution to be found by Sept. 8. Five environmental groups had filed
lawsuits arguing that government action was required under the
Endangered Species Act.
   The requirement for the TEDs was to have gone into effect in May,
but Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher suspended enforcement of the
regulation after complaints from the shrimpers and their
congressional representatives.
   Environmentalists said Tuesday that they regretted the delay.
   ``Basically we're pleased, but we're sorry it took so long and we
had to jump through so many legal hoops,'' said Charles Miller of
the National Wildlife Federation. ``At this point the turtles are
going to have a fighting chance.''
   Environmentalists warn that several of the sea turtle species _
especially the Kemp's ridley _ may be doomed to extinction if they
are not protected from shrimpers nets.
   The number of female Kemp's ridley sea turtles nesting each year
has declined from some 42,000 in the 1940s to no more than 700,
according to James Ross, an expert on sea turtles.
   Ross said that from 600 to 1,600 Kemp's ridley turtles are killed
each year, often after young turtles get in the way of the shrimping
nets. The decline of the species is estimated at about 3 percent a
year, he said.
   Mialjevich, of the Louisiana-based shrimpers' association,
doesn't deny the number of those turtles has fallen dramatically.
   ``But we did not bring the turtle population from 40,000 to 600.
So how can we be the solution to saving them?'' he asked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
