<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-TaxEvasion     09-06 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Tax Evasion,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>All But a Few People Investigated Found Evading Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All but a few, or 98.5 percent of 3,628 inheritors
of assets, investigated by tax officials in the Tokyo area this year
were found to be evading inheritance taxes, the Tokyo Regional Tax
Administration Bureau said Wednesday.
   The bureau said it uncovered an all-time high of 150 billion yen,
or about $1.02 billion, worth of unreported assets subject to
inheritance taxes.
   Accordingly, the taxes on those assets, combined with punitive
taxes, amounted to 53.4 billion yen, it said.
   The bureau said 18,600 of 132,000 people who died in Tokyo and
the three adjacent cities of Chiba, Kanagawa and Yamanashi in 1988
left behind assets subject to taxation.
   Of the total, 3,628 cases were considered questionable, and the
bureau conducted follow-up checks.
   About 70 percent of the unreported assets were in the form of
stocks, golf club memberships, cash and savings. Golf club
memberships are tradeable assets similar to stocks in Japan.
   The bureau said one company executive topped the list for evading
taxes totaling 118 million yen, or about $805,500.
</TEXT>
