<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1111EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet11am     09-06 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0262</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lapsed into a broad decline
today amid uncertainty over the outlook for Federal Reserve policy
and interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 27.92 to 2,716.76 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 276 up, 1,014 down
and 468 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 63.72 million shares at
midmorning.
   Analysts said a belief was spreading among investors that the
Federal Reserve was unlikely to relax its credit policy further any
time soon, given a stronger-than-expected economy.
   ``At a minimum, the Fed is not going to provide the fuel to drive
the market further,'' said Hugh Johnson at First Albany Corp. in
Albany, N.Y.
   Johnson also said portfolio managers at investing institutions
seemed to be in a wary mood.
   ``Institutional money managers have had an exceptionally good
year, and they're all trying to figure out how to protect their
gains. Most of them don't have many alternatives other than to sell
stocks,'' he observed.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down [ at
49~; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down | at 39\; Merck, down 1{
at 71}, and Union Carbide, down | at 29}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 1.72 to 194.12. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 1.58 at 382.95.
