<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Little Changed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting a lack of significant news on the supply-and-demand front.
   Midwestern weather forecasts, full of rain and mild temperatures,
remained bearish for corn and soybean prices. But selling was
limited this morning by the Agriculture Department's weekly
crop-progress report. The report showed only a slight improvement
last week in the corn and soybean crops, most of which remain in
fair to good shape.
   The wheat market gained slightly in response to Tuesday's USDA
announcement it had targeted the Philippines for sales of 600,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   ``That's a pretty good-sized offer to that country,'' said Jerry
Gidel, research director in Chicago for LIT America Inc., a
British-owned futures brokerage.
   The USDA's report of higher-than-expected exports of U.S. grains
last week also helped firm futures prices this morning.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.98\ a bushel; corn was
} cent lower to \ cent higher with September at $2.31} a bushel;
oats were unchanged to { cent lower with September at $1.34\ a
bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 1} cents higher with
September at $5.83 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were narrowly mixed while pork futures were mostly
lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent lower to .08 cent higher with October
at 72.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .17 cent
higher with October at 81.25 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent
to .40 cent lower with October at 39.12 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .25 cent lower with February at 43.37
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Tuesday.
