<SECOND>BC-Westinghouse-Nuclear,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Gets Nuclear Design Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Energy has awarded
Westinghouse Electric Corp. a $50 million contract to continue
designing an advanced nuclear reactor plant.
   Westinghouse will match the DOE funds with $50 million of its own
money combined with grants from the Electric Power Research
Institute, a Westinghouse spokeswoman said late Tuesday, confirming
an announcement U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
   The company started work on the design in 1984. Westinghouse
expects to achieve design certification by 1994 and expects the
advanced reactor to be operating by the end of the century, the
spokeswoman said.
   Partners in the design include Avondale Shipyards; Bechtel, Burns
& Roe; Morrison Knudson; and Chicago Bridge and Iron.
