<FIRST>r f PM-US-China 2ndLd-Writethru f0041 09-06 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0041,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration to Hold Meetings with Chinese Trade Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to CORRECT to ``Tariffs and Trade;'' Inserts grafs
3-6, Presidential press secretary, with White House comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite its ban on high-level contacts with
Chinese authorities, the Bush administration plans ``working level
discussions'' this month with Chinese officials on that nation's bid
to join an international trade body, a U.S. official said today.
   No firm date has been set for the meeting, however, and an
official at the office of the U.S. trade representative described
the planned session as a regular bilateral consultation on Chinese
efforts to accede to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or
GATT.
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said that, despite
the upcoming meeting, the administration remains opposed to China's
entry to GATT.
   ``They have to undertake significant economic reforms to be
eligible for GATT membership,'' Fitzwater said.
   He also defended the meeting and denied it was a violation of
President Bush's ban on high-level U.S.-Chinese contacts in the
aftermath of the Tianamen Square massacre.
   ``These are low-level, continuing discussions. They are not
negotiations,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``This can by no stretch of the imagination be considered a
high-level meeting,'' said Cecilia Kline, director for GATT affairs
in the trade office. ``The appointment hasn't been set up yet,'' she
said, but when it is, it would be ``a meeting in the normal course
of diplomatic activity.''
   Bush banned high-level contacts June 3 after the Chinese
crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators. Among the canceled
meetings were a visit to China by Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher.
   A multilateral meeting scheduled for Geneva in July on China's
effort to take part in the GATT was also postponed.
   State Department officials said today they want to continue
``working level discussions'' with the Chinese on GATT.
   That decision has come under fire from a conservative Washington
group, the Center for Security Policy, which opposes closer ties
with China's communist government. The center's director, Frank J.
Gaffney, released what Kline called a ``purloined cable'' describing
U.S. efforts to schedule a bilateral GATT meeting.
   She said the U.S. government had told the Chinese it was willing
to meet with their GATT negotiators as hey headed to Europe for
discussions with other participants in the 96-nation accord.
   ``The president's statement on high-level contact I do not
believe covered multilateral institutions,'' she said. ``We attend
U.N. meetings where the Chinese are present.''
   U.S. diplomats in Beijing invited Wang Shichun of China's
Ministry of Foreign Economic Relations and Trade to a meeting in
Washington on Sept. 11-12, according to the cable.
   ``Wang expressed his surprise that Washington had agreed to the
talks. He said their embassy in Washington informed Beijing that
Washington was unlikely to meet now,'' said the cable, signed by
U.S. Ambassador James Lilley.
   Wang said members of his delegation had not applied for visas and
plane tickets, and suggested a Sept. 18 meeting date instead, the
cable said.
   Gaffney, a former deputy assistant defense secretary, called the
U.S. invitation to Wang ``a major new initiative that rewards the
Chinese with something that they have sought for a long time.''
   ``Letting them into GATT ... fundamentally undercuts the forces
that are pressing for reforms in the People's Republic of China. And
it signals the Soviets and others who are facing social pressures
that there is no punishment for a Chinese-style crackdown,'' Gaffney
said.
   He contends that Secretary of State James A. Baker III violated
the ban July 31 by meeting with Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
at the beginning of the Cambodian peace talks in Paris.
   State Department sources said no date had been set for the
meeting on GATT and described Wang as ``deputy director of an
office, not a high-ranking individual, and therefore not covered in
the ban.''
   ``We would not be violating a ban that the president has
instituted,'' said one department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The president's ban, said the official, applied to ``politicial
level visits that would have a symbolic nature. This would be a
working level, technical visit.''
   A second department official, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the United States ``has a long-term interest in
getting China to abide by the rules of market countries'' set forth
in GATT and related international negotiations.
   ``The objective is to try to encourage China to continue along
its path of economic reform, to have a economic system that would be
consistent with market economies, to abide by the same rules,'' said
the official.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
