<HEAD>With PM-Catastrophic Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a state-by-state list of how a key
congressional proposal to revise financing of the Medicare
catastrophic care program would affect elderly people, according to
a report released by Families United for Senior Action.
   The list includes each state's total number of elderly tax filing
units _ single individuals age 65 and older and married couples
where one or both spouses are 65 or older.
   The total is followed by the percentages of elderly tax filing
units that would be winners and losers under revisions approved by
the House Ways and Means Committee, reflecting those who would pay
more or less under the proposal.
   The states' winners and losers figures do not add up to 100
percent because some people would not be affected by the proposed
change.
