<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CrazyEddie     09-06 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crazy Eddie,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crazy Eddie Founder Charged with Falsifying Info, Profiting Illegally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eddie Antar, the reclusive founder and former
chairman of the Crazy Eddie electronics chain, was charged today in
what authorities called a ``massive financial fraud'' to overstate
the company's income.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission, in a civil complaint
lodged here, accused Antar and six former top executives with a
broad scheme to inflate inventory and cover up losses. Federal
prosecutors also are conducting an investigation.
   During the time of the allegations, Antar sold his holdings in
the company for $60 million, the agency said. The SEC seeks
injunctions, return of any illegal profits from stock sales and
penalties.
   The Edison, N.J.-based Crazy Eddie Inc., known for its manic
commercials proclaiming ``Our prices are insane,'' has foundered in
recent years after once boasting 43 stores in New York, New Jersey
and Pennsylvania.
   A dissident group of shareholders bought out the company in late
1987, but Crazy Eddie filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code last June.
   The SEC said that Antar in 1985 and 1986 ordered employees to
falsify financial records to overstate the company's financial
health. For the two years, pre-tax income was overstated by $8.7
million, the agency said.
   In 1987, Antar was still behind the scheme but it was directed by
cousin Sam E. Antar, chief financial officer, who was one of three
men in the office of president, created after Antar withdrew from
the firm, according to the SEC.
   Instead of a substantial loss that year, the company reported
pre-tax income of $20.6 million, said the SEC.
   SEC attorney Richard Simpson said the company used a variety of
methods to inflate inventory, from adding zeros on product lists to
inflating prices on the books to fabricating product returns to
manufacturers.
   Justin Feldman, a lawyer for Eddie Antar in a shareholder lawsuit
against the former Crazy Eddie executive, said he had not seen the
SEC's papers and could not comment. Antar and other defendants have
denied artificially inflating the company's worth in that case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
