<FIRST>r f BC-AutoIncentives     09-06 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Incentives,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chevy Puts Incentives on '90 Cars, Trucks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Only version planned.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevrolet announced rebates Wednesday on two of
its 1990 cars, two weeks after formally introducing the line for
next year.
   The General Motors Corp. division became the first of the Big
Three automakers to announce incentives on any 1990 model. Ford
Motor Co. doesn't show off its 1990 offerings until next week and
Chrysler Corp.'s introduction is a week later.
   Chevrolet put a $750 cash rebate on all models of its 1990 Lumina
sedan, a car introduced earlier in the year to replace the Chevrolet
Celebrity, and an $800 rebate to buyers of the Geo Prizm or
Chevrolet Nova. Other rebates on remaining 1989 and 1988 cars and
light trucks range from $400 to $1,250.
   Interest rates through General Motors Acceptance Corp., a GM
subsidiary, range from 2.9 percent for two-year loans to 10.9
percent for five-year contracts on a variety of vehicles.
