<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-USTrade     09-06 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Can't Expect Fast Results From Trade Talks, Economist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top government economist said Wednesday it is
unrealistic for the United States to expect current talks on
structural trade barriers to produce quick changes in its $52
billion trade imbalance with Japan.
   ``If the United States expects a specific change in the trade
imbalance by April of next year, then the talks will be totally
counterproductive and our efforts will only backfire,'' said Masaru
Yoshitomi, director general of the research division of the Economic
Planning Agency.
   U.S. trade officials have said they expect ``tangible changes''
from the talks, which are expected to take place over a year. The
first round ended here Tuesday and the next will be in Washington on
Nov. 6-7.
   Yoshitomi said the trade imbalance is due to general economic
factors rather than Japanese impediments to imports from the United
States.
   ``It should be rectified by broad economic and exchange rate
policies, not trade policy,'' he said.
   ``Today's economic problems transcend the simple question of
trade friction. It is also necessary to establish a co-leadership
between Japan and the United States,'' Yoshitomi said in a briefing
to reporters.
   If Japan overcomes a current ``Japan phobia'' among other nations
based on its economic and technological prowess, Japan and the
United States could establish a ``co-leadership for the world'' for
better world trade policies, overseas development aid programs and
an improved international monetary system, he said.
   In volume terms, Japan's exports have changed little since 1985
while its imports of manufactured goods have grown 106 percent,
government statistics show.
   However, in value terms the gains failed to register because the
yen is stronger now in dollar terms, Yoshitomi said.
   During the two days of talks, dubbed the Structural Impediments
Initiative, the two countries agreed to develop their own plans to
overcome structural barriers to trade.
   The talks centered on Japan's intricate distribution system,
exclusive corporate relationships, and land use policy, as well as
the savings and investment balance, government regulations and
corporate behavior in the United States.
   Among other things, Japan was asked to relax government
regulations on distribution, modify its land and construction
policies and improve foreign access to domestic distribution
channels.
   The United States was urged to cut consumption, slash its budget
deficit, enhance its productive capacity and review government
regulations detrimental to industrial competitiveness.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party, which faces unprecedented
low public approval ratings at home, may find it difficult to
institute such fundamental economic changes.
   The party ``appears far more reluctant now than ever before about
going ahead with market liberalization at the risk of losing further
votes,'' the Japan Times newspaper said in an analysis Wednesday.
   An election for the powerful lower house of Parliament is
expected within the next several months. Opposition parties, which
made impressive gains in July elections for the upper house of
parliament, oppose drastic market-opening measures.
   A top Foreign Ministry official said some of the changes the
United States is demanding, such as those relating to corporate
behavior, are beyond government control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0270 </DOCNO>
