<HEAD>London Shares End Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with closing prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell sharply Wednesday on the London
Stock Exchange in what analysts described as some profit-taking
following a recent runup in prices that had lifted one key market
index to its highest level since the October 1987 stock market crash.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index, which closed
at post-crash highs for two successive days Monday and Tuesday, fell
35.2 points, or 1.4 percent, to close at 2,390.8.
   Volume rose to 540.1 million shares from 465.1 million shares on
Tuesday.
   The FT-30 index closed 29.9 points lower at 1,978.7. The
500-share index was 1,337.55, down 18.13.
   Fears that British interest rates are headed higher, unappealing
profit reports by a few British construction concerns and rumors of
new rights issues all helped push the market lower throughout the
day, dealers said.
</TEXT>
