<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1428EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Ford-Saab Bjt   09-06 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford-Saab, Bjt,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Eyeing Saab-Scania Trucks, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co., a relatively small player in the
world of big trucks, is negotiating with Saab-Scania AB of Stockholm
with an eye on the Swedish company's truck business, experts say.
   Because it has been making and selling cars in Europe for more
than 60 years, Ford wouldn't need Saab's car distribution network.
Ford, in fact, sells more cars in Sweden than does Saab.
   And while Ford doesn't offer a car like the top-of-the line Saab
9000, it has the technology and engineering skill to make one, the
analysts added in interviews Tuesday.
   What Ford doesn't have is a medium- and heavy-duty truck
operation in Europe, like the Scania division of the Swedish company.
   Ford and Saab earlier this week confirmed reports that the two
companies had been holding negotiations about a business
arrangement. No one would elaborate or comment further.
   ``The jewel at Saab is the truck division,'' auto analyst Ron
Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. of San Francisco said earlier
this week. ``I'm not sure why Ford would bother with the car
division.''
   Saab-Scania's annual report from last year showed that its truck
division's pre-tax earnings were more than 300 times that of its car
division. For the last five years, the company's trucks have shown
profit increases while the Saab's cars have been earnings losers
from 1986-88.
   Much of the decline in car earnings came when the U.S. dollar
weakened, making imported items more expensive.
   ``The car is somewhat eccentric, I have one myself,'' Glantz
said. ``I can see why Saab would want to sell (the car division). I
can't see why Ford would want to buy.''
   ``I think it's absolutely trucks,'' said analyst Joseph Phillippi
of Shearson Lehman Hutton of New York City. ``Scania is hardly even
visible in the United States.''
   Saab-Scania of America Inc. supplies vehicles to Saab dealers in
the United States. It operated a bus manufacturing plant in Orange,
Conn., from 1984 to late 1988.
   ``Saab is basically a heavy truck maker that also makes airplanes
and cars,'' Glantz said.
   Ford Motor Co. AB was founded in Stockholm, Sweden, in 1924 to
market Ford products in the Scandinavia. The company was involved in
manufacturing in Sweden for about 10 years, mostly in the 1950s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0273 </DOCNO>
