<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1444EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Campbell     09-06 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Campbell,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 4th-Qtr Loss Due to Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. said Wednesday it lost $195
million in the fourth quarter of its fiscal year, citing a worldwide
restructuring.
   The loss for the three-month period ended July 31 contrasted with
a profit of $72 million, or 56 cents a share, in the comparable
period a year ago.
   Sales in the fourth quarter rose 14 percent to $1.3 billion from
$1.15 billion a year earlier.
   For the full fiscal year, the Camden-based company earned $13
million, or 10 cents a share, down dramatically from $274 million,
or $2.12 a share, a year ago. The restructuring, announced Aug. 24,
produced a one-time charge of $2.01 per share against earnings for
the 1989 fiscal year.
   Sales for the year totaled $5.7 billion, up 16.5 percent from
$4.9 billion in the previous year.
   Besides soups, Campbell makes and markets a variety of foods
under the Franco-American, Vlasic, V-8 and Pepperidge Farm labels,
among many others.
   ``We sacrificed current fiscal year earnings to improve
Campbell's long-term profitability,'' said R. Gordon McGovern,
Campbell president. ``We are committed to being a world-class
manufacturer and to marketing products that are number one or two in
their categories.''
   The reorganization, which cost 2,800 jobs and closed down
manufacturing plants in New Jersey, Maryland and Tennessee, is
expected to save the company almost $15 million during fiscal 1990
and about $150 million over the next four years, McGovern said.
   Campbell, which has about 100 processing plants around the world,
said losses at facilities in the United Kingdom and Italy also
affected the company's earnings for the year and the fourth quarter.
   Campbell U.S.A., the company's largest division, reported a 15
percent increase in operating earnings for the year and a 9 percent
increase in sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
