<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1518EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CoorsBeer     09-06 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coors Beer,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coors To Unveil New Popular-Priced Beer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Coors Co. plans to unveil its new
Keystone beer this month with a high-priced advertising campaign
designed to attract male buyers by featuring their perceived
fantasies.
   The beer, the brewer's first entry into the ``popular-priced''
category, will be touted as ``bottled-beer taste in a can'' and will
sell for about $10.45 to $11.50 a case, a Coors spokeswoman said.
Coors is scheduled to begin selling the beer Monday.
   The beer will get its multi-million dollar advertising debut
during professional football and major league baseball games Sept.
16-17.
   Popular-priced beers _ such as Old Milwaukee, Meister Brau and
Milwaukee's Best _ are a bit cheaper than the premium beers, but
more expensive than economy beers.
   Although popular-priced beers have lost market share in recent
years, Coors decided to go ahead with Keystone because ``we didn't
think that we'd pick up that volume with a premium beer,'' said
Robert Klugman, company vice president of development.
   ``We promised our distributors we'd spend at a greater level''
than the $11 million to $12 million that the Stroh Brewery Co.
spends on Milwaukee brand, the nation's No. 1 popular-priced beer,
Klugman said.
   The ad campaign, designed by Foote, Cone &amp; Belding of Chicago,
features fantasies of men photographing woman candidates for a
sports magazine's swimsuit issue, pinch-hitting a home run in the
World Series and winning billions of dollars.
   Dan Fox, a company advertising executive, said the ads were
designed to be humorous. ``Lighten up, we're talking about a
six-pack of beer,'' he said. ``We shouldn't lose sight of the fact
that having a beer is supposed to be fun.''
   Klugman said Coors officials believe the advertisements ``will
not be found by most reasonable people to be offensive.''
</TEXT>
