<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1516EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-France-SuezTakeover Bjt   09-06 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Suez Takeover, Bjt,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>France's Biggest Takeover Clears New Regulatory Hurdle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Societe des Bourses Francaises said Wednesday it
has approved a sweetened $4.1 billion bid by Compagnie Financiere de
Suez for Compagnie Industrielle and its insurance unit, Compagnie
Financiere du Groupe Victoire in what would be France's biggest
takeover ever.
   The SBF, the Paris stock exchange's self-regulatory body, also
said in a statement it has extended the close of the tender offer to
Sept. 25 from the original date of Sept. 18.
   The approval and the extension of the 27.2 billion-franc offer
bring Suez, which won a huge struggle last year for control of
Societe Generale de Belgique, one step closer to final victory.
   The only regulatory hurdle remaining for the bid is the
government's Commission des Operations de Bourse, which already
approved the initial Suez bid. The new approval is expected before
the end of the week.
   French stock analysts said the apparent success of the Suez offer
was an indication of trends in the insurance industry, as greater
integration of European businesses approaches, and in the French
stock market, where large-scale takeovers such as those common in
the United States and Britain have been rare.
   ``We have proof now that what happens in other countries could
happen in Paris,'' said Georges Dieng of the Paris broker
Cholet-Dupont. ``It's the business mentality that is evolving.''
   The previous record takeover bid in France was a bid last year by
Schneider SA of about $930 million, or 6 billion francs, for control
of Telemecanique Electrique SA.
   Alain Tchibozo, an analyst for Tuffier, Ravier, Py et Associes in
Paris, said more takeovers can be expected, especially in the
insurance industry. Among the regulations falling in 1992, when the
European Economic Community countries will end trade and business
barriers, will be those that previously made it difficult for
insurance companies to sell policies outside their own countries.
   ``There's going to be a grand battle in insurance,'' Tchibozo
said. ``It's important to have a network, and you can't start an
insurance company now, it's too expensive. You have to buy one.''
   Suez, which traces its corporate roots to the building of the
Suez Canal in the 19th century, has developed a diversified array of
assets in banking, industry, insurance and real estate.
   The takeover was not expected to cause any changes of course for
Groupe Victoire, which vaulted to the rank of second-largest French
insurance company with its recent purchase of the West German
insurer Colonia Versicherung AG.
   ``Suez has always allowed its subsidiaries a great deal of
autonomy,'' Dieng said. ``I don't think it will change much for
Victoire. Suez could eventually give them the chance for further
alliances.''
   The sweetened Suez bid made Tuesday offers 14,800 francs for each
share plus 2,276 francs a share for Victoire's common stock and
1,138 francs a share for its nonvoting stock.
   The earlier bid, which was criticized by the target company's
management as inadequate, offered 13,000 francs a share for
Compagnie Industrielle, 2,000 francs a share for Victoire common
stock and 1,000 francs a share for its non-voting stock.
   Compagnie Industrielle President Jean-Marc Vernes said he would
tender his 25.5-percent share in the company under the revised Suez
offer, virtually guaranteeing the financial holding company's bid
will succeed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-06 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Rise On Scaled-Back Crop Estimates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices rose moderately
Wednesday amid expectations that the Agriculture Department will
reduce its harvest estimates for those commodities in a crop report
due out next week.
   Rumors circulated in the markets that Sparks Commodities Inc., a
private analytical firm based in Memphis, Tenn., was preparing to
release crop estimates lower than the USDA's August forecasts of
7.35 billion bushels of corn and 1.91 billion bushels of soybeans.
   The USDA crop report is scheduled for release Tuesday.
   In a weekly crop-progress report issued after the close of
trading Tuesday, the USDA indicated modest improvement in the corn
and soybean crops last week.
   But fears are building that a rainy month of September could slow
harvest activity, increasing the danger of frost damage to crops,
especially in eastern Illinois, Michigan and Indiana, where planting
was delayed by spring rains.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents lower to \ cent higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.97 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 4{ cents higher with September at $2.35{ a bushel; oats were
{ cent lower to 2 cents higher with September at $1.35} a bushel;
soybeans were { cent lower to 5} cents higher with September at
$5.87 a bushel.
