<FIRST>r f AM-FirstChicago-FCIA     09-06 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-First Chicago-FCIA,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Chicago Sells Investment Advisory Unit to Management</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   CHICAGO _ First Chicago Corp. said Wednesday it was selling it
First Chicago Investment Advisors subsidiary, an institutional
investment service, to a group led by the unit's management in a
deal worth more than $102 million.
   Under terms of the agreement, First Chicago will receive $70
million in cash, a $15 million subordinated note and a 10 percent
ownership stake in the new company, which will be renamed Brinson
Partners Inc.
   The agreement also calls for First Chicago to receive $17 million
in dividends, the bank holding company said in a news release.
   First Chicago said it expected to recognize a pre-tax gain of $60
million to $65 million at the time of the sale, which is likely to
be completed this month.
   Gary P. Brinson, president and chief executive of First Chicago
Investment Advisors, will head the new company, which has $12
billion under management and 120 employees in Chicago, London and
Tokyo.
   First Chicago President Richard L. Thomas said the sale was
consistent with First Chicago's strategic goals.
   Thomas said First Chicago, which has more than $48 billion in
assets, would continue to offer institutional investment services
through the American National Bank and Trust Co. of Chicago and its
suburban Chicago operations.
   Thomas said First Chicago's flagship bank, the First National
Bank of Chicago, would continue to use the new company as the
adviser for its pension plan and other employee benefit plans.
</TEXT>
