<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1634EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Germany-Daimler-MBB     09-06 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Germany-Daimler-MBB,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economics Minister Set To Approve Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's economics minister plans
to approve a proposed takeover by automaker Daimler-Benz of West
Germany's largest aerospace and defense contractor, government
sources said Wednesday.
   Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann is expected to announce his
decision to approve the takeover of Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm GmbH
at a news conference Friday, said the sources, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   The decision would culminate two years of haggling over one of
the biggest corporate mergers in West German history.
   Under terms of the merger approval, Daimler, already West
Germany's largest industrial concern, will shed MBB's interests in
battle tank manufacturer Krauss Maffei. Some of its board members
will relinquish supervisory board posts at other companies.
   The government also is expected to give up its interest in the
European Airbus Industrie project, now held through MBB, sooner than
planned.
   In addition, Deutsche Bank AG, West Germany's largest bank, will
slightly lower its 28 percent shareholding in Daimler-Benz in an
effort to ease fears over the bank's dominant role in industry, the
sources said.
   The West German Cartel Office earlier this year voted down the
merger, saying it would give Daimler a dominant position in defense,
aerospace and truck manufacturing sectors.
   The federal monopolies commission later voted to go along with
the proposal, but only if Daimler shed some of its defense holdings.
   The economics minister also hinted to Parliament on Wednesday
that he would approve the deal. He told the chamber that he would
hold ``to the basic orientation of the monopolies commision'' in
making the decision.
   Haussmann has the power to override the cartel office decision if
he determines that the merger is in the nation's economic interest.
   The West German government has backed the deal as a way of easing
its share of the subsidy burden in the loss-plagued Airbus program.
   Even by shedding some operations, the conglomerate still will be
a major global force in weapons sales and aviation technology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
