<FIRST>r f BC-FreddyKruegerDoll     09-06 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Freddy Krueger Doll,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toy Company Dreams Up New Doll From `Nightmare' Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone who has seen ``Nightmare on Elm Street'' horror movies
knows fiendish Freddy Krueger is no doll. But a toy company has
sweet dreams about sales of a new talking doll version of the
popular movie villain.
   Matchbox Toys (USA) Ltd. Wednesday announced creation of a
17-inch-tall, bendable doll based on the Freddy Krueger character
with a repertoire of six ghoulish sayings.
   Pull a string and the Freddy doll spouts phrases such as
``Pleasant dreams,'' ``Watch Out, Freddy's back'' or the character's
trademark diabolical laugh.
   The Matchbox doll, which will sell for about $25, will be
available in stores for Halloween sales. New Line Cinema Corp.,
creator of the ``Nightmare'' movies, sold the licensing rights for
the Freddy doll to Matchbox.
   Although attendance at the latest sequel, ``A Nightmare on Elm
Street 5: The Dream Child,'' started to fade in August after an
initial burst in the first few weeks of release, the ``Nightmare''
series has been a gold mine for film company New Line.
   Forbes Magazine has estimated that Freddy Krueger has generated
nearly $300 million in domestic and foreign box office receipts and
videocassette sales plus more than $3 million in licensing fees for
Freddy posters, T-shirts and other items.
   ``Freddy Krueger has translated nightmares into a dream
business,'' said Gene Morra, senior director of marketing at
Matchbox. ``We've known the talking doll business and we hope to do
well with Freddy because we know when Freddy talks, people listen,''
Morra said in a news release.
</TEXT>
