<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 2059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Party'sOver Adv10   09-06 1099</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Party's Over, Adv 10,1135</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 10 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ad Campaign Puts Miller Lite On Top, Brewer Says, But At What Cost?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miller Brewing Co. spent 16 months promoting a
Labor Day blast featuring The Who's last U.S. concert, a party that
boosted beer sales but did little to erase the industry's ``just say
yes'' stigma among critics.
   Now that the party's over, the No. 2 U.S. beer maker behind
Anheuser-Busch Cos. says its multimillion dollar ``Biggest Party in
History'' effort in Texas won more Miller customers in one of the
most lucrative beer markets.
   At the same time, anti-alcohol groups accused the brewer of
irresponsibly beckoning underage guzzlers with feel-good ads, a
charge Miller denies.
   Its Texas campaign reflected an image problem faced by many
brewers scrapping over a stagnant beer-drinking population, caused
partly by greater social awareness of alcohol's potential dangers.
Even young people say some beer ads aimed at them are offensive and
patronizing.
   Miller, especially, drew heavy criticism this spring for a
supplement mailed to college newspapers featuring bikini-clad coeds
clutching beer bottles and offering tips for men on ``sure fire ways
to scam babes.''
   The Milwaukee-based brewer, a subsidiary of consumer products
giant Philip Morris Cos., remains sensitive about the supplement,
which it admitted was in poor taste when some students objected. The
supplement was hastily withdrawn and Miller officials still bristle
when the subject is raised.
   The ``Biggest Party In History'' campaign conspicuously stayed
away from gorgeous babes and hunks extolling the brew, choosing
instead Texas-born actor Randy Quaid as pitchman.
   In addition, as part of the campaign Miller donated $1 million in
proceeds to the Texas Special Olympics, an athletic competition for
the handicapped. One commercial featured Quaid and several Special
Olympians.
   It still didn't sit well with activists against substance abuse.
   ``I've got a real question as to how (brewers) gear their
advertising toward young people,'' said Milo Kirk, a national vice
president of Mothers Against Drunk Driving and a founder of the
Dallas chapter. ``They gear their advertising around concerts and
sporting events. One brewer is using a dog, ... and studies will
show children react to animals.
   ``What is the subliminal message that they're trying to get
across here?'' she said.
   Anheuser-Busch, which uses the bull terrier Spuds McKenzie in
some of its beer ads, evidently was so stung by this kind of
criticism that it agreed to donate $250,000 to the Texas chapter of
Students Against Drunk Driving.
   Miller official Tom Cardella, who spearheaded the ``Biggest
Party'' campaign, said it was directed primarily at drinkers of
Miller Lite in Texas, where the brand had been losing ground.
   ``It is not targeted at below minimum drinking age,'' he said.
``The campaign is directed at legal age people.'' Miller also issued
colored wristbands during the party in an effort to block purchases
by minors.
   Jerry Steinman, who publishes an industry newsletter about the
beer business, defended brewer advertising as proper and ethical. He
said automobile makers are worse offenders.
   Beer companies ``don't go running around showing teen-agers in
ads,'' he said.
   ``Is it more responsible for an automobile manufacturer to
emphasize speed, and the zoom style of youth than it is for the beer
manufacturers to sponsor a concert that entertains?'' Steinman said.
   The money at stake is enormous: Steinman estimates the total
market at $45 billion a year, with Texas accounting for about 8.2
percent, second only to California.
   That means each percentage share in Texas is worth about $37
million in retail sales. Steinman's Beer Marketer's Insights Inc.
shows Miller as a brand has finished a close second to
Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc. since 1983.
   Miller officials say the advertising campaign has changed that.
   ``Based on the Texas state shipment reports (compiled by the
Wholesale Beer Distributors of Texas, Inc.), year to date through
July, Miller Lite brand was up 9 percent,'' Cardella said. ``In
comparison, in 1987 Miller Lite was down 6 to 7 percent.''
   ``Prior to the campaign, Miller Lite was in the number two
position and as of this July shipment report, Miller is the number
one brand in Texas'' by 2 percentage points, he said.
   Beginning in June 1988, Miller began the advertising campaign
built around the concept of ``the biggest party in history,'' with
free concerts in six Texas cities.
   The highlight was the Sunday night concert by The Who in Dallas,
the last stop on what may be their last tour. (The Who concert in
Dallas' Cotton Bowl, which also featured Stevie Ray Vaughn and the
Fabulous Thunderbirds, was not free, although groups except The Who
performed for free earlier in the day.)
   An estimated 500,000 people attended the events: 120,000 in
Houston Saturday and about 90,000 in Dallas Sunday.
   The campaign included radio, television and print ads featuring
Quaid searching Texas for a place large enough for the party,
finding enough food, or the right date. Each spot was signed off
with the slogan ``I'll get back to you later with more details.''
   Although Quaid is hardly a matinee idol, Cardella said, he was
selected because he is a native Texan and, ``based on his
appearance, he comes across in a very fun, enjoyable manner, kind of
homespun, very folksy.''
   Miller was pleased with Quaid's acceptance, said company
spokeswoman Beverly Jurkowski, who declined to say if the brewery
was considering further campaigns with Quaid.
   Jack Raskopf, a professor at Texas Christian University in Fort
Worth who has studied advertising of controversial materials, gave
Miller high marks for the campaign.
   ``I think it helped itself,'' said Raskopf. ``They did take a
gamble, they could have had a drunk go berserk, but it was a
remarkably docile crowd.''
   He said brewers are faced with advertising ``a product that is
probably of questionable value to society, but on the other hand it
is a perfectly legitimate product.''
   Brewers have been criticized for their advertising ``since Cain
opened the first brewery,'' Raskopf said. ``Miller lost no ground
there.''
   Cardella said Miller had planned from the outset to promote
responsible drinking, and near the end of the campaign aired a
commercial featuring The Who's Roger Daltrey and Pete Townsend
urging partygoers to ``think when you drink,'' with Townsend signing
off saying, ``Remember. Who cares.''
   Ms. Kirk, however, said MADD and others had hoped Miller would
make a more direct appeal. ``Why didn't they come right out and have
Randy Quaid come out and say if you're under 21, we don't want you.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 10</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 
</TEXT>
