<FIRST>r f BC-BankStationery-MBGroup     09-06 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bank Stationery-MB Group,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Bank Stationery Being Sold to Unit of Britain's MB Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Privately-held American Bank Stationery Co., one
of the country's largest check printers, will be sold to the U.S.
arm of Britain's MB Group PLC for $300 million cash, it was
announced Wednesday.
   The acquisition will strengthen MB America Inc.'s presence in the
growing check-printing business and enhance its ability to take
advantage of new opportunities that develop with the deregulation of
U.S. interstate banking, the company said.
   MB America has agreed to buy American Bank Stationery from an
investment group that includes company management and headed by the
New York investment banking firm Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen.
   Gibbons, Green, specialists in management buyouts, had led the
investment group in acquiring American Bank Stationery from American
Standard Inc. in 1986 for about $99.5 million.
   American Bank Stationery, based in Baltimore, is the third
largest U.S. check printer. It has about 2,300 employees working at
29 imprint plants and 2 base printing plants in 21 states.
   MB America said the acquisition will complement its existing
check-printing operations. It already owns Clarke Checks Inc., based
in San Antonio, Texas, which is the fourth biggest company in the
business.
   ``The check printing business in the United States continues to
grow,'' said Peter J. Hewett, chairman and president of MB America.
Hewett also will be chairman of Clarke American Holdings Inc., a new
holding company being formed to combine Clarke and American Bank
Stationery.
   ``The combination of Clarke Checks and ABS results in a network
of 56 printing plants and gives us nationwide coverage of virtually
all the principal markets in the United States,'' Hewett said. ``The
acquisition also positions MB to take full advantage of the new
market opportunities that will be available after the anticipated
deregulation of U.S. interstate banking in 1991.''
   American Stationery's sales totaled $80.3 million in the first
six months of 1989, up from $74.9 million in the corresponding 1988
period, MB America said.
   Sales for all of last year came to $148.6 million and profit
before interest and tax was $20.4 million while net assets at
year-end totaled $37.8 million, Gibbons, Green said in a separate
announcement.
   MB America is based in Westport, Conn. and its corporate parent
is based in Reading, England.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1711EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-06 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With AM-Fed-Currency Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower Wednesday against major
foreign currencies amid market concerns of higher interest rates
overseas.
   Gold prices rose. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery settled at $361.60 a troy ounce, up $2
from Tuesday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid
for gold of $360.70 an ounce, up $2.10.
   Currency traders attributed the dollar's retreat Wednesday
largely to profit-taking and speculation that West Germany and Japan
might hike their interest rates to thwart the dollar's recent
strength.
   The dollar also was depressed by reported continued intervention
by the Bank of Japan.
   But Earl I. Johnson, a trader for Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago,
said overall sentiment toward the dollar remained bullish. ``We're
just seeing a technical retrenchment,'' he said.
   Johnson predicted that West Germany and Japan would keep their
interest rates stable, paving the way for further increases in the
dollar later this week.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 146.65 yen, unchanged from Tuesday.
It traded at 146.15 yen in London, and fell to 146.10 yen in New
York, down from 146.75 yen Tuesday.
   The dollar was lower against the British pound Wednesday. Each
British pound cost $1.5552, more expensive than Tuesday's $1.5385.
Sterling fetched $1.5525 in New York, up from $1.5385.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Tuesday, included: 1.97525 West German marks, down from 1.9875;
1.7048 Swiss francs, down from 1.7150; 6.6550 French francs, down
from 6.7000; 1.18015 Canadian dollars, down from 1.18065; and
1,417.875 Italian lire, down from 1,424.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Tuesday's rates
included: 1.9735 West German marks, down from 1.9895; 1.7045 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7170; 6.6480 French francs, down from 6.7055;
2.2280 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2415; 1,417.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,425.50; and 1.1798 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1811.
   Gold bullion closed in London at $360.25 an ounce, up from
$358.25 late Tuesday. The late Zurich bid was $359.75 an ounce, up
from $358.30.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $359.75 a troy ounce, up
from $359.35.
   Silver prices gained ground. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $5.103 a troy ounce, up from $5.063
Tuesday. Silver rose in London to $5.12 an ounce from $5.07.
</TEXT>
