<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Prices Push Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices headed higher Wednesday amid
speculation about tight supplies.
   A lot of the buying took place in the gasoline futures pit on the
New York Mercantile Exchange. The contract for October delivery of
unleaded gasoline rose 1.35 cents to 55.11 cents a gallon and added
to Tuesday's gain of 0.44 cent. The November, December and January
contracts also posted gains.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
the October contract of No.2 heating oil moved 0.91 cent higher to
55.48 cents a gallon after Tuesday's gain of 0.60 cent. Contracts
for more distant months also rose.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $19.28 per 42-gallon barrel, up
23 cents from Tuesday and bringing the contract's two-day increase
to 43 cents. Other delivery months sported similar gains.
   Michael Hiley of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said the advance in
energy prices came in reaction to a convergence of factors that
encouraged buying.
   ``It was a market that was receptive to any bullish news,'' said
Hiley, citing reports of two refinery fires as examples.
   A fire at Shell Oil Co.'s Martinez, Calif. refinery and one at
Ashland Petroleum Co.'s refinery in St. Paul Park, Minn. raised
speculation in the market about a possible tightening in supplies
temporarily.
