<FIRST>r f AM-Buick     09-06 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Buick,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buick Introduces a Convertible Reatta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOVI, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buick on Wednesday introduced its long-delayed
Reatta convertible after solving engineering problems on the first
soft-top Buick since 1985.
   Buick General Manager Ed Mertz said the General Motors Corp.
division may make as many Reatta convertibles as hardtop versions of
the sporty two-seater introduced last year.
   Mertz declined to estimate sales for the 1990 versions of the
Reatta, which was introduced as a hardtop early last year, or any
other Buick line. But he predicted the full Buick division's share
of the U.S. car market would rise to about 6 percent from an
expected 5.7 percent at the end of this year.
   ``More and more people are understanding the cars we build,''
Mertz said at the formal introduction of the company's 1990 cars in
this Detroit suburb.
   Buick has sold 5,509 Reatta coupes, priced at $26,700, through
Aug. 31.
   Tracking Reatta sales is difficult since production at the Reatta
Craft Centre in Lansing was stopped or slowed several times for
retooling for convertible production and installation of a new paint
shop.
   Mertz said once Reatta convertible production gets into full
swing late this year or early next year, the company should make as
many soft tops as hardtops.
   The convertible is expected to be in dealer showrooms next spring
but prices won't be announced until later this year.
   Production of the coupe began in January 1988 at the Craft
Centre. A convertible was to be introduced later that year but
engineering problems with the top delayed introduction until this
fall.
   The convertible Reatta is the first soft-top Buick has offered
since the 1985 Riviera, which was converted by an outside company.
The last Buick-produced convertible was the 1975 LeSabre.
   Also for 1990, Buick will offer the Regal as a four-door sedan,
part of the GM-10 line of midsize cars. The cars originally were
introduced as two-door coupes, a move criticized by analysts who
thought the company was missing an important segment of the midsize
car market.
</TEXT>
