<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1950EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-UnisysDocuments     09-06 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unisys Documents,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Keep Names Sealed In Unisys Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Wednesday refused to release
identities of Unisys Corp. employees possibly involved with a
defense consultant who sold procurement secrets to the company.
   U.S. District Judge Diana Murphy said privacy interests of the
Unisys workers supersede the public's First Amendment right to
review court documents.
   Murphy has released a series of documents related to the June 14,
1988 search of Unisys property in Eagan, a suburb of Minneapolis, as
part of a nationwide investigation into defense procurement fraud,
but names of the Unisys employees in the set released Wednesday were
blackened out.
   That leaves undisclosed 39 words in all documents related to the
search. The undisclosed words all refer to identities of people
connected with the investigation.
   The judge decided to protect the identity of the Unisys employees
in the latest batch of documents even though federal prosecutors had
no objection to releasing their names. The Star Tribune and St. Paul
Pioneer Press Dispatch sued to gain the unconditional release of all
documents related to the search.
   A lawyer for the Unisys employees has maintained that disclosure
of the names would tarnish the reputations of his clients even
though they have not been charged with a crime.
   Tim McGuire, managing editor of the Star Tribune, said the
newspaper won't seek further disclosure of information in the
documents.
   ``We do not plan to pursue the case any further,'' McGuire said.
``We have gotten more information than any other circuit. We think
that that's been valuable and important.''
   McGuire said federal judges in districts around the country have
been inconsistent in ruling on media requests for the release of
documents in the case.
   The disparity signals a need for the newspaper industry and the
Justice Department to discuss disclosure issues to prevent ``this
kind of fiasco in the future,'' McGuire said.
   Mark Nadler, managing editor of the Pioneer Press Dispatch, said
the newspaper is reviewing Murphy's decision but doesn't have any
immediate plans to appeal.
   The release of the latest set of documents followed William J.
Sanda's guilty plea Friday to procuring information in 1987 for
Unisys and other defense contractors in exchange for large
consulting fees.
   Court documents show Sanda received confidential information on
the Navy's $100 million Advanced Tactical Air Command Central system
and passed it on to Unisys and other companies.
   Sanda, a former Unisys employee in Eagan, admitted passing on
confidential documents to a Unisys marketing representative who
agreed to write a series of purchase orders for Sanda for $25,000
each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
