<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     09-06 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Sink on Signs of Progress in Strike Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices tumbled Wednesday, the third straight day
of losses on New York's Commodity Exchange, on perceptions that
labor tensions are easing in countries where miner strikes have
disrupted copper production.
   On other markets, energy futures rose following an oil refinery
explosion in California; meat futures rallied on renewed hopes that
pork bellies will be shipped to Poland; and corn futures gained on
dimming crop prospects.
   Copper futures settled 2.55 cents to 3.90 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $1.2575 a pound, a two-week
low.
   Copper futures had traded above $1.36 a pound as recently as Aug.
25 on supply fears prompted by strikes in Peru and Canada and mine
shutdowns in Mexico and Papua New Guinea.
   Since then, the Peruvian strike has ended, a strike has begun at
a mine in Chile, and the Bouganville mine in Papua New Guinea
reopened only to be closed a day later by a resurgence of the
landowner-led violence that prompted the original shutdown in July.
   Overall, the market perceives less of a threat to copper supplies
than it did two weeks ago, analysts said.
   ``The worst seems to be over, at least for the short term, so the
market's undergoing a healthy correction,'' said William O'Neill,
research director with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   The easing of supply worries is based partly on settlement of the
Peruvian strike and signs that talks aimed at ending the 2-month-old
Highland Valley strike in British Columbia and the 6-day-old strike
at the Chilean Copper Co.'s El Salvador mine are making ``a kind of
grinding progress,'' O'Neill said.
   Further selling was prompted by Southern Peru Copper Co.'s
statement Wednesday that it would not have to cancel any shipments
as a result of the 16-day nationwide copper miners strike that ended
Sept. 31.
   Despite its pullback, the copper market is likely to remain
sensitive to supply fears, said Peter Cardillo, commodity trading
adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New York.
   ``On the next major report of production problems, the market
will begin to rally,'' he said. ``The only way I see copper prices
really coming in is if we have signs of a recession and I really
don't see that right now.''
   Precious metal futures advanced on the Comex, largely in response
to the weaker dollar.
   Gold settled $2 to $3 higher with October at $363.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 4 cents to 4.7 cents higher with September at
$5.103 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices climbed on the New York Mercantile Exchange
following reports of an explosion Tuesday that shut down a Shell Oil
Co. refinery near San Francisco.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 23 cents
higher with October at $19.28 a barrel; heating oil was .14 cent
lower to .91 cent higher with October at 55.48 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .30 cent to 1.35 cents higher with October at
55.11 cents a gallon.
   Pork belly futures led a rally in the livestock and meat complex
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange on word that the Polish
government had requested 50,000 metric tons each of pork bellies and
beef in food aid from the United States.
   Live cattle rose .03 cent to .27 cent with October at 72.37 cents
a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .35 cent higher with October
at 81.47 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .88 cent higher with
October at 39.62 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.20 cents
to 1.70 cents higher with February at 44.82 cents a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures prices rose moderately on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid expectations that the Agriculture Department
will reduce its harvest estimates for those commodities in a crop
report due out next week.
   Wheat futures settled 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher with
September at $3.96} a bushel; corn was } cent to 4{ cents higher
with September at $2.35{ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 1 cent
higher with September at $1.35 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 6{
cents higher with September at $5.87} a bushel.
</TEXT>
