<HEAD>Pharmaceuticals Company Chairman Announces Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McKesson Corp. Chairman Thomas W. Field Jr.
resigned after a dispute with the pharmaceuticals company's board
over his management style and plans, the company announced Wednesday.
   Former chairman and chief executive Neil E. Harlan was elected to
his old jobs on an interim basis, McKesson, a leading distributor of
pharmaceuticals and other medical products, said in a statement.
   Harlan stepped down as the company's chief executive officer in
July 1986 but served as chairman until retiring in July 1988.
   Field's resignation was accepted by the board of directors, the
company said. He resigned as McKesson's chairman, president, chief
executive officer, director and other posts with company
subsidiaries.
   Field joined McKesson in 1984 and was president and chief
operating officer until July 1986, when he was named president and
chief executive officer. Field was named chairman, president and
chief executive in July 1988.
   The company in July reported record first-quarter revenue but
said income from continuing operations was flat, while earnings rose
1 percent over the same period last year.
