<DOCNO> AP890906-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1845EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TugboatPageant Bjt   09-06 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tugboat Pageant, Bjt,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tugboat Beauty Pageant Features Stout Contestants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While Miss America contestants stroll down the runway in Atlantic
City next week, another string of beauties will chug into New York
Harbor for the first-ever Tugboat Beauty Contest, complete with Bert
Parks as emcee.
   The contestants in the Sept. 13 event will be strutting more
horsepower than cheesecake, but organizers believe beauty _ when it
comes to tugboats _ is definitely in the eye of the beholder.
   The event is being staged coincidentally with the Miss America
pageant to promote the often overlooked tug industry and the revival
of Jersey City, N.J., as a port of call.
   The vessels will be judged ``on how well they are dressed, their
trim, sparkle, maneuverability, charm and overall appearance,'' said
Lauri Masur, one of the organizers.
   Among the leading contenders are the Rebecca P., a 105-foot
knockout with 3,000 horsepower and a 32-foot beam, and the Sea Star,
which is equally broad at the beam, 109 feet long and 2,300
horsepower.
   Hubba, hubba.
   Unlike the Atlantic City affair, both boy tugs and girl tugs are
eligible for the title. About 10 tugs are expected to compete, all
members of the Towboat &amp; Harbor Carriers Association of New York and
New Jersey.
   Parks, a former Miss America host, will introduce the
contestants, which will sashay down a channel in Jersey City that
leads into New York Harbor.
   But Parks won't get the chance to croon a rendition of ``There
She Is,'' the Miss America theme. Instead, a band will play ``A
Pretty Girl'' and other similar ditties.
   Unlike the Miss America Pageant, where the winner receives a
$35,000 scholarship, ``Miss Tugboat'' will win $2,500 in cash to
spend on whatever his or her owners want, Ms. Masur said.
   In place of a crown and sash will be a more seaworthy symbol.
``She'll get a flag to run up her line proclaiming her the winner,''
Ms. Masur said.
   The Rebecca P., representing Poling Transportation of Staten
Island, N.Y., is a 9-year-old tug adorned in white, pale blue and
yellow. For her ``talent,'' she can ply both inland and coastal
waters, said Anthony Rondinone, Poling's general manager.
   ``As far as we're concerned, she's the winner,'' he said.
   Fourteen-year-old Sea Star's owner, Peter W. Sheehan of
Spentonbush-Red Star Co. in New York, takes exception to that
prediction.
   Dressed in white, green and yellow, Sea Star can do ship docking
and tow barges up to 85,000 barrels.
   ``She has two propellers, and she will make a beautiful
360-degree turn so you can see her full dress,'' he said.
   In Atlantic City this week, the 51 Miss America contestants are
being quizzed on controversial subjects such as abortion and flag
burning. The tugboat contestants won't be held to such standards.
   ``This is strictly a beauty pageant,'' said Ms. Masur with tongue
firmly in cheek.
   Judges include Jersey City Mayor Gerald McCann, Coast Guard Capt.
Robert North, Hudson County Executive Robert Janiszewski and U.S.
Rep. Frank J. Guarini, D-N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
