<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 1853EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FungicideWithdrawn     09-06 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fungicide Withdrawn,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>EBDC Chemicals Being Withdrawn for Fruits and Vegetables</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three manufacturers of a widely used class of
fungicides announced Wednesday they are halting sales for use on
dozens of fruits and vegetables because of government concerns that
the potential cancer risks are too high.
   The fungicides involved, the ethylene bisdithiocarbamate or EBDC
class, have been under a special review by the Environmental
Protection Agency since 1987 because a breakdown product has been
shown to cause cancer in test animals.
   In a joint announcement the three manufacturers _ the Du Pont
Co., Pennwalt Corp. and Rohm &amp; Haas Co. _ said they ending sales for
many fruits and vegetables ``to maintain public confidence'' in the
foods.
   The decision came as the EPA was preparing to order curbs on EBDC
uses because of recent tests that indicated unacceptable cancer
risks from residues in some foods.
   The manufacturers maintained that despite their action, the
chemical is safe for consumers if used properly.
   But, according to EPA documents, agency tests show that the
cancer risks posed by EBDC residues on some foods can be more than
23 times the one-in-one million level the agency uses to indicate
neglible risk. In the case of residues on tomatoes it can be 63
times the benchmark level.
   That contrasts to EPA's estimate of a lifetime cancer risk of 45
times the benchmark for Alar, the widely publicized chemical that
caused an uproar earlier this year becuase of its use on apples.
   The EPA estimates that the chances of a person getting cancer
during a lifetime from exposure to EBDC residues on all foods could
be as high as one in 10,000, a level that has triggered restrictions
on many chemicals in the past.
   That result assumes crop residues are at the maximum permitted
level. The companies are conducting marketbasket studies to
determine actual exposure to consumers since the chemical is known
to decay with time.
   EPA spokesman John Kasper said he could not immediately provide
specific test results, but added, ``We've got some risk estimates
that we're concerned about.''
   Kasper said the manufacturers' voluntary withdrawl would be
examined by the agency. ``It's entirely possible we could make (the
restrictions on EBDC's use) even more stringent to reduce the risks
even further,'' he said.
   One form of the chemical, mancozeb, is sold by all three
companies and another form, maneb, is sold by Pennwalt.
   ``The action is being taken to maintain public confidence in the
safety of fruits and vegetables,'' said the three manufacturers in a
joint statement. They said the chemical could continue to be used on
13 crops.
   Although the announcement named no products, an environmental
group, the Natural Resources Defense Council, said the 13 products
for which EBDC will continue to be used include potatoes, sugar
beets, sweet corn, tomatoes and wheat and almonds.
   The fungicide has been used on more than 70 crops. The major
crops for which use will be discontinued include apples, carrots,
celery, cucumbers, melons, pears, squash and pineapples, according
to the environmental group.
   The fungicide has been used for nearly 40 years and according to
some estimates from 12 to 18 million tons are used annually.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890906-0304 </DOCNO>
