<FIRST>u f AM-Midway-Ampco     09-06 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Midway-Ampco,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ampco-Pittsburgh Boosts Stake in Midway Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ampco-Pittsburgh Corp. said Wednesday it had
increased its stake in Midway Airlines Inc. to 9.6 percent of the
carrier's common stock and indicated it was still considering a
takeover attempt.
   Ampco-Pittsburgh, a manufacturer that previously acknowledged a
6.6 percent stake in Midway, revealed the additional stock
accumulation in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   In its original SEC filing Aug. 7, the Pittsburgh-based company
said it had bought Midway shares ``for investment and to acquire a
significant equity interest,'' adding that it ``may also consider
seeking to acquire control of Midway.''
   Ampco spokesman Marshall Berkman said the company's purpose in
acquiring the additional shares was the same as in its original
filing.
   Midway spokeswoman Sandra Allen said that to her knowledge,
officials of Midway and Ampco-Pittsburgh had not discussed Ampco's
interest in the Chicago-based airline, the nation's 16th largest.
   ``We're treating it as a routine business investment,'' she said.
   Midway Chairman David Hinson has said Midway is not interested in
being acquired.
   Ampco said its subsidiary Ampco-Pittsburgh Securities II Corp.
acquired 960,000 shares of Midway common stock as of Sept. 5 at an
average price of $16.77 a share. Midway closed at $20.62{ a share
Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange, up $1.62{.
   Midway announced last week it had strengthened its defenses
against a hostile takeover by loosening the trigger on its
shareholder rights plan, commonly called a ``poison pill.''
   The shareholder rights plan would take effect if an outsider
acquired 15 percent of Midway's stock. The plan would increase the
number of outstanding shares to make a buyout prohibitively
expensive.
   Midway, founded in 1979, is a fast-growing airline serving 51
U.S. cities from Los Angeles to Boston and from Chicago to Miami. It
operates from Midway Airport in Chicago.
   Ampco-Pittsburgh owns Buffalo Forge Co. and Union Electric Steel
Corp.
</TEXT>
