<FIRST>r f BC-GeorgiaGulf-NLIndustries     09-06 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Georgia Gulf-NL Industries,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Gulf Agrees to Meet With NL Industries Over Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Georgia Gulf Corp. said Wednesday
they will meet with NL Industries about a possible $55-a-share
merger or acquisition after NL Industries threatened a move to oust
Georgia Gulf's directors.
   NL Industries, whose biggest shareholder is Texas billionaire
Harold C. Simmons, sent a letter dated Wednesday to Georgia Gulf
officials warning that it planned to seek consent from other
shareholders to replace the chemical company's board of directors.
   In the company's response, Dennis Chorba, a Georgia Gulf vice
president and its general counsel, said he and President Jerry
Satrum will meet with Landis Martin of NL Industries on Sept. 13 in
Atlanta.
   Chorba also said Georgia Gulf will not alter its incorporation
papers or effect a transaction that would prevent shareholders from
considering an NL Industries offer.
   He wrote that would change ``if NL Industries, or any other
stockholder, were to take any action, such as filing preliminary
proxy materials ... holding discussions with other stockholders
regarding a consent solicitation or otherwise taking steps to
implement a removal of the directors of the company.''
   NL Industries owns 2.3 million shares of Georgia Gulf common
stock, about 9.9 percent of its outstanding shares.
   Earlier advances by NL Industries prompted a series of
anti-takeover measures by Georgia Gulf.
   NL Industries and NL Chemicals Inc., both controlled by Simmons,
first disclosed an ownership in Georgia Gulf in early July,
reporting the purchase of 8.3 percent of outstanding shares. In
mid-August, the Simmons companies announced they would look at
options, including a takeover.
