<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-89 2138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BraniffLease     09-06 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Braniff Lease,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Braniff Leases Boeing Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc. announced Wednesday it has
agreed to lease 20 new Boeing 737-300 jets for about $600 million
from Guiness Peat Aviation.
   The new aircraft will be delivered between June 1990 and June
1992.
   The lease agreement releases Braniff from a contract to purchase
12 new Fokker 100 aircraft from GPA Fokker Ltd., an affiliate of
Guiness Peat Aviation, an Irish aircraft leasing concern.
   ``We believe that the F-100 is an excellent, state-of-the-art
aircraft, but the larger, longer-range Boeing 737-300 better suits
our present route system and traffic demand,'' said William G.
McGee, chairman, president and chief executive of Braniff, which is
based in Orlando.
   Guiness Peat Aviation said it has reached preliminary agreements
with other carriers to lease the 12 F-100s.
   GPA New York Financial Services, a subsidiary of Guiness Peat
Aviation, will arrange $75 million in financing for Braniff under
the agreement, which must be approved by both companies' boards of
directors.
   The Boeing 737-300 typically seats 130 passengers, whereas the
F-100 only seats 101 passengers.
   Braniff plans to build its future aircraft fleet around the
737-300s and its previously-leased Airbus 320s. Braniff ordered 100
A-320s, which it began using Aug. 28.
   The airline said its revenue passenger miles increased 2.2
percent in August over the same month in 1988. A revenue passenger
mile is equal to one paying passenger flying one mile.
</TEXT>
